WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
[Unknown]: IVM.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.320
[Amit Varma]: Jurassic period, the supercontinent of Pangaea began to break up.

00:01:04.320 --> 00:01:09.000
[Amit Varma]: Pangaea itself began to move west, splitting up into multiple fragments and as a result

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:14.400
[Amit Varma]: creating new oceans out of the super ocean that surrounded it, Panthalosa.

00:01:14.400 --> 00:01:20.520
[Amit Varma]: The tectonic plate that contained what is today India, severed itself and sped northeast

00:01:20.520 --> 00:01:23.600
[Amit Varma]: across what would later become the Pacific and Indian oceans.

00:01:23.600 --> 00:01:27.080
[Amit Varma]: I say sped in a geological sense of course.

00:01:27.080 --> 00:01:33.080
[Amit Varma]: It took about 115 million years and about 65 million years ago, this plate containing

00:01:33.080 --> 00:01:38.380
[Amit Varma]: what we now call India, crashed into the Laurasian plate which contained Eurasia and what later

00:01:38.380 --> 00:01:40.080
[Amit Varma]: became North America.

00:01:40.080 --> 00:01:45.000
[Amit Varma]: Imagine in your mind's eye what happens in a time lapse spanning millennia as these two

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:50.280
[Amit Varma]: enormous landmasses collide together and the violence of earth, sand and water as their

00:01:50.280 --> 00:01:56.200
[Amit Varma]: edges rise up from the impact, high up towards the sky till the landmasses finally slow down,

00:01:56.200 --> 00:01:59.120
[Amit Varma]: still moving but a bit more still.

00:01:59.120 --> 00:02:04.000
[Amit Varma]: And these battered grotesque edges, the mountain ranges that rise up with the coming together

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:07.580
[Amit Varma]: of two ancient landmasses, how do we know them today?

00:02:07.580 --> 00:02:09.480
[Amit Varma]: We know them as the Himalayas.

00:02:09.480 --> 00:02:12.080
[Amit Varma]: They lie between India and China.

00:02:12.080 --> 00:02:14.960
[Amit Varma]: That's how old our business is.

