[Guest]: And yeah, thank you so much.

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:43.760
[Amit Varma]: That was a wonderful introduction.

00:04:43.760 --> 00:04:48.760
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I that image of that giant rock will not leave my head.

00:04:48.760 --> 00:04:52.600
[Amit Varma]: Before we get on to sort of China and India and so on, tell me a little bit more about

00:04:52.600 --> 00:04:58.040
[Amit Varma]: yourself like your route to becoming a foreign policy expert is quite interesting.

00:04:58.040 --> 00:05:01.640
[Guest]: Yeah, I've taken sort of a really strange route.

00:05:01.640 --> 00:05:04.000
[Guest]: I was a journalist for much of my career.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:07.280
[Guest]: Okay, so the first time I visited China was in 2001.

00:05:07.280 --> 00:05:10.320
[Guest]: But the first time I went there alone was in 2005.

00:05:10.320 --> 00:05:11.600
[Guest]: And it was really strange experience.

00:05:11.600 --> 00:05:13.800
[Guest]: I was put on a bus.

00:05:13.800 --> 00:05:17.040
[Guest]: I knew where I was supposed to go, but I didn't know where the bus was going.

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:18.040
[Guest]: I didn't know the language.

00:05:18.040 --> 00:05:19.520
[Guest]: I didn't know anything.

00:05:19.520 --> 00:05:23.360
[Guest]: And the bus drops me in the middle of the night at about half past three in this small

00:05:23.360 --> 00:05:27.120
[Guest]: tiny town and a tiny little bus stop.

00:05:27.120 --> 00:05:31.720
[Guest]: And at like about 3.30 a.m. in the morning, I have cab drivers coming and asking me where

00:05:31.720 --> 00:05:32.720
[Guest]: I want to go.

00:05:32.720 --> 00:05:34.880
[Guest]: Obviously, I didn't understand a word of what they were saying.

00:05:34.880 --> 00:05:38.960
[Guest]: And my first reaction of sitting in that bus stop for the next two hours waiting for somebody

00:05:38.960 --> 00:05:44.080
[Guest]: to come and pick me up was of absolute horror, wondering whether I'm going to become a fisherman

00:05:44.080 --> 00:05:46.040
[Guest]: lost in some village in China.

00:05:46.040 --> 00:05:47.880
[Guest]: But that was my introduction to the country.

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:50.840
[Guest]: Since then, the love affair has grown.

00:05:50.840 --> 00:05:51.840
[Guest]: I've gone back repeatedly.

00:05:51.840 --> 00:05:56.160
[Guest]: So as a journalist, I went back to China in about 2011.

00:05:56.160 --> 00:06:00.200
[Guest]: After having spent about six years of working in India, I was always interested in foreign

00:06:00.200 --> 00:06:01.200
[Guest]: policy.

00:06:01.200 --> 00:06:02.960
[Guest]: I studied international relations.

00:06:02.960 --> 00:06:05.040
[Guest]: I went to China, I did some freelance work.

00:06:05.040 --> 00:06:09.000
[Guest]: And then I worked with Chinese state media for a few years, which gave me an interesting

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:11.800
[Guest]: insight into how the country operates.

00:06:11.800 --> 00:06:12.800
[Guest]: What are the structures?

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:13.800
[Guest]: What are the processes?

00:06:13.800 --> 00:06:14.800
[Guest]: How do people think?

00:06:14.800 --> 00:06:18.560
[Guest]: I mean, there's a real divide between how people think in China about themselves and

00:06:18.560 --> 00:06:21.280
[Guest]: how the world outside views them.

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:27.280
[Guest]: And yeah, and that was the way I got into studying China and foreign policy broadly.

00:06:27.280 --> 00:06:32.800
[Amit Varma]: And given that you'd already studied international relations, I guess you must already have had,

00:06:32.800 --> 00:06:36.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, conceptions of what China was like, what the Chinese were like, what they wanted,

00:06:36.880 --> 00:06:38.120
[Amit Varma]: what the objectives were.

00:06:38.120 --> 00:06:43.680
[Amit Varma]: Did actually spending time, you know, working in that country change your mind?

00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:44.680
[Amit Varma]: And if so, in what ways?

00:06:44.680 --> 00:06:49.000
[Guest]: So, yeah, I mean, you know, going into the country, you obviously have this image, particularly

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:54.680
[Guest]: when you come from India and in India, the frame that we look at China is a deep suspicion.

00:06:54.680 --> 00:06:59.320
[Guest]: And even at our sort of points of time where we talk about heady cooperation, whether it

00:06:59.320 --> 00:07:04.600
[Guest]: was in the 50s or whether it was in the early 2000s, when you were talking about this notion

00:07:04.600 --> 00:07:10.280
[Guest]: of Chindia, there was a sense of, yes, euphoria, the ratio is rising, but there was also, there's

00:07:10.280 --> 00:07:12.720
[Guest]: always a sense of suspicion.

00:07:12.720 --> 00:07:17.200
[Guest]: So as an Indian going there and having studied in the West, you go with a deep sense of suspicion,

00:07:17.200 --> 00:07:21.920
[Guest]: not just from a realist perspective of Indian interest, but also from a value based perspective

00:07:21.920 --> 00:07:28.720
[Guest]: of being from a liberal democratic country in ethos to going to a country which is authoritarian,

00:07:28.720 --> 00:07:30.360
[Guest]: communist and all of that.

00:07:30.360 --> 00:07:34.120
[Guest]: But when you actually visit the country and live there for a significant amount of time,

00:07:34.120 --> 00:07:39.960
[Guest]: you do realize that the authoritarianism comes in shades, like a shade card of a paint company.

00:07:39.960 --> 00:07:43.760
[Guest]: You know, there are elements which are deep red, and then things start to sort of become

00:07:43.760 --> 00:07:45.520
[Guest]: lighter in shade.

00:07:45.520 --> 00:07:47.400
[Guest]: Criticism is allowed on different things.

00:07:47.400 --> 00:07:49.880
[Guest]: And criticism takes place on different things.

00:07:49.880 --> 00:07:51.280
[Guest]: People are people like they are everywhere.

00:07:51.280 --> 00:07:53.080
[Guest]: They're looking for a better life.

00:07:53.080 --> 00:07:57.600
[Guest]: People are looking for more space to voice their opinion in public and just basically

00:07:57.600 --> 00:07:59.240
[Guest]: express themselves much more.

00:07:59.240 --> 00:08:00.800
[Guest]: And you see that even in China.

00:08:00.800 --> 00:08:05.960
[Guest]: And you see a diversity of opinion, which often does not get reflected in news coverage

00:08:05.960 --> 00:08:06.960
[Guest]: of the country.

00:08:06.960 --> 00:08:11.120
[Guest]: And also what also always happens in news coverage of the country is that we tend to

00:08:11.120 --> 00:08:16.200
[Guest]: impose our own biases and our own perceptions without having understood why a country is

00:08:16.200 --> 00:08:17.560
[Guest]: doing certain things.

00:08:17.560 --> 00:08:19.480
[Guest]: What are the sort of historic drivers?

00:08:19.480 --> 00:08:21.280
[Guest]: What are the economic drivers?

00:08:21.280 --> 00:08:23.760
[Guest]: What are the political drivers of certain action?

00:08:23.760 --> 00:08:28.320
[Guest]: Everything gets sort of clubbed together in this notion of authoritarianism, and therefore

00:08:28.320 --> 00:08:29.320
[Guest]: state control.

00:08:29.320 --> 00:08:31.000
[Guest]: And therefore, that framework defines everything.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:36.480
[Guest]: Whereas there is much more push and pull happening between society, businesses, government, party,

00:08:36.480 --> 00:08:38.600
[Guest]: which don't necessarily get reflected in broader coverage.

00:08:38.600 --> 00:08:40.400
[Amit Varma]: No, and it's very interesting.

00:08:40.400 --> 00:08:44.800
[Amit Varma]: Like, you know, you were talking about these nuances, and I found that the two episodes

00:08:44.800 --> 00:08:49.320
[Amit Varma]: of the two part series you recorded with Pawan for the Pragati podcast, very illuminating,

00:08:49.320 --> 00:08:51.520
[Amit Varma]: where you bust eight myths about China.

00:08:51.520 --> 00:08:55.360
[Amit Varma]: And those myths are all about nuance in the sense that most of them are partly true, but

00:08:55.360 --> 00:08:56.360
[Amit Varma]: not quite.

00:08:56.360 --> 00:08:59.120
[Amit Varma]: For example, does China own, does the state own all the land?

00:08:59.120 --> 00:09:01.600
[Amit Varma]: Well, yeah, kind of, but they give leases.

00:09:01.600 --> 00:09:05.320
[Amit Varma]: And you know, so there is private property in the terms of what is built on those lands.

00:09:05.320 --> 00:09:10.600
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, you talk about how, you know, the media is fettered to the extent that they

00:09:10.600 --> 00:09:15.440
[Amit Varma]: will not directly, you know, criticize the premier or whatever, but they will talk about

00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:20.760
[Amit Varma]: the policy and within that marketplace that exists, you know, they will try to carve out

00:09:20.760 --> 00:09:22.640
[Amit Varma]: niches with the presentation of the news.

00:09:22.640 --> 00:09:26.840
[Amit Varma]: So you know, that it was kind of eye opening to me and you're right that, you know, many

00:09:26.840 --> 00:09:32.720
[Amit Varma]: Indians sort of think of China as this whole monolithic beast and it isn't quite that.

00:09:32.720 --> 00:09:34.040
[Guest]: Yeah, it isn't quite that.

00:09:34.040 --> 00:09:40.200
[Guest]: And I mean, I think there is justified reason for, in many ways, the Chinese media and the

00:09:40.200 --> 00:09:43.200
[Guest]: Chinese messaging is to blame for this.

00:09:43.200 --> 00:09:49.840
[Guest]: They would like to emphasize that, you know, that there is a strong central command over

00:09:49.840 --> 00:09:50.840
[Guest]: things.

00:09:50.840 --> 00:09:53.600
[Guest]: And on many things, there is strong central control.

00:09:53.600 --> 00:09:57.280
[Guest]: But this messaging that they also tend to deliver, and it varies from time to time.

00:09:57.280 --> 00:10:02.520
[Guest]: So if you look at the early 2000s to the till Xi Jinping comes to power, there is a sense

00:10:02.520 --> 00:10:06.720
[Guest]: that the Chinese themselves are delivering this message to you, that there is greater

00:10:06.720 --> 00:10:07.720
[Guest]: diversity here.

00:10:07.720 --> 00:10:09.760
[Guest]: And there's much more happening here.

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:14.120
[Guest]: But once Xi Jinping comes to power, things begin to consolidate and the messaging also

00:10:14.120 --> 00:10:19.760
[Guest]: changes because you want to message to the outside world of a strong leader because you

00:10:19.760 --> 00:10:24.040
[Guest]: also want to bring political legitimacy for his control within the country.

00:10:24.040 --> 00:10:26.520
[Guest]: So there are multiple reasons why this messaging goes out.

00:10:26.520 --> 00:10:30.760
[Guest]: And therefore, there is a strand of truth that yes, the central government controls

00:10:30.760 --> 00:10:34.680
[Guest]: a lot of things, the central leadership and the party across the board from center to

00:10:34.680 --> 00:10:39.120
[Guest]: provinces to villages has a significant role to play and has an increasing role to play

00:10:39.120 --> 00:10:40.600
[Guest]: under Xi Jinping.

00:10:40.600 --> 00:10:46.520
[Guest]: But the fact that there is societal pushback is missed quite frequently.

00:10:46.520 --> 00:10:52.720
[Guest]: And one of the sort of classic cases of this is legislation on domestic violence.

00:10:52.720 --> 00:10:57.640
[Guest]: Recently, there's been lots of controversy in China about a domestic violence bill, which

00:10:57.640 --> 00:10:59.400
[Guest]: was passed in 2016.

00:10:59.400 --> 00:11:04.240
[Guest]: And the bill creates more room for women to sort of file for divorce on grounds of domestic

00:11:04.240 --> 00:11:05.240
[Guest]: violence.

00:11:05.240 --> 00:11:11.200
[Guest]: Yet, often the judiciary is conflicted between protecting women's rights and following the

00:11:11.200 --> 00:11:16.280
[Guest]: parties dictate that family issues are also a matter of broader social harmony.

00:11:16.280 --> 00:11:20.440
[Guest]: So therefore, you see judges giving these misguided judgments where sometimes you will

00:11:20.440 --> 00:11:24.160
[Guest]: acknowledge that there is violence, but not grant divorce because it might impact the

00:11:24.160 --> 00:11:27.200
[Guest]: broader social fabric, which is absurd.

00:11:27.200 --> 00:11:32.320
[Guest]: But there is still pushback against this and people end up winning cases once sort of the

00:11:32.320 --> 00:11:33.320
[Guest]: narrative begins.

00:11:33.320 --> 00:11:38.380
[Guest]: And this one particular case in Sichuan, which was recently reported, the lady ends up going

00:11:38.380 --> 00:11:40.760
[Guest]: and appealing this verdict of not granting her divorce.

00:11:40.760 --> 00:11:43.560
[Guest]: And there is a bit of a public narrative that builds around this.

00:11:43.560 --> 00:11:46.200
[Guest]: And eventually the courts have to grant her divorce.

00:11:46.200 --> 00:11:52.240
[Guest]: So this is a sort of pull between state policy, party, party desires to individuals pushing

00:11:52.240 --> 00:11:53.240
[Guest]: back against this.

00:11:53.240 --> 00:11:57.760
[Amit Varma]: I guess, you know, what I often say about India that we sort of inhabit different centuries

00:11:57.760 --> 00:12:02.280
[Amit Varma]: at once, 1920 and 21st is in a sense true of China as well.

00:12:02.280 --> 00:12:06.520
[Amit Varma]: And you know, the kind of these tussles around modernity that you mentioned in the judicial

00:12:06.520 --> 00:12:11.200
[Amit Varma]: case is something that you see in India as well, where you will have judges telling rape

00:12:11.200 --> 00:12:14.600
[Amit Varma]: victims that why don't you marry your rapist and things like that.

00:12:14.600 --> 00:12:18.560
[Amit Varma]: So I guess that's one thing that's common to both countries.

00:12:18.560 --> 00:12:22.880
[Amit Varma]: You know, one interesting difference between India and China, which we discussed in our

00:12:22.880 --> 00:12:29.920
[Amit Varma]: last episode as well, is that in India, the idea of India or the battling ideas of India

00:12:29.920 --> 00:12:32.480
[Amit Varma]: are all relatively recent.

00:12:32.480 --> 00:12:37.800
[Amit Varma]: I mean, we were basically many nations started coming together, perhaps because of the East

00:12:37.800 --> 00:12:40.160
[Amit Varma]: India Company and the British Empire.

00:12:40.160 --> 00:12:44.800
[Amit Varma]: And you know, now we are what we are and, you know, because memories are so short, there

00:12:44.800 --> 00:12:47.000
[Amit Varma]: seems to be the sense of permanence about it.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:50.320
[Amit Varma]: But the ideas of India are relatively recent.

00:12:50.320 --> 00:12:54.560
[Amit Varma]: The idea of China, on the other hand, stretches back centuries.

00:12:54.560 --> 00:12:59.600
[Amit Varma]: And you know, you'd use this phrase, Tianxia to describe it, you know, all under the heaven.

00:12:59.600 --> 00:13:03.560
[Amit Varma]: The idea of China as a middle kingdom with the rest of the world revolving around it.

00:13:03.560 --> 00:13:08.880
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about that and how that idea has found expression through the ages.

00:13:08.880 --> 00:13:14.840
[Guest]: So this notion of Tianxia sort of goes back a couple of thousand years, actually.

00:13:14.840 --> 00:13:18.520
[Guest]: So if you look at China, one of the things that at least even the current government

00:13:18.520 --> 00:13:22.700
[Guest]: in China and the Communist Party sort of tries to project is of the sense of a continuous

00:13:22.700 --> 00:13:24.000
[Guest]: civilization.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:28.440
[Guest]: And that allows you to trace yourself back to about a couple of thousand years ago.

00:13:28.440 --> 00:13:33.600
[Guest]: So about say 1500 BC or you have a dynasty called the Shang Dynasty.

00:13:33.600 --> 00:13:39.760
[Guest]: The Shang Dynasty has sort of, it's the territory they control is nowhere close to what modern

00:13:39.760 --> 00:13:40.760
[Guest]: day China is like.

00:13:40.760 --> 00:13:44.480
[Guest]: It's a very small chunk of territory, but that's seen as the dynasty.

00:13:44.480 --> 00:13:48.920
[Guest]: And that begins with controlling a lot of narrative.

00:13:48.920 --> 00:13:52.720
[Guest]: And the Shangs believe in a certain deity, which is the supernatural entity, which is

00:13:52.720 --> 00:13:55.420
[Guest]: bestowing the emperor with certain authority.

00:13:55.420 --> 00:13:58.880
[Guest]: The Shang Dynasty goes and you have the next dynasty come into place, which is Zhou.

00:13:58.880 --> 00:14:02.680
[Guest]: And the Zhou essentially believe in something called the heavens.

00:14:02.680 --> 00:14:06.840
[Guest]: And they believe that, well, it's not necessarily an individual deity type of sort of personification

00:14:06.840 --> 00:14:07.920
[Guest]: of God.

00:14:07.920 --> 00:14:10.320
[Guest]: It's the heavens are a system and an order.

00:14:10.320 --> 00:14:14.260
[Guest]: And the word for heaven or sky in Mandarin is Tian.

00:14:14.260 --> 00:14:19.280
[Guest]: And the idea is that, well, everything is under the set of heavens and there is an order

00:14:19.280 --> 00:14:20.800
[Guest]: that has to be maintained.

00:14:20.800 --> 00:14:26.200
[Guest]: And the emperor and the dynasty is maintaining that order as some sort of an agent of heavens.

00:14:26.200 --> 00:14:29.160
[Guest]: And the heaven has given a mandate to the emperor to do so.

00:14:29.160 --> 00:14:34.080
[Guest]: Fast forward, this dynasty also collapses as a brutal sort of period of wars between

00:14:34.080 --> 00:14:39.320
[Guest]: different fiefdoms, which is called the Warring States period.

00:14:39.320 --> 00:14:43.520
[Guest]: And then you have finally the Qin Dynasty, which unifies this, you know, the entire these

00:14:43.520 --> 00:14:44.960
[Guest]: sort of warring states.

00:14:44.960 --> 00:14:51.680
[Guest]: And then this idea of, well, we need a deity, but we also need an orderly system.

00:14:51.680 --> 00:14:56.720
[Guest]: And it sort of usurps both these ideas and it creates this notion of everything under

00:14:56.720 --> 00:14:59.920
[Guest]: the heaven and the emperor being the son of heaven.

00:14:59.920 --> 00:15:04.080
[Guest]: And therefore you get Tianxia, which essentially means everything under the heaven.

00:15:04.080 --> 00:15:06.240
[Guest]: And the emperor becomes the son of heaven.

00:15:06.240 --> 00:15:11.040
[Guest]: Now in this sort of a worldview over the years, over the centuries, the world starts to get

00:15:11.040 --> 00:15:16.360
[Guest]: structured largely ethnically, but also based on territory in terms of, you know, the central

00:15:16.360 --> 00:15:17.360
[Guest]: realm.

00:15:17.360 --> 00:15:20.840
[Guest]: And then you think of, imagine concentric circles around one central circle.

00:15:20.840 --> 00:15:25.160
[Guest]: And what you will see is that the inner realm is the realm of the emperor.

00:15:25.160 --> 00:15:27.520
[Guest]: The rest of it all is of course under the heavens.

00:15:27.520 --> 00:15:32.120
[Guest]: And the emperor's grace and the emperor's rule radiates from the center outward.

00:15:32.120 --> 00:15:37.240
[Guest]: But as you go outward, you find the inner subjects and then you find outer subjects

00:15:37.240 --> 00:15:41.600
[Guest]: and then you find people at the furthest realms of the concentric circle, sort of the furthest

00:15:41.600 --> 00:15:45.360
[Guest]: concentric circle, which is the barbarians.

00:15:45.360 --> 00:15:51.520
[Guest]: And the emperor's job is essentially to sort of expand his realm and to be able to bring

00:15:51.520 --> 00:15:53.760
[Guest]: civilization to these different realms.

00:15:53.760 --> 00:15:58.040
[Guest]: Whereas the barbarians, well, you can, you might not be able to civilize them.

00:15:58.040 --> 00:15:59.160
[Guest]: That's up for debate.

00:15:59.160 --> 00:16:05.320
[Guest]: But that's essentially the Sinocentric worldview, where China becomes the center and therefore

00:16:05.320 --> 00:16:09.320
[Guest]: the phrase, the middle kingdom again, which has much more to its origin.

00:16:09.320 --> 00:16:13.960
[Guest]: It was related to that second dynasty that I mentioned, the Zhou dynasty, which was in

00:16:13.960 --> 00:16:16.040
[Guest]: the center of these multiple warring states.

00:16:16.040 --> 00:16:20.720
[Guest]: But essentially the idea that at the center of it all is China today and the world sort

00:16:20.720 --> 00:16:26.560
[Guest]: of is around it and the realm of the emperor is sort of, the grace of the emperor is expanding

00:16:26.560 --> 00:16:27.560
[Guest]: to these different realms.

00:16:27.560 --> 00:16:31.800
[Guest]: And at the outermost edge are the barbarians, who you potentially can't civilize, but they

00:16:31.800 --> 00:16:34.040
[Guest]: aren't necessarily as important.

00:16:34.040 --> 00:16:39.240
[Guest]: And that's this notion of Dianxia, where you create a set of tributary states whom you

00:16:39.240 --> 00:16:43.480
[Guest]: sort of associate with, there are inner subjects, which are your subjects, there are outer subjects,

00:16:43.480 --> 00:16:46.040
[Guest]: and then there are tributary states and then there are barbarians.

00:16:46.040 --> 00:16:49.960
[Guest]: And the tributary states are countries that you sort of subjugate in some sort of a relationship

00:16:49.960 --> 00:16:56.000
[Guest]: where their leaders can kowtow before you and acknowledge your superiority and your

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:57.560
[Guest]: authority.

00:16:57.560 --> 00:17:00.320
[Guest]: That does not mean that you annex territory.

00:17:00.320 --> 00:17:04.840
[Guest]: Over the centuries, the relationship with the Chinese dynasties and their tributary

00:17:04.840 --> 00:17:07.040
[Guest]: states has not necessarily been about annexing territory.

00:17:07.040 --> 00:17:12.720
[Guest]: It's basically about acknowledging the civilizational superiority of China, which meant sometimes

00:17:12.720 --> 00:17:17.400
[Guest]: adopting the calendar, adopting the language, adopting the script, adopting certain cultural

00:17:17.400 --> 00:17:18.480
[Guest]: practices.

00:17:18.480 --> 00:17:21.540
[Guest]: It meant preferable trading relationships.

00:17:21.540 --> 00:17:24.440
[Guest]: It meant that you would get access to the Chinese market.

00:17:24.440 --> 00:17:29.320
[Guest]: In return, obviously, you can come and kowtow, which is a long ceremonial process where you

00:17:29.320 --> 00:17:33.840
[Guest]: basically come and kneel before the emperor and acknowledge his superiority over you.

00:17:33.840 --> 00:17:38.200
[Guest]: And you can see reflections of, somewhere, reflections of this in modern Chinese behavior.

00:17:38.200 --> 00:17:42.840
[Guest]: I wouldn't say it's necessarily modern Chinese foreign policy is directly derivative of this,

00:17:42.840 --> 00:17:48.360
[Guest]: but this is a cultural strand which continues within the broader DNA.

00:17:48.360 --> 00:17:52.680
[Guest]: And you can see that today when Xi Jinping greets foreign leaders who visit China, there's

00:17:52.680 --> 00:17:53.680
[Guest]: a long red carpet.

00:17:53.680 --> 00:17:57.320
[Guest]: He stands at the edge of it as the emperor greeting somebody who's coming.

00:17:57.320 --> 00:18:02.560
[Guest]: Usually when the person who's sitting next to him is turned towards him in the photograph,

00:18:02.560 --> 00:18:07.560
[Guest]: usually reportage of it will talk to you about how visiting dignitary came and told Xi Jinping

00:18:07.560 --> 00:18:12.080
[Guest]: about how great his reform process has been, how wonderful China's development is, and

00:18:12.080 --> 00:18:15.120
[Guest]: how much they can gain from China's development by partnering with China.

00:18:15.120 --> 00:18:19.560
[Guest]: And all of that sort of tells you a little bit about this mentality of the Middle Kingdom

00:18:19.560 --> 00:18:23.760
[Guest]: and the emperor and the son of heaven, who is this benevolent ruler, who's scholarly,

00:18:23.760 --> 00:18:26.720
[Guest]: benevolent, powerful, and therefore commands respect.

00:18:26.720 --> 00:18:27.720
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:18:27.720 --> 00:18:30.480
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, the Qing dynasty, of course, fell in 1911.

00:18:30.480 --> 00:18:35.680
[Amit Varma]: And in 1949, the Communist Party finally takes over and Mao takes charge.

00:18:35.680 --> 00:18:41.260
[Amit Varma]: But you know, the period between 1839 and 1949 is also referred to sometimes as a period

00:18:41.260 --> 00:18:44.560
[Amit Varma]: of China's national humiliation, quote unquote.

00:18:44.560 --> 00:18:49.880
[Amit Varma]: And as John Garver writes in Protracted Contest, one of the books you recommended on the India-China

00:18:49.880 --> 00:18:55.600
[Amit Varma]: relationship, quote, as constructed by modern Chinese nationalism during the period between

00:18:55.600 --> 00:19:01.680
[Amit Varma]: 1839 and 1949, China was bullied, oppressed and exploited by foreign imperialism.

00:19:01.680 --> 00:19:07.400
[Amit Varma]: One dimension of this humiliation was a seizure of Chinese territory by aggressive imperialist

00:19:07.400 --> 00:19:09.560
[Amit Varma]: powers, stop quote.

00:19:09.560 --> 00:19:14.240
[Amit Varma]: And these terrorists, of course, include places where there were ethnic Chinese, like, which

00:19:14.240 --> 00:19:18.480
[Amit Varma]: is Han people like Taiwan, Hong Kong, Macau, but also those populated by non-Han people

00:19:18.480 --> 00:19:20.760
[Amit Varma]: like Vietnam, Mongolia, and Korea.

00:19:20.760 --> 00:19:26.840
[Amit Varma]: So when Mao comes to power in 1949, and this more than a century of humiliation, as it

00:19:26.840 --> 00:19:34.880
[Amit Varma]: were, has ended, what is the sort of response to the world that emerges from there?

00:19:34.880 --> 00:19:38.240
[Guest]: So there is, I'm just going to sort of trace back a little bit and talk about the century

00:19:38.240 --> 00:19:42.120
[Guest]: of humiliation, because it's an interesting sort of trope, which continues to play a role

00:19:42.120 --> 00:19:44.680
[Guest]: even in today's present day Chinese foreign policy, right?

00:19:44.680 --> 00:19:49.520
[Guest]: I mean, one of the things that the Chinese side has been talking about in its negotiations

00:19:49.520 --> 00:19:54.360
[Guest]: with the US in terms of this trade deal is that we will not sign up to unequal treaties.

00:19:54.360 --> 00:19:59.640
[Guest]: And this unequal treaty sort of conception goes back to the opium wars, where the first

00:19:59.640 --> 00:20:04.760
[Guest]: opium war, the Qing dynasty lost, and that launched the century of humiliation.

00:20:04.760 --> 00:20:10.360
[Guest]: Essentially, the idea was this, that the strong Qing state had begun to collapse, and foreigners

00:20:10.360 --> 00:20:12.680
[Guest]: had come to take stake in it.

00:20:12.680 --> 00:20:18.160
[Guest]: There was a lot of gunboat diplomacy, which led to, say, Britain signing this lease for

00:20:18.160 --> 00:20:21.080
[Guest]: 100 years with Hong Kong, managing more territory.

00:20:21.080 --> 00:20:24.480
[Guest]: And all of this was done for trading purposes and trading rights.

00:20:24.480 --> 00:20:29.160
[Guest]: And the Qing emperor starts to concede trading rights, not just to Britain, but to many other

00:20:29.160 --> 00:20:30.480
[Guest]: European powers.

00:20:30.480 --> 00:20:34.200
[Guest]: Germany eventually occupies a large part of Shandong province.

00:20:34.200 --> 00:20:35.560
[Guest]: And there's a lot of this that happens.

00:20:35.560 --> 00:20:38.160
[Guest]: China's coast begins to be forcefully opened up.

00:20:38.160 --> 00:20:40.640
[Guest]: The Qing emperor sort of have very little control over this.

00:20:40.640 --> 00:20:42.240
[Guest]: And there's this sort of number of reasons.

00:20:42.240 --> 00:20:46.280
[Guest]: I mean, historically, if you look at the literature in China, what they will tell you is that

00:20:46.280 --> 00:20:47.840
[Guest]: it was our folly.

00:20:47.840 --> 00:20:49.160
[Guest]: We were weak.

00:20:49.160 --> 00:20:54.040
[Guest]: And we were weak because we were stuck to certain dogma and certain processes of the

00:20:54.040 --> 00:20:56.200
[Guest]: past without looking to modernize.

00:20:56.200 --> 00:21:00.320
[Guest]: So in that period of following the first opium war, actually even before the first opium

00:21:00.320 --> 00:21:05.080
[Guest]: war, but following that more so, there's this movement called the self-strengthening movement.

00:21:05.080 --> 00:21:10.040
[Guest]: And that's a bunch of people who are learned, some of whom have attempted the civil services

00:21:10.040 --> 00:21:14.920
[Guest]: exam but failed it because the exam is so driven by rote learning and understanding

00:21:14.920 --> 00:21:20.520
[Guest]: of the classics, but not about say modern systems like what's a modern financial system

00:21:20.520 --> 00:21:22.600
[Guest]: like how do you develop new trading links?

00:21:22.600 --> 00:21:24.120
[Guest]: How do you do modern banking?

00:21:24.120 --> 00:21:25.480
[Guest]: What sort of technology do you need?

00:21:25.480 --> 00:21:27.240
[Guest]: How do you invest in modern weaponry?

00:21:27.240 --> 00:21:30.520
[Guest]: But it's actually looking at sort of Confucian classics, which you need to memorize, which

00:21:30.520 --> 00:21:34.080
[Guest]: have been standardized for decades and decades and centuries before.

00:21:34.080 --> 00:21:35.920
[Guest]: So the relevance of that is in question.

00:21:35.920 --> 00:21:38.400
[Guest]: And these guys are essentially saying, look, we need to change.

00:21:38.400 --> 00:21:42.600
[Guest]: And in many ways, we need to learn from the West, because if we have to survive in a world

00:21:42.600 --> 00:21:47.000
[Guest]: which is changing, and that was a changing world with the Industrial Revolution, we need

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:50.320
[Guest]: to adapt and we need to educate ourselves.

00:21:50.320 --> 00:21:54.100
[Guest]: And for that, we need to learn from the Baharians who are coming over.

00:21:54.100 --> 00:21:57.360
[Guest]: And there goes your trope for the Tianxia concept.

00:21:57.360 --> 00:22:00.560
[Guest]: And that movement sort of builds, but it doesn't really achieve critical mass because there

00:22:00.560 --> 00:22:05.120
[Guest]: are so many internal pushes and pulls, and the fact that the Europeans are sort of way

00:22:05.120 --> 00:22:10.960
[Guest]: ahead of the Qing in terms of just their material capacity, and also the political will to go

00:22:10.960 --> 00:22:16.520
[Guest]: and extract rewards from the Chinese Empire by force, that the Qing dynasty sort of starts

00:22:16.520 --> 00:22:18.120
[Guest]: to begin to unravel.

00:22:18.120 --> 00:22:22.560
[Guest]: Once it unravels, China goes through this massive period of turmoil, where initially

00:22:22.560 --> 00:22:27.880
[Guest]: there is warlordism, there's a weak central government.

00:22:27.880 --> 00:22:33.920
[Guest]: All of this sort of culminates into this sort of 1919 movement called the New Culture Movement,

00:22:33.920 --> 00:22:36.520
[Guest]: or what is today known as the May 4th Movement.

00:22:36.520 --> 00:22:41.960
[Guest]: On May 4th, 1919, after the First World War, you end up seeing a massive protest in Beijing

00:22:41.960 --> 00:22:44.920
[Guest]: and many other cities, but in Beijing predominantly.

00:22:44.920 --> 00:22:49.600
[Guest]: And this protest is about the Treaty of Versailles, the fact that the Germans had been defeated.

00:22:49.600 --> 00:22:52.560
[Guest]: The Chinese felt that this would mean that their territory held by the Germans would

00:22:52.560 --> 00:22:54.640
[Guest]: be given back to the Chinese government.

00:22:54.640 --> 00:22:59.680
[Guest]: But that territory is traded off to the Japanese, and that angers a lot of people.

00:22:59.680 --> 00:23:06.160
[Guest]: This is a search for a new system to hold China together, a new philosophy, a new idea.

00:23:06.160 --> 00:23:08.920
[Guest]: So you're searching for this idea of China.

00:23:08.920 --> 00:23:13.460
[Guest]: And in that, there are some people who are going to modern day nationalism, sort of driven

00:23:13.460 --> 00:23:15.200
[Guest]: by European nationalism.

00:23:15.200 --> 00:23:18.120
[Guest]: There are some people who are going back to the classics and saying, we need to go back

00:23:18.120 --> 00:23:19.520
[Guest]: to what we were like.

00:23:19.520 --> 00:23:23.120
[Guest]: And then there are others who are looking at new ideas like communism.

00:23:23.120 --> 00:23:26.760
[Guest]: And therefore you have the Communist Party formed in 1921.

00:23:26.760 --> 00:23:31.720
[Guest]: Again the next 30-35 years are a period of turmoil with the Japanese invasions, a civil

00:23:31.720 --> 00:23:36.080
[Guest]: war between the Communist Party and the Nationalists led by Chiang Kai-shek.

00:23:36.080 --> 00:23:40.260
[Guest]: And eventually you come to 1949, which is after the World War and after Japan has been

00:23:40.260 --> 00:23:44.880
[Guest]: defeated and Japan sort of starts to recede from, to give up control of the territories

00:23:44.880 --> 00:23:47.140
[Guest]: of China that they had control.

00:23:47.140 --> 00:23:49.400
[Guest]: You end up with Mao Zedong taking charge.

00:23:49.400 --> 00:23:53.960
[Guest]: And Mao Zedong takes charge as Chiang Kai-shek flees because after 1945, after the Second

00:23:53.960 --> 00:23:57.280
[Guest]: World War ended, there was another period of three, four years of conflict between the

00:23:57.280 --> 00:24:01.640
[Guest]: Nationalists and the Communists, which the Communists eventually win and Chiang Kai-shek

00:24:01.640 --> 00:24:05.680
[Guest]: flees Taiwan, setting up the Republic of China in Taiwan.

00:24:05.680 --> 00:24:07.440
[Guest]: And when Mao takes charge, he essentially looks at this.

00:24:07.440 --> 00:24:09.800
[Guest]: He looks at two broad priorities.

00:24:09.800 --> 00:24:13.720
[Guest]: The predominant thing that we today take away from Maoism is the idea of revolution and

00:24:13.720 --> 00:24:18.060
[Guest]: people's war and promoting a communist revolution around the world.

00:24:18.060 --> 00:24:25.120
[Guest]: But he blended that with this notion of China being the middle kingdom and also China being

00:24:25.120 --> 00:24:27.320
[Guest]: a nationalistic entity.

00:24:27.320 --> 00:24:31.840
[Guest]: So Mao was very clear that this is a system of states and yes, as much as we would like

00:24:31.840 --> 00:24:37.360
[Guest]: global revolution, we realize that in this system of international system of states,

00:24:37.360 --> 00:24:39.300
[Guest]: we need to become a powerful state.

00:24:39.300 --> 00:24:41.520
[Guest]: And therefore he invests in sort of nuclear weapons.

00:24:41.520 --> 00:24:45.240
[Guest]: He invests in science and technology, invests in the missile program.

00:24:45.240 --> 00:24:50.080
[Guest]: He undertakes very flawed policies like the Great Leap Forward to sort of industrialize

00:24:50.080 --> 00:24:52.800
[Guest]: and mechanize China very rapidly.

00:24:52.800 --> 00:24:55.520
[Guest]: And that sort of falls flat on his face by doing that.

00:24:55.520 --> 00:25:00.040
[Guest]: He also sort of harks back to history, which is like you mentioned, in Gawa's book, he

00:25:00.040 --> 00:25:07.320
[Guest]: tells you that in 1954, China puts out a map which identifies territories of Chinese interest.

00:25:07.320 --> 00:25:12.960
[Guest]: And that talks about the sense of nationalistic Chinese territories.

00:25:12.960 --> 00:25:16.080
[Guest]: It's a nationalist vision as opposed to a world vision for a revolution.

00:25:16.080 --> 00:25:19.600
[Guest]: Mao Zedong's first speech talks about China standing up.

00:25:19.600 --> 00:25:21.640
[Guest]: That's clearly a nationalistic statement.

00:25:21.640 --> 00:25:23.800
[Guest]: He talks about the century of humiliation.

00:25:23.800 --> 00:25:25.800
[Guest]: He talks about the classics of the past.

00:25:25.800 --> 00:25:31.280
[Guest]: So he's very cognizant of China as a civilization, as a state, and also as a revolutionary actor.

00:25:31.280 --> 00:25:35.320
[Guest]: And he tries to blend that together by saying that China needs to be the middle kingdom

00:25:35.320 --> 00:25:37.500
[Guest]: at the heart of this revolution.

00:25:37.500 --> 00:25:40.440
[Guest]: So that's broadly how Mao Zedong sort of looks at history.

00:25:40.440 --> 00:25:44.720
[Amit Varma]: And you know, that blending of nationalism with communism, you know, which otherwise

00:25:44.720 --> 00:25:49.160
[Amit Varma]: typically doesn't take so much recourse to nationalism, seems to me also to, you know,

00:25:49.160 --> 00:25:53.200
[Amit Varma]: in later years, what they say today about socialism with Chinese characteristics.

00:25:53.200 --> 00:25:58.680
[Amit Varma]: So it almost seems like you cannot really use any other lens to look at China because

00:25:58.680 --> 00:26:04.520
[Amit Varma]: a key part of how they have constructed what they are lies sort of in their past.

00:26:04.520 --> 00:26:09.360
[Amit Varma]: So how does sort of foreign policy evolve through the Mao years leading on to Deng?

00:26:09.360 --> 00:26:12.080
[Amit Varma]: And how does it then change with Deng in the late 70s?

00:26:12.080 --> 00:26:13.240
[Guest]: Okay, yeah, sure.

00:26:13.240 --> 00:26:14.720
[Guest]: I have this framework, right?

00:26:14.720 --> 00:26:16.160
[Guest]: You know, I teach a course in China.

00:26:16.160 --> 00:26:21.800
[Guest]: And in that, I talk about this idea that there are three distinct phases of Chinese foreign

00:26:21.800 --> 00:26:22.800
[Guest]: policy.

00:26:22.800 --> 00:26:25.920
[Guest]: I mean, you can divide, people can slice history as they want to, I've sliced it in three distinct

00:26:25.920 --> 00:26:27.120
[Guest]: phases.

00:26:27.120 --> 00:26:34.520
[Guest]: The first phase is this revolutionary era, which is characterized by high levels of control,

00:26:34.520 --> 00:26:39.160
[Guest]: a lot of elite friction also, although Mao is supreme, yet there is a lot of elite friction

00:26:39.160 --> 00:26:44.320
[Guest]: and one of the reasons for this elite friction is because there is a focus on mass agitation.

00:26:44.320 --> 00:26:48.320
[Guest]: Mao believes in people's wars and people's movements and people's evolutions.

00:26:48.320 --> 00:26:50.120
[Guest]: Growth fluctuates radically.

00:26:50.120 --> 00:26:54.920
[Guest]: So there are years where you will grow at, you know, 9% or double digit growth also.

00:26:54.920 --> 00:26:57.960
[Guest]: And then suddenly the next year, you might, a year or two later, you might end up with

00:26:57.960 --> 00:26:59.360
[Guest]: sort of negative growth.

00:26:59.360 --> 00:27:02.440
[Guest]: And that's problematic because it causes much more chaos.

00:27:02.440 --> 00:27:05.120
[Guest]: Foreign policy for Mao predominantly was ideological.

00:27:05.120 --> 00:27:10.840
[Guest]: He saw ideology as not just, like I said, in terms of the revolution, but also in terms

00:27:10.840 --> 00:27:11.840
[Guest]: of nationalism.

00:27:11.840 --> 00:27:17.720
[Guest]: If you look at his early years, he was very close to the Soviet Union.

00:27:17.720 --> 00:27:21.600
[Guest]: China learned a lot in the Soviet Union, not just in terms of the organizational structures

00:27:21.600 --> 00:27:28.640
[Guest]: of a Leninist party state structure, but also in terms of say, technology, weapons development,

00:27:28.640 --> 00:27:31.040
[Guest]: agricultural organization, and those sorts of things.

00:27:31.040 --> 00:27:34.680
[Guest]: And he sort of followed the Soviet Union to a certain degree until there came a split

00:27:34.680 --> 00:27:39.440
[Guest]: and that split had a lot to do with also internal dynamics within China, where Mao felt that

00:27:39.440 --> 00:27:44.560
[Guest]: his position was being threatened by so-called revisionists who didn't believe in the ideology

00:27:44.560 --> 00:27:45.780
[Guest]: as he did.

00:27:45.780 --> 00:27:48.920
[Guest]: And those revisionists were linked to sort of changes in the Soviet Union.

00:27:48.920 --> 00:27:52.680
[Guest]: And therefore, there's this period of seeing a Soviet split.

00:27:52.680 --> 00:27:57.280
[Guest]: And during which, at the same time, you also see, you know, Mao going through launching

00:27:57.280 --> 00:28:01.400
[Guest]: the cultural revolution domestically, which therefore means that his foreign policy objectives

00:28:01.400 --> 00:28:06.920
[Guest]: become secondary in many ways, because he's focusing on the cultural revolution at home,

00:28:06.920 --> 00:28:12.240
[Guest]: which is this tremendous violent period with millions and millions dying as student Red

00:28:12.240 --> 00:28:14.160
[Guest]: Guards take to the streets.

00:28:14.160 --> 00:28:17.560
[Guest]: You're burning books, you're attacking academics, you're attacking elites.

00:28:17.560 --> 00:28:23.520
[Guest]: Xi Jinping's father, who was a senior party member, was one of the targets of the cultural

00:28:23.520 --> 00:28:24.520
[Guest]: revolution.

00:28:24.520 --> 00:28:30.000
[Guest]: Xi Jinping as a student was sent to work in a small village, and he lived in a cave, as

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:32.680
[Guest]: the famous story goes, as part of the cultural revolution.

00:28:32.680 --> 00:28:36.000
[Guest]: So his education was sort of truncated at that point of time.

00:28:36.000 --> 00:28:40.120
[Guest]: So that revolution still holds much sway in China today in terms of the historical memory

00:28:40.120 --> 00:28:41.120
[Guest]: of it.

00:28:41.120 --> 00:28:42.280
[Guest]: But that was Mao's foreign policy.

00:28:42.280 --> 00:28:45.840
[Guest]: He looked at promoting revolution and he looked at China at the heart of that revolution.

00:28:45.840 --> 00:28:48.480
[Guest]: There was very limited success.

00:28:48.480 --> 00:28:53.280
[Guest]: Some of his gains were essentially about strengthening China's national power capacity through weapons

00:28:53.280 --> 00:28:57.280
[Guest]: development, which gave China a seat at the table predominantly.

00:28:57.280 --> 00:29:00.880
[Guest]: When it came to India, his approach was slightly mixed.

00:29:00.880 --> 00:29:08.240
[Guest]: At some level, he saw India as a potential partner, but also a hegemonic successor to

00:29:08.240 --> 00:29:10.120
[Guest]: the British Raj.

00:29:10.120 --> 00:29:15.120
[Guest]: He saw the Indian state as being the Indian leadership at that point of time, being capitalist

00:29:15.120 --> 00:29:18.080
[Guest]: in their orientation, Nehru particularly.

00:29:18.080 --> 00:29:22.600
[Guest]: He saw them being Western educated and therefore being driven by those sorts of agendas.

00:29:22.600 --> 00:29:29.240
[Guest]: He saw them as the mindset of the Indian foreign policy as being one of desiring hegemony over

00:29:29.240 --> 00:29:33.640
[Guest]: what is South Asia and also territories which the Chinese were interested in, which is places

00:29:33.640 --> 00:29:36.440
[Guest]: like Sikkim, Bhutan, Tibet.

00:29:36.440 --> 00:29:40.720
[Guest]: And therefore, there was a sense of friction between these two countries, not just at a

00:29:40.720 --> 00:29:47.440
[Guest]: level of territorial disputes, but also in the context of where they each saw their ideologies.

00:29:47.440 --> 00:29:49.720
[Guest]: And that source of friction sort of persisted over a period of time.

00:29:49.720 --> 00:29:52.920
[Guest]: After Deng Xiaoping, what happened was that China went through such a terrible phase in

00:29:52.920 --> 00:29:58.800
[Guest]: the Cultural Revolution that once Deng Xiaoping took charge, Mao Zedong died in 1976.

00:29:58.800 --> 00:30:02.440
[Guest]: And for two years, there was still a lot of turmoil with the Gang of Four, essentially

00:30:02.440 --> 00:30:07.640
[Guest]: successors to Mao, lobbying for power and therefore continuing persecution until there's

00:30:07.640 --> 00:30:13.840
[Guest]: a pushback from other party elites and the Gang of Four get tried and get sentenced.

00:30:13.840 --> 00:30:15.720
[Guest]: And Deng Xiaoping emerges as this leader.

00:30:15.720 --> 00:30:17.880
[Guest]: Deng himself had suffered in the Cultural Revolution.

00:30:17.880 --> 00:30:20.400
[Guest]: He was himself chastised.

00:30:20.400 --> 00:30:24.840
[Guest]: And he, once he takes charge, he looks at things pragmatically and he says, look, we

00:30:24.840 --> 00:30:29.900
[Guest]: are millions and millions and hundreds of millions of people in China in deep poverty.

00:30:29.900 --> 00:30:33.040
[Guest]: We can't be talking about revolution until we address some of these things.

00:30:33.040 --> 00:30:35.800
[Guest]: We need to be open to the world abroad.

00:30:35.800 --> 00:30:37.640
[Guest]: Under Mao, some changes had begun.

00:30:37.640 --> 00:30:41.960
[Guest]: There was a rapprochement with the US which had begun and Deng Xiaoping takes that time

00:30:41.960 --> 00:30:44.200
[Guest]: to nurture that rapprochement.

00:30:44.200 --> 00:30:46.480
[Guest]: And in the early 80s, he travels to the US.

00:30:46.480 --> 00:30:50.280
[Guest]: He launches what is a reform and opening up policy which says we're going to reform domestic

00:30:50.280 --> 00:30:51.280
[Guest]: economic structures.

00:30:51.280 --> 00:30:52.600
[Guest]: We're going to trim down the state.

00:30:52.600 --> 00:30:56.440
[Guest]: We're going to pull back this ideological control a little bit.

00:30:56.440 --> 00:31:02.440
[Guest]: The party still remains primary and the role of the party is at the heart of everything.

00:31:02.440 --> 00:31:07.320
[Guest]: But we need to change the way we do business in order to achieve economic goals.

00:31:07.320 --> 00:31:11.520
[Guest]: And so economic diplomacy and economic foreign policy becomes his primary objective.

00:31:11.520 --> 00:31:15.520
[Guest]: And that's where things sort of start to develop with Deng Xiaoping.

00:31:15.520 --> 00:31:21.320
[Guest]: When he starts to expand the Chinese economy, try and lift people out of poverty, and also

00:31:21.320 --> 00:31:23.680
[Guest]: hedge with the US and the Soviet Union.

00:31:23.680 --> 00:31:27.760
[Guest]: Under Gorbachev, with Deng Xiaoping, China and Soviet Union begin to get some sort of

00:31:27.760 --> 00:31:32.200
[Guest]: a rapprochement again after their sort of tumultuous 60s and 70s.

00:31:32.200 --> 00:31:35.920
[Guest]: But then the Soviet Union collapses and the ballgame changes entirely.

00:31:35.920 --> 00:31:40.280
[Guest]: But for Deng Xiaoping predominantly, and even for his successors thereafter, the objective

00:31:40.280 --> 00:31:45.400
[Guest]: of foreign policy was to pursue your interests, ensure that your territorial interests and

00:31:45.400 --> 00:31:51.560
[Guest]: sovereignty remained intact and you didn't sort of succumb and give some of those away.

00:31:51.560 --> 00:31:58.280
[Guest]: But you expand growth, ease control, while maintaining the central role of the Communist

00:31:58.280 --> 00:31:59.640
[Guest]: Party of China.

00:31:59.640 --> 00:32:04.480
[Guest]: And that's how it's been for the next 30-35 years until Xi Jinping sort of comes to power.

00:32:04.480 --> 00:32:08.040
[Guest]: Actually a little before Xi Jinping, but say around 2008-2009.

00:32:08.040 --> 00:32:11.000
[Guest]: And that's what broadly the foreign policy has been about.

00:32:11.000 --> 00:32:12.680
[Guest]: It's been about economic development.

00:32:12.680 --> 00:32:18.240
[Guest]: It's been about economic diplomacy, while ensuring that you remain fairly tough on issues

00:32:18.240 --> 00:32:23.400
[Guest]: that are core to you, say Tibet, say Hong Kong, say even Taiwan.

00:32:23.400 --> 00:32:28.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and you know, one of Deng's slogans, of course, was hide your strength, bide your

00:32:28.360 --> 00:32:33.240
[Amit Varma]: time, stop quote, which is, you know, almost like a paraphrasing of what Sun Tzu said centuries

00:32:33.240 --> 00:32:38.840
[Amit Varma]: earlier, which is, quote, to subdue the enemy without fighting is the supreme excellence,

00:32:38.840 --> 00:32:39.840
[Amit Varma]: stop quote.

00:32:39.840 --> 00:32:43.880
[Amit Varma]: So just the phrase bide your time is very interesting, because it almost seems as if

00:32:43.880 --> 00:32:47.320
[Amit Varma]: what happened in all the Deng years was that China was building its strength and biding

00:32:47.320 --> 00:32:52.760
[Amit Varma]: its time, true to what he said, and then Xi Jinping onwards, they clearly feel that their

00:32:52.760 --> 00:32:54.360
[Amit Varma]: time has come.

00:32:54.360 --> 00:32:56.020
[Amit Varma]: Would that be a correct summation?

00:32:56.020 --> 00:33:00.320
[Amit Varma]: And how has foreign policy changed since Xi Jinping?

00:33:00.320 --> 00:33:05.960
[Amit Varma]: And how much of it is, for example, due to the powerful personality of the man himself?

00:33:05.960 --> 00:33:10.200
[Amit Varma]: I mean, a lot of, you know, he centralized a lot of power around himself and clearly

00:33:10.200 --> 00:33:11.800
[Amit Varma]: had his own vision of the world.

00:33:11.800 --> 00:33:14.360
[Amit Varma]: How big a part does that play in the thing?

00:33:14.360 --> 00:33:19.160
[Guest]: So yeah, I mean, Deng Xiaoping's logic of keeping a low profile, I mean, the phrase

00:33:19.160 --> 00:33:23.400
[Guest]: is tao kuang yang hui, which, like you said, means broadly, roughly hide your strength

00:33:23.400 --> 00:33:27.160
[Guest]: and bide your time, keep a low profile while pursuing your interests.

00:33:27.160 --> 00:33:29.600
[Guest]: Essentially, what he wanted to do was what he could do.

00:33:29.600 --> 00:33:36.640
[Guest]: China was a large country with a lot of problems and a lot of fundamental problems.

00:33:36.640 --> 00:33:41.640
[Guest]: And you didn't have the capacity, while you might have had the will to sort of achieve

00:33:41.640 --> 00:33:45.440
[Guest]: certain broader foreign policy objectives, you didn't have the capacity to do that.

00:33:45.440 --> 00:33:50.040
[Guest]: And your objective predominantly was growth and development, because if you did not have

00:33:50.040 --> 00:33:54.480
[Guest]: performance legitimacy over a period of time, it would be very difficult for the party to

00:33:54.480 --> 00:34:01.840
[Guest]: sustain control over such a large population if it continued to remain that volatile.

00:34:01.840 --> 00:34:04.560
[Guest]: So that was broadly what it was like.

00:34:04.560 --> 00:34:09.480
[Guest]: His successors, so for example, Hu Jintao, who was a successor, who was after Jiang Zemin.

00:34:09.480 --> 00:34:14.200
[Guest]: So Deng Xiaoping's leadership, the next big leader that comes out is Jiang Zemin and subsequently

00:34:14.200 --> 00:34:15.200
[Guest]: Hu Jintao.

00:34:15.200 --> 00:34:18.480
[Guest]: Hu Jintao had a policy recognizing that China was rising, right?

00:34:18.480 --> 00:34:24.200
[Guest]: So his policy was about China's peaceful rise and China's sort of peaceful development.

00:34:24.200 --> 00:34:28.080
[Guest]: And the idea was signaling to the world that, yes, while we are rising, we're not going

00:34:28.080 --> 00:34:29.280
[Guest]: to be rising with violence.

00:34:29.280 --> 00:34:30.800
[Guest]: We're going to be rising peacefully.

00:34:30.800 --> 00:34:35.080
[Guest]: We're going to be rising by trying to lift all the boats together.

00:34:35.080 --> 00:34:38.080
[Guest]: And in that process of rise, of course, things will change.

00:34:38.080 --> 00:34:43.280
[Guest]: I mean, Edward Luttwak in his book on China has a really interesting analogy to describe

00:34:43.280 --> 00:34:44.280
[Guest]: this, right?

00:34:44.280 --> 00:34:47.960
[Guest]: He talks about China being this big elephant in an elevator.

00:34:47.960 --> 00:34:53.560
[Guest]: And while the elephant is continuing to expand, it might not be threatening, it's squeezing

00:34:53.560 --> 00:34:56.880
[Guest]: other people and therefore it will automatically seem threatening.

00:34:56.880 --> 00:35:00.000
[Guest]: And that was essentially the sort of dilemma that Hu Jintao was facing.

00:35:00.000 --> 00:35:03.640
[Guest]: And therefore this narrative of peaceful rise was framed.

00:35:03.640 --> 00:35:06.480
[Guest]: Under Xi Jinping, what starts to happen is something very different.

00:35:06.480 --> 00:35:08.600
[Guest]: And it starts a little bit before that, like I mentioned in the past.

00:35:08.600 --> 00:35:14.520
[Guest]: So around 2008, 2009, you have financial crisis and the world economy is going through a downturn.

00:35:14.520 --> 00:35:16.560
[Guest]: The US in particular is struggling.

00:35:16.560 --> 00:35:18.560
[Guest]: The Chinese are particularly cognizant about this.

00:35:18.560 --> 00:35:22.080
[Guest]: So in one of the sort of strategic economic dialogues with the Obama administration's

00:35:22.080 --> 00:35:26.680
[Guest]: officials after the 2008 crisis hits, the Chinese are quoted as saying, look, we're

00:35:26.680 --> 00:35:27.680
[Guest]: disappointed in you.

00:35:27.680 --> 00:35:30.160
[Guest]: I mean, what on earth have you done?

00:35:30.160 --> 00:35:32.840
[Guest]: And they're quite annoyed with the US for the particular failures that they've sort

00:35:32.840 --> 00:35:36.840
[Guest]: of experienced, because they feel this causes economic problems for the Chinese also.

00:35:36.840 --> 00:35:41.440
[Guest]: And it did cause economic problems because China's economy was predicated on export-led

00:35:41.440 --> 00:35:42.440
[Guest]: growth.

00:35:42.440 --> 00:35:47.440
[Guest]: And if your biggest export markets are today going through deep crises, you're never going

00:35:47.440 --> 00:35:49.600
[Guest]: to be able to sustain that growth.

00:35:49.600 --> 00:35:54.320
[Guest]: So they had to shift to higher investments and more debt and also launch a bailout package.

00:35:54.320 --> 00:35:56.200
[Guest]: But at the same time, you saw an opportunity.

00:35:56.200 --> 00:36:00.680
[Guest]: And the opportunity was in the fact that there is greater space opening up in the international

00:36:00.680 --> 00:36:01.800
[Guest]: system.

00:36:01.800 --> 00:36:07.360
[Guest]: And China today has the capacity and can continue to develop the capacity to exploit that space.

00:36:07.360 --> 00:36:11.600
[Guest]: So starting from 2008, 2009, you see something start to shift.

00:36:11.600 --> 00:36:15.680
[Guest]: You see them start to build these sort of start to work towards consolidating their

00:36:15.680 --> 00:36:17.380
[Guest]: strength in the South China Sea.

00:36:17.380 --> 00:36:22.760
[Guest]: You see the then Chinese foreign minister go to an ASEAN meeting and say something like,

00:36:22.760 --> 00:36:27.200
[Guest]: you know, China is a big country and big countries do what we do.

00:36:27.200 --> 00:36:31.140
[Guest]: And I was telling all these ASEAN states that, look, you're small states, you need to listen

00:36:31.140 --> 00:36:32.140
[Guest]: to us.

00:36:32.140 --> 00:36:35.320
[Guest]: And that's a different expression from what their normal diplomatic balance is, which

00:36:35.320 --> 00:36:39.480
[Guest]: is that all states are equal, sovereignty is the norm and those sorts of things.

00:36:39.480 --> 00:36:42.080
[Guest]: And you start to see this sense changing.

00:36:42.080 --> 00:36:46.240
[Guest]: You also start to see a sense of nationalism beginning to rise.

00:36:46.240 --> 00:36:50.360
[Guest]: And you start to see increasingly more assertive actions being taken.

00:36:50.360 --> 00:36:55.760
[Guest]: All of this comes into this framework of a policy discussion that's going on within China,

00:36:55.760 --> 00:37:01.800
[Guest]: whether we should fundamentally shift from this idea in our minds also, from being a

00:37:01.800 --> 00:37:07.040
[Guest]: developing country, which is still keeping its head low and which is not interfering

00:37:07.040 --> 00:37:11.200
[Guest]: too much, but actually just taking care of its interests predominantly, to now saying

00:37:11.200 --> 00:37:14.480
[Guest]: that, look, we're a big country and we're a rising power.

00:37:14.480 --> 00:37:16.720
[Guest]: And while we say that, let's acknowledge that to ourselves.

00:37:16.720 --> 00:37:21.200
[Guest]: And that would mean a change in the way we behave and a change in the way of what we

00:37:21.200 --> 00:37:23.240
[Guest]: expect from our behavior.

00:37:23.240 --> 00:37:25.040
[Guest]: And therefore, this discussion sort of starts to take place.

00:37:25.040 --> 00:37:30.840
[Guest]: So the shift from Deng Xiaoping's Taokuang Yanghui to a modern logic, which is called

00:37:30.840 --> 00:37:36.760
[Guest]: Fanfa Youwei, which essentially means striving for achievement or striving to change your

00:37:36.760 --> 00:37:41.000
[Guest]: external environment in order to suit your interests, actively doing things to change

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:44.480
[Guest]: it, as opposed to just reacting to keep your interests in check.

00:37:44.480 --> 00:37:48.840
[Guest]: And under Xi Jinping, this sort of model starts to take far more prominence because he starts

00:37:48.840 --> 00:37:51.560
[Guest]: to take actions to change the external environment.

00:37:51.560 --> 00:37:56.440
[Guest]: One of the first things he does is he comes in, he announces this idea that everybody

00:37:56.440 --> 00:37:58.560
[Guest]: needs to pursue a Chinese dream.

00:37:58.560 --> 00:38:01.080
[Guest]: And that's a very populist framework, right?

00:38:01.080 --> 00:38:06.360
[Guest]: I mean, you come out and you say, you know, every Chinese has a dream and this nation

00:38:06.360 --> 00:38:09.040
[Guest]: has a dream and that nation's dream is the China dream.

00:38:09.040 --> 00:38:13.200
[Guest]: And all of your cumulative dreams come together to create this China dream.

00:38:13.200 --> 00:38:18.960
[Guest]: So that's the first sign of Xi Jinping being breaking away from traditional robotic, you

00:38:18.960 --> 00:38:25.120
[Guest]: know, black dyed, gelled head Chinese leaders who are very morose to somebody who's charismatic,

00:38:25.120 --> 00:38:29.360
[Guest]: who wants to sort of connect with the people and who also wants to present a picture to

00:38:29.360 --> 00:38:35.160
[Guest]: the outside world of China being different and changing and becoming far more active.

00:38:35.160 --> 00:38:40.200
[Guest]: So it's a little bit of Xi Jinping's personality himself when he was nominated as a successor

00:38:40.200 --> 00:38:41.400
[Guest]: in 2007, 2008.

00:38:41.400 --> 00:38:47.240
[Guest]: Nobody really saw him as this charismatic individual, but as he takes power in 2012,

00:38:47.240 --> 00:38:50.280
[Guest]: 2013, you see him launch this notion of the Chinese dream.

00:38:50.280 --> 00:38:53.640
[Guest]: And that is the first sign of Xi Jinping being a man of the people.

00:38:53.640 --> 00:38:56.760
[Guest]: He subsequently launches a massive corruption crackdown.

00:38:56.760 --> 00:39:01.080
[Guest]: And that corruption crackdown has a lot of public support because of the preceding years,

00:39:01.080 --> 00:39:04.820
[Guest]: there's a lot of criticism of corruption in China domestically.

00:39:04.820 --> 00:39:10.440
[Guest]: People are annoyed with sort of venal Communist Party leaders who are keeping, maintaining

00:39:10.440 --> 00:39:14.880
[Guest]: concubines, taking money outside the country, living luxurious lifestyles.

00:39:14.880 --> 00:39:18.760
[Guest]: There are certain scandals which come out and all this sort of builds this momentum

00:39:18.760 --> 00:39:19.760
[Guest]: against corruption.

00:39:19.760 --> 00:39:25.360
[Guest]: Xi Jinping leverages that and like every other Chinese leader launches a corruption campaign.

00:39:25.360 --> 00:39:31.320
[Guest]: It's just that his is far more sharper and the edge is targeted at corruption and also

00:39:31.320 --> 00:39:33.160
[Guest]: at political opponents.

00:39:33.160 --> 00:39:37.000
[Guest]: Xi Jinping doesn't have a clear defined political opponent because he's not really part of any

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:40.080
[Guest]: of the established factions in Chinese political system.

00:39:40.080 --> 00:39:41.720
[Guest]: So Xi Jinping is sort of an outsider.

00:39:41.720 --> 00:39:46.520
[Guest]: He doesn't necessarily have, he's not a member of any of the established factions that dominate

00:39:46.520 --> 00:39:47.920
[Guest]: the Chinese political system.

00:39:47.920 --> 00:39:51.920
[Guest]: And that's one of the reasons why he was a consensus candidate when he was chosen in

00:39:51.920 --> 00:39:52.920
[Guest]: 2007, 2008.

00:39:52.920 --> 00:39:58.200
[Guest]: But when he takes power, he sort of starts to take the knees out of both the factions,

00:39:58.200 --> 00:40:00.280
[Guest]: both the dominating factions.

00:40:00.280 --> 00:40:05.040
[Guest]: He also starts to take the knees out of the oil grouping, the bureaucrats who are in the

00:40:05.040 --> 00:40:06.040
[Guest]: oil industry.

00:40:06.040 --> 00:40:11.560
[Guest]: And he takes, he hits at some of the seriously prominent figures who just left their positions

00:40:11.560 --> 00:40:13.080
[Guest]: of power.

00:40:13.080 --> 00:40:17.760
[Guest]: And that sort of sends a chill down the political system and the bureaucracy and allows him

00:40:17.760 --> 00:40:19.200
[Guest]: to further consolidate his power.

00:40:19.200 --> 00:40:23.980
[Guest]: His first five years have been extremely, were extremely critical.

00:40:23.980 --> 00:40:28.680
[Guest]: And the fact that he had, he managed to get things done and consolidate himself in the

00:40:28.680 --> 00:40:32.880
[Guest]: position that he has, that he now has his name in the Chinese constitution and the party's

00:40:32.880 --> 00:40:38.560
[Guest]: constitution right alongside Mao Zedong, because Mao Zedong in the constitution has a thought.

00:40:38.560 --> 00:40:40.160
[Guest]: It's called Mao Zedong thought.

00:40:40.160 --> 00:40:41.780
[Guest]: And Xi Jinping has a thought.

00:40:41.780 --> 00:40:43.280
[Guest]: Other leaders have theories.

00:40:43.280 --> 00:40:45.680
[Guest]: In the Chinese parlance, thought is greater than theory.

00:40:45.680 --> 00:40:48.560
[Guest]: So Xi Jinping is at par with Mao right now.

00:40:48.560 --> 00:40:54.840
[Guest]: And therefore he's got the freedom to try and pursue a far more expressive and expansive

00:40:54.840 --> 00:40:55.840
[Guest]: foreign policy.

00:40:55.840 --> 00:40:56.840
[Guest]: And he does that, right?

00:40:56.840 --> 00:40:59.200
[Guest]: He launches Belt and Road in 2013.

00:40:59.200 --> 00:41:03.400
[Guest]: He establishes the AIIB, the Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank.

00:41:03.400 --> 00:41:06.400
[Guest]: He strengthens the Shanghai Cooperation Organization grouping.

00:41:06.400 --> 00:41:09.400
[Guest]: Today, India and Pakistan are parts of that grouping.

00:41:09.400 --> 00:41:15.280
[Guest]: And he starts to express himself far more broadly on the international stage.

00:41:15.280 --> 00:41:17.640
[Guest]: China now has its own narrative on human rights.

00:41:17.640 --> 00:41:22.920
[Guest]: China has its own narrative on economic globalization, which has gotten particularly more prominent

00:41:22.920 --> 00:41:25.060
[Guest]: after Donald Trump in the US.

00:41:25.060 --> 00:41:27.440
[Guest]: And this is where sort of Xi Jinping's foreign policy is leading.

00:41:27.440 --> 00:41:32.400
[Guest]: It's about establishing China as a big country, not just from an external viewer's point of

00:41:32.400 --> 00:41:37.320
[Guest]: view, but also internalizing it within the Chinese system that we are a big country and

00:41:37.320 --> 00:41:39.320
[Guest]: we need to be there for acting like a big country.

00:41:39.320 --> 00:41:44.960
[Amit Varma]: Now, you know, on the one hand, it might seem as if China's foreign policy is sort of evolving

00:41:44.960 --> 00:41:47.440
[Amit Varma]: with the state of the country itself.

00:41:47.440 --> 00:41:52.720
[Amit Varma]: That you know, first, it's not really a superpower, you know, through the 70s, 80s, 90s, whatever.

00:41:52.720 --> 00:41:57.400
[Amit Varma]: So they bide their time as they gradually build, you know, in 96, Jiang talks about

00:41:57.400 --> 00:42:00.080
[Amit Varma]: the five principles of peaceful coexistence.

00:42:00.080 --> 00:42:02.280
[Amit Varma]: And at that point, they're not really asserting themselves.

00:42:02.280 --> 00:42:06.440
[Amit Varma]: And then as China gets economically more powerful, they sort of assert themselves, I guess, that's

00:42:06.440 --> 00:42:07.880
[Amit Varma]: one way of looking at it.

00:42:07.880 --> 00:42:14.800
[Amit Varma]: But you know, just thinking about my question to you also is about how big a role domestic

00:42:14.800 --> 00:42:20.560
[Amit Varma]: political imperatives play in shaping the foreign policy of Xi, for example, just to

00:42:20.560 --> 00:42:25.840
[Amit Varma]: sort of draw an analogy, if you sort of look at how Indira Gandhi came to power, where

00:42:25.840 --> 00:42:31.840
[Amit Varma]: she was also like a kind of a compromise candidate, you know, the party, senior folks thought

00:42:31.840 --> 00:42:34.880
[Amit Varma]: she'll be easy to control, they called her a goongi guria.

00:42:34.880 --> 00:42:39.840
[Amit Varma]: And then because of the political imperative of having to distinguish herself, she turned

00:42:39.840 --> 00:42:46.200
[Amit Varma]: sharply left, and, you know, carried out a series of economic measures like bank nationalizations,

00:42:46.200 --> 00:42:51.040
[Amit Varma]: FARA, all those labor laws which came up, which basically devastated the country.

00:42:51.040 --> 00:42:56.000
[Amit Varma]: And those were not driven by that bad economics was not driven by a belief in economics in

00:42:56.000 --> 00:43:02.040
[Amit Varma]: that that economics per se, but just to distinguish herself politically, from her rivals and carve

00:43:02.040 --> 00:43:03.480
[Amit Varma]: out that niche.

00:43:03.480 --> 00:43:10.580
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, I wonder how much of the assertive foreign policy under Xi comes from this necessity

00:43:10.580 --> 00:43:17.520
[Amit Varma]: for him to also carve out that space in China's new modern mythology, like first, of course,

00:43:17.520 --> 00:43:22.520
[Amit Varma]: he consolidates power using the corruption campaign, gets rid of his rivals, and gradually

00:43:22.520 --> 00:43:27.320
[Amit Varma]: power consolidates more and more under him till now, you say, as you say, his name is

00:43:27.320 --> 00:43:28.680
[Amit Varma]: in the Constitution.

00:43:28.680 --> 00:43:33.480
[Amit Varma]: But does a lot of this assertiveness also have to do with the man himself and the local

00:43:33.480 --> 00:43:36.760
[Amit Varma]: incentives which are driving his geopolitical moves?

00:43:36.760 --> 00:43:40.880
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, that's an interesting question, right? And often this gets missed.

00:43:40.880 --> 00:43:45.400
[Guest]: So when it comes to the man himself, I mean, it's very difficult, obviously, to paint a

00:43:45.400 --> 00:43:48.800
[Guest]: picture of the man himself, given that the system is so big.

00:43:48.800 --> 00:43:54.240
[Guest]: But from the sense that we get is that Xi Jinping himself sees himself as a man of destiny

00:43:54.240 --> 00:43:55.440
[Guest]: in many ways.

00:43:55.440 --> 00:44:01.160
[Guest]: He has a strong sense of history, and he has a strong sense of the need for the party to

00:44:01.160 --> 00:44:02.160
[Guest]: sustain.

00:44:02.160 --> 00:44:08.560
[Guest]: If you look at what is now known as Xi Jinping thought on diplomacy, the first point of Xi

00:44:08.560 --> 00:44:12.760
[Guest]: Jinping thought on diplomacy is the first objective is to uphold the centralized and

00:44:12.760 --> 00:44:16.120
[Guest]: unified leadership of the Communist Party of China.

00:44:16.120 --> 00:44:20.200
[Guest]: The second of those is to pursue diplomacy to realize national rejuvenation.

00:44:20.200 --> 00:44:23.040
[Guest]: Both of those are essentially domestic objectives.

00:44:23.040 --> 00:44:29.560
[Guest]: You are looking at maintaining economic growth, ensuring expansion of Chinese national power

00:44:29.560 --> 00:44:35.320
[Guest]: to be able to not just fuel national pride and all of that, but also to improve the lot

00:44:35.320 --> 00:44:40.120
[Guest]: of the people in the country, but also through that legitimized party rule.

00:44:40.120 --> 00:44:44.400
[Guest]: So economic growth, economic development is fundamental to what his foreign policy has

00:44:44.400 --> 00:44:45.440
[Guest]: been.

00:44:45.440 --> 00:44:50.040
[Guest]: And one of the biggest drivers of this Belt and Road Initiative, which is essentially

00:44:50.040 --> 00:44:54.560
[Guest]: now characterizes his entire foreign policy, because BRI is everything and nothing in many

00:44:54.560 --> 00:45:01.000
[Guest]: ways, is that you need to be able to find new markets, you need to diversify your markets,

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:05.760
[Guest]: you need to be able to shift capacity from China, economic capacity from China to other

00:45:05.760 --> 00:45:09.600
[Guest]: places while ensuring that you don't necessarily lose jobs.

00:45:09.600 --> 00:45:13.660
[Guest]: And in that process, you need to also create China as a consumer market because the economy

00:45:13.660 --> 00:45:15.440
[Guest]: needs to grow through consumption.

00:45:15.440 --> 00:45:18.320
[Guest]: So therefore, the manufacturing also needs to shift somewhere else because you're also

00:45:18.320 --> 00:45:21.760
[Guest]: dealing with issues of rising wage, labor costs and those sorts of things.

00:45:21.760 --> 00:45:24.560
[Guest]: So all of these objectives are what define BRI.

00:45:24.560 --> 00:45:30.080
[Guest]: One of the other objectives of BRI is to ensure that China's energy needs are met and its

00:45:30.080 --> 00:45:35.480
[Guest]: energy sources are diversified, because there's a lot of fear over the years, there's been

00:45:35.480 --> 00:45:40.840
[Guest]: lots of fear about the sea lanes of communication being blockaded in case of conflict.

00:45:40.840 --> 00:45:44.600
[Guest]: And that as a vulnerability has also led to some thought of, well, we need to develop

00:45:44.600 --> 00:45:47.480
[Guest]: pipelines and land routes, which are better.

00:45:47.480 --> 00:45:51.800
[Guest]: So a number of domestic objectives, but the primary domestic objective is to ensure that

00:45:51.800 --> 00:45:53.600
[Guest]: the party sustains.

00:45:53.600 --> 00:45:58.400
[Guest]: And the argument that Xi Jinping supporters will give you is that the corruption campaign

00:45:58.400 --> 00:46:03.960
[Guest]: and the rest of it, the political persecution, has been a lot about ensuring that the party

00:46:03.960 --> 00:46:08.480
[Guest]: survives because the party had become so corrupt and venal that it was extremely difficult

00:46:08.480 --> 00:46:09.480
[Guest]: for it to survive.

00:46:09.480 --> 00:46:12.280
[Guest]: It was losing legitimacy among the public.

00:46:12.280 --> 00:46:17.300
[Guest]: And therefore, you had to do something like this in order to create that sense of legitimacy.

00:46:17.300 --> 00:46:21.440
[Guest]: The nationalism that he's further stirred, because Xi Jinping talks a lot about the century

00:46:21.440 --> 00:46:26.880
[Guest]: of humiliation, and he talks a lot about Chinese national rejuvenation, which is his predominant

00:46:26.880 --> 00:46:27.880
[Guest]: objective.

00:46:27.880 --> 00:46:31.760
[Guest]: It all sort of harks back to this idea that we were once a great power, we've lost our

00:46:31.760 --> 00:46:33.520
[Guest]: way and we are now finding a way.

00:46:33.520 --> 00:46:39.080
[Guest]: And the only way for us to head in that direction of becoming this massive international power

00:46:39.080 --> 00:46:41.800
[Guest]: is by the leadership of the Communist Party.

00:46:41.800 --> 00:46:46.760
[Guest]: And therefore, he puts his record in front of you saying that in 70 years of the Communist

00:46:46.760 --> 00:46:51.240
[Guest]: Party's rule, we've seen a record number of people being lifted out of poverty.

00:46:51.240 --> 00:46:53.400
[Guest]: We've seen China's national power increase.

00:46:53.400 --> 00:46:57.440
[Guest]: So a lot of this also, when you're sort of expressing yourself at the international stage,

00:46:57.440 --> 00:47:03.520
[Guest]: is a signal to your domestic constituency that this is what we have achieved, that today

00:47:03.520 --> 00:47:05.960
[Guest]: we have a say at that table.

00:47:05.960 --> 00:47:07.520
[Guest]: Previously, nobody cared.

00:47:07.520 --> 00:47:11.600
[Guest]: We were a poor country, but today we've grown and we've grown because the party has been

00:47:11.600 --> 00:47:12.600
[Guest]: unified.

00:47:12.600 --> 00:47:17.440
[Guest]: So the domestic drivers of his foreign policy are predominantly these, in terms of his own

00:47:17.440 --> 00:47:19.660
[Guest]: sense of his own history.

00:47:19.660 --> 00:47:24.440
[Guest]: He brings that into play on occasion when he talks about...

00:47:24.440 --> 00:47:29.440
[Guest]: So just in the last year, you had lots of celebrations leading up to the 70th anniversary

00:47:29.440 --> 00:47:32.680
[Guest]: of the PRC, which was on October 1st.

00:47:32.680 --> 00:47:38.220
[Guest]: You had lots of museums which were hosting sort of exhibitions, and you could see that

00:47:38.220 --> 00:47:44.400
[Guest]: Xi Jinping's father was prominently displayed, particularly at the National Museum in Beijing.

00:47:44.400 --> 00:47:49.000
[Guest]: And his role in leading economic reform in the 1990s was played up.

00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:51.760
[Guest]: Because often when we talk about Deng Xiaoping, we forget about some of the other people who

00:47:51.760 --> 00:47:54.680
[Guest]: came in the picture and who led some of these things.

00:47:54.680 --> 00:47:58.680
[Guest]: And Xi Jinping's father's work in Southern China was extremely important to kick-starting

00:47:58.680 --> 00:48:02.680
[Guest]: economic reform in the 1990s after what happened in Tiananmen Square.

00:48:02.680 --> 00:48:04.760
[Guest]: And that was prominently displayed.

00:48:04.760 --> 00:48:09.560
[Guest]: This idea of him being a princeling, not necessarily a princeling in the context of somebody who

00:48:09.560 --> 00:48:13.960
[Guest]: comes from a well-off background, but somebody who has deep connections with the party's

00:48:13.960 --> 00:48:17.760
[Guest]: original aspirations, is played out quite frequently.

00:48:17.760 --> 00:48:19.280
[Guest]: Because Xi Jinping does this, right?

00:48:19.280 --> 00:48:23.720
[Guest]: So in the last one year, you've seen him repeatedly talk about an education program across not

00:48:23.720 --> 00:48:29.720
[Guest]: just society, but also the party, about upholding and reaffirming our original aspirations.

00:48:29.720 --> 00:48:32.920
[Guest]: Remember the original aspiration of the Communist Party.

00:48:32.920 --> 00:48:38.680
[Guest]: And him going to these old Communist Party foundation sites and paying homage is basically

00:48:38.680 --> 00:48:43.920
[Guest]: signaling that I am in line with these ancestors, with these guys who came in the past.

00:48:43.920 --> 00:48:47.000
[Guest]: I am a man of history who understands this.

00:48:47.000 --> 00:48:50.280
[Guest]: And this is my historic mission that China has stood up.

00:48:50.280 --> 00:48:51.560
[Guest]: It has grown rich.

00:48:51.560 --> 00:48:54.240
[Guest]: And today, under me, it will grow strong.

00:48:54.240 --> 00:48:58.060
[Guest]: And that's where we can gauge how he sees his place in history, right?

00:48:58.060 --> 00:49:03.120
[Amit Varma]: And is it fair to say that in the last few years, as China has grown economically and

00:49:03.120 --> 00:49:07.040
[Amit Varma]: as markets have functioned there within the parameters set for them, and people have been

00:49:07.040 --> 00:49:13.400
[Amit Varma]: empowered within those parameters, is it also fair to say that, one, the party has also

00:49:13.400 --> 00:49:19.160
[Amit Varma]: grown stronger within China, and two, that Xi himself has grown stronger within the party?

00:49:19.160 --> 00:49:23.560
[Guest]: Yeah, so the bit about the party growing stronger in China is a little bit of a tricky question,

00:49:23.560 --> 00:49:28.240
[Guest]: because in many ways, the party's reach has expanded, whether the legitimacy expanded

00:49:28.240 --> 00:49:29.240
[Guest]: is another issue.

00:49:29.240 --> 00:49:31.000
[Guest]: The reach has definitely expanded.

00:49:31.000 --> 00:49:33.560
[Guest]: So Xi Jinping has made sure that the party now is supreme.

00:49:33.560 --> 00:49:38.820
[Guest]: I mean, in his speech at the 19th Party Congress, which is a five yearly meeting of the leadership

00:49:38.820 --> 00:49:42.560
[Guest]: of the party across the country, one of the things that he said was that the party sort

00:49:42.560 --> 00:49:47.480
[Guest]: of, I'm paraphrasing, but essentially what he said was that the party sort of has control

00:49:47.480 --> 00:49:50.400
[Guest]: over all corners, the North, East, South and West.

00:49:50.400 --> 00:49:54.880
[Guest]: Essentially, he emphasizes the primacy of the party over the primacy of the state, which

00:49:54.880 --> 00:49:59.640
[Guest]: in many ways is sort of a slight bit of a shift from what was happening since Deng Xiaoping's

00:49:59.640 --> 00:50:00.640
[Guest]: reform started.

00:50:00.640 --> 00:50:05.460
[Guest]: Under Deng Xiaoping's reform, you were trying to create a division between the party and

00:50:05.460 --> 00:50:08.160
[Guest]: state while maintaining certain linkages.

00:50:08.160 --> 00:50:12.600
[Guest]: The division was a state acts as an executionary authority, which executes things, which does

00:50:12.600 --> 00:50:17.320
[Guest]: things professionally, whereas the party pursues ideology, some degree of control and those

00:50:17.320 --> 00:50:18.320
[Guest]: sorts of things.

00:50:18.320 --> 00:50:22.800
[Guest]: But you wanted to create more professionalism as opposed to more ideologically driven operations.

00:50:22.800 --> 00:50:30.440
[Guest]: Under Xi Jinping, he started to sort of remove that bit of linkage, that bit of discrimination.

00:50:30.440 --> 00:50:33.840
[Guest]: He started to create a linkage, deeper linkage between the party and the state.

00:50:33.840 --> 00:50:38.000
[Guest]: So more party organs now take care of more state institutions.

00:50:38.000 --> 00:50:42.720
[Guest]: Xi Jinping himself sort of commands a number of central leading groups, which end up creating

00:50:42.720 --> 00:50:45.120
[Guest]: policy, which the state then implements.

00:50:45.120 --> 00:50:50.440
[Guest]: So the state from being a policy actor in many ways has been increasingly reduced to

00:50:50.440 --> 00:50:52.000
[Guest]: just an executor.

00:50:52.000 --> 00:50:56.360
[Guest]: Under Deng Xiaoping's reform, the state had some role to play in policy formation, policy

00:50:56.360 --> 00:50:58.000
[Guest]: acting, state institutions were doing that.

00:50:58.000 --> 00:51:02.880
[Guest]: Today, the state is far less important in that sense, and the party is far more important.

00:51:02.880 --> 00:51:05.760
[Guest]: His control in that sense has increased, but not just at the state level.

00:51:05.760 --> 00:51:10.080
[Guest]: But if you look at, say, private enterprises, under Xi Jinping, there's been a greater focus

00:51:10.080 --> 00:51:13.640
[Guest]: on establishing party cells in private enterprises.

00:51:13.640 --> 00:51:18.400
[Guest]: Party cells always existed, but their role was sort of acting as this sort of liaising

00:51:18.400 --> 00:51:23.080
[Guest]: authority between a private company and the government and sort of the political leadership.

00:51:23.080 --> 00:51:29.400
[Guest]: If you think of it at a, say, local city level, I'm a private company's CEO, I run a technology

00:51:29.400 --> 00:51:34.960
[Guest]: business, and it's useful for me to have a party cell because it can help me get some

00:51:34.960 --> 00:51:39.240
[Guest]: sort of political patronage within my local government and that sort of things.

00:51:39.240 --> 00:51:44.280
[Guest]: But increasingly, that was the role that they were traditionally performing, trying to build

00:51:44.280 --> 00:51:48.760
[Guest]: certain party building activities and act as a link between the party and enterprises.

00:51:48.760 --> 00:51:53.240
[Guest]: But increasingly, there has been effort to change the articles of association of companies

00:51:53.240 --> 00:51:57.160
[Guest]: to make sure that the party cells have far more decision-making role to play in these

00:51:57.160 --> 00:51:58.160
[Guest]: companies.

00:51:58.160 --> 00:52:00.440
[Guest]: They provide guidance and direction far more.

00:52:00.440 --> 00:52:03.520
[Guest]: And that sort of led to some degree of backlash internationally also.

00:52:03.520 --> 00:52:08.000
[Guest]: Today, this conversation that we see around Huawei and Chinese private companies being

00:52:08.000 --> 00:52:13.080
[Guest]: state actors essentially has to do with this assertion that Xi Jinping has made where the

00:52:13.080 --> 00:52:16.960
[Guest]: party cells have become far more active in private enterprises.

00:52:16.960 --> 00:52:21.320
[Guest]: Across society also, yes, you will have party groupings, party meetings, and they've become

00:52:21.320 --> 00:52:24.480
[Guest]: far more ideological, far more active in that sense.

00:52:24.480 --> 00:52:27.920
[Guest]: So in that sense, yes, the party has regained far more control.

00:52:27.920 --> 00:52:31.160
[Guest]: It's become far stronger, far more rejuvenated.

00:52:31.160 --> 00:52:36.940
[Guest]: But the issue is, can this sense of centralized rejuvenation of the party and reaffirmation

00:52:36.940 --> 00:52:41.280
[Guest]: of ideology really enthuse your grassroots workers?

00:52:41.280 --> 00:52:42.960
[Guest]: It's not necessarily the case, right?

00:52:42.960 --> 00:52:47.840
[Guest]: Because there's an old saying in China, which is, the heaven is high above and the emperor

00:52:47.840 --> 00:52:49.700
[Guest]: is far away.

00:52:49.700 --> 00:52:53.640
[Guest]: And therefore, it tells you that people at grassroots level, at provincial levels, at

00:52:53.640 --> 00:52:58.680
[Guest]: village levels, at district levels, you realize that, well, yes, okay, he wants me to do some

00:52:58.680 --> 00:53:03.440
[Guest]: of these things and he's pushing for this, and this is the party's direction and guidance,

00:53:03.440 --> 00:53:04.480
[Guest]: but I have my interests.

00:53:04.480 --> 00:53:10.240
[Guest]: So therefore, you get things like data being faked, you get information being misreported.

00:53:10.240 --> 00:53:14.520
[Guest]: And therefore, if you see, often the central leadership of the party sends a lot of inspection

00:53:14.520 --> 00:53:16.080
[Guest]: teams around the country.

00:53:16.080 --> 00:53:20.520
[Guest]: So on things like pollution, on things like business report, business data, on things

00:53:20.520 --> 00:53:24.700
[Guest]: like whether certain policies of central government have been implemented, you have constantly

00:53:24.700 --> 00:53:30.680
[Guest]: inspection teams from the central leadership going across the country and conducting inspections.

00:53:30.680 --> 00:53:33.560
[Guest]: You wouldn't need to do that if everything was functioning so smoothly and everybody

00:53:33.560 --> 00:53:37.240
[Guest]: was so ideologically and interest-wise aligned.

00:53:37.240 --> 00:53:41.820
[Guest]: And repeatedly, if you look at Xi Jinping's speeches on domestic politics, he is constantly

00:53:41.820 --> 00:53:46.640
[Guest]: talking about the need for party branches across all levels to follow the bottom line

00:53:46.640 --> 00:53:48.760
[Guest]: and the unified leadership of the central leadership.

00:53:48.760 --> 00:53:52.280
[Guest]: The reason that you emphasize it again and again is because it's not happening.

00:53:52.280 --> 00:53:54.240
[Guest]: And that's a challenge for him.

00:53:54.240 --> 00:53:55.240
[Guest]: But that's his objective, right?

00:53:55.240 --> 00:54:00.600
[Guest]: To expand central control, to ensure that the party becomes stronger than the state,

00:54:00.600 --> 00:54:07.040
[Guest]: which it has, and also to expand the party's reach beyond its traditional spheres of influence.

00:54:07.040 --> 00:54:12.200
[Amit Varma]: And on the question of foreign policy, would it be fair to say that while he is more assertive

00:54:12.200 --> 00:54:18.040
[Amit Varma]: of, you know, China's interests and so on, it is also the case that he sees the world

00:54:18.040 --> 00:54:23.000
[Amit Varma]: not in a zero-sum way as some geopolitical actors might see it as, for example, the US

00:54:23.000 --> 00:54:27.240
[Amit Varma]: President Trump certainly seems to see it, but in a more non-zero-sum way that, you know,

00:54:27.240 --> 00:54:28.240
[Amit Varma]: let's help each other.

00:54:28.240 --> 00:54:29.240
[Amit Varma]: We can all grow.

00:54:29.240 --> 00:54:30.240
[Amit Varma]: This is what we want.

00:54:30.240 --> 00:54:31.240
[Amit Varma]: We can all do this.

00:54:31.240 --> 00:54:32.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, we get what we want.

00:54:32.240 --> 00:54:34.800
[Amit Varma]: We'll try to help you along the way as well.

00:54:34.800 --> 00:54:36.920
[Amit Varma]: Is that sort of more of how he sees the world?

00:54:36.920 --> 00:54:41.000
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, I think Chinese foreign policy, when you compare him to Donald Trump, of course,

00:54:41.000 --> 00:54:42.000
[Guest]: he's a saint.

00:54:42.000 --> 00:54:43.000
[Guest]: He's far more nuanced.

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:46.720
[Guest]: But he's far more thoughtful, far more nuanced.

00:54:46.720 --> 00:54:50.040
[Guest]: And his approach has been far more adaptable in many ways.

00:54:50.040 --> 00:54:53.480
[Guest]: So if you look at India's relationship with China or China's relationship with Japan over

00:54:53.480 --> 00:54:59.720
[Guest]: the last six, seven years, there was a steady downward trend until things with the US and

00:54:59.720 --> 00:55:02.920
[Guest]: China became far more prickly.

00:55:02.920 --> 00:55:04.200
[Guest]: And then you see China adapt.

00:55:04.200 --> 00:55:05.880
[Guest]: It's adapting to its neighbors.

00:55:05.880 --> 00:55:08.520
[Guest]: It's starting to become much more softer.

00:55:08.520 --> 00:55:13.640
[Guest]: Its foreign policy rhetoric is constantly about win-win relationships and denying the

00:55:13.640 --> 00:55:15.760
[Guest]: Cold War mentality.

00:55:15.760 --> 00:55:17.600
[Guest]: To me, that's a lot of rhetoric.

00:55:17.600 --> 00:55:24.240
[Guest]: There is a sense of win-win broadly means, yes, you can win, but I must win more.

00:55:24.240 --> 00:55:26.400
[Guest]: And that's how it usually functions.

00:55:26.400 --> 00:55:29.600
[Guest]: And it's very cognizant of the fact that it's a large player.

00:55:29.600 --> 00:55:32.720
[Guest]: So there is some strand of thought in China which talks about the fact that, look, as

00:55:32.720 --> 00:55:39.160
[Guest]: a growing power, we need to also be far more cognizant of the fact that we can't be only

00:55:39.160 --> 00:55:40.160
[Guest]: winning all the time.

00:55:40.160 --> 00:55:43.400
[Guest]: There are times where we need to be a little bit more benevolent in our approach.

00:55:43.400 --> 00:55:45.880
[Guest]: And there are times where we need to give on some things.

00:55:45.880 --> 00:55:50.560
[Guest]: But it's really difficult given the sort of mercantilist sort of culture, where you're

00:55:50.560 --> 00:55:54.220
[Guest]: looking at gaining much more from each transaction.

00:55:54.220 --> 00:55:58.160
[Guest]: If you look at the belt in the road over the last couple of years, what you will see is

00:55:58.160 --> 00:56:00.400
[Guest]: that there are two strands of conversation.

00:56:00.400 --> 00:56:05.480
[Guest]: One is about China's trapping people in debt, trapping states in debt in order to then extract

00:56:05.480 --> 00:56:09.000
[Guest]: strategic or geopolitical advantages, geopolitical concessions.

00:56:09.000 --> 00:56:12.040
[Guest]: Humber and Toto is one example that people will keep talking about.

00:56:12.040 --> 00:56:15.840
[Guest]: The other strand of thought is that, well, you might have given all this debt and the

00:56:15.840 --> 00:56:17.560
[Guest]: state has to pay you back so much.

00:56:17.560 --> 00:56:22.160
[Guest]: But what if the state doesn't pay you back and then drills up nationalism to say that,

00:56:22.160 --> 00:56:26.600
[Guest]: you know, we're not giving back territory, we're not doing this.

00:56:26.600 --> 00:56:30.000
[Guest]: And given the sort of pushback that some of the things are happening, what is your negotiating

00:56:30.000 --> 00:56:31.560
[Guest]: capacity with that state?

00:56:31.560 --> 00:56:35.200
[Guest]: And in many cases, what we've seen, particularly in Africa, is that the Chinese have had to

00:56:35.200 --> 00:56:37.500
[Guest]: undergo debt restructuring again and again.

00:56:37.500 --> 00:56:40.640
[Guest]: And they've had to sort of forgive and let go of certain amount of debt.

00:56:40.640 --> 00:56:42.280
[Guest]: They've had to restructure certain debt.

00:56:42.280 --> 00:56:46.580
[Guest]: They've had to expand time periods for loan payments while forgiving certain percentages.

00:56:46.580 --> 00:56:52.320
[Guest]: So the question of what their capacity would be and whether they are looking at singularly

00:56:52.320 --> 00:56:57.260
[Guest]: I win and you lose or whether they're looking at partnerships in which they can also gain

00:56:57.260 --> 00:57:01.000
[Guest]: in the long term is to be sort of seriously thought about.

00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:04.280
[Guest]: And to my knowledge, to my understanding, the Chinese are looking at it from a long

00:57:04.280 --> 00:57:05.280
[Guest]: term point of view.

00:57:05.280 --> 00:57:08.560
[Guest]: They're looking at, you know, their investments abroad.

00:57:08.560 --> 00:57:11.360
[Guest]: They're looking at, you know, BRI.

00:57:11.360 --> 00:57:14.600
[Guest]: They're looking at their competition with the US from a long term perspective.

00:57:14.600 --> 00:57:18.720
[Guest]: In that, you will be making tactical shifts, you will be making short term adjustments.

00:57:18.720 --> 00:57:22.920
[Guest]: But you're looking at a long term perspective saying that if we need to establish our sort

00:57:22.920 --> 00:57:28.640
[Guest]: of presence across this broader Asia Pacific to begin with, and then going forward globally,

00:57:28.640 --> 00:57:31.640
[Guest]: caution we need to act with a certain degree of sense.

00:57:31.640 --> 00:57:34.720
[Guest]: And in that they've made a lot of mistakes.

00:57:34.720 --> 00:57:36.960
[Guest]: So Huawei is a particular mistake.

00:57:36.960 --> 00:57:41.240
[Guest]: The focus on Communist Party sales in private companies is a particular mistake.

00:57:41.240 --> 00:57:44.280
[Guest]: And it's a far more aggressive diplomatic attitude.

00:57:44.280 --> 00:57:48.160
[Guest]: Chinese diplomats have become some of the most brutish individuals in the diplomatic

00:57:48.160 --> 00:57:55.360
[Guest]: community, whether it was the former DCM in Pakistan, who took to very sort of very limited

00:57:55.360 --> 00:57:59.680
[Guest]: Twitter diplomacy, or the former ambassador to Canada, who in the case of this Huawei

00:57:59.680 --> 00:58:05.080
[Guest]: CFO had been particularly harsh, particularly undiplomatic in his language, or others, they've

00:58:05.080 --> 00:58:08.280
[Guest]: been changed, their attitude has changed to becoming far more aggressive.

00:58:08.280 --> 00:58:11.680
[Guest]: I'm not saying that they wouldn't see it as zero sum, there are certain places where you

00:58:11.680 --> 00:58:13.080
[Guest]: see it as zero sum.

00:58:13.080 --> 00:58:17.080
[Guest]: But the long term vision is that we need to be doing things to expand our presence, our

00:58:17.080 --> 00:58:22.680
[Guest]: scope of interest and our capacity to deal with challenges around the world.

00:58:22.680 --> 00:58:25.440
[Guest]: Because our interests are now truly global.

00:58:25.440 --> 00:58:28.720
[Guest]: And in that you will see times where they've made serious mistakes.

00:58:28.720 --> 00:58:31.940
[Guest]: So during Doklam, they've made serious mistakes with India.

00:58:31.940 --> 00:58:34.120
