[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to The Scene and The Yancey.

01:00:49.160 --> 01:00:53.720
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Manoj Kevalramani on the question of what does China want and specifically

01:00:53.720 --> 01:00:57.080
[Amit Varma]: what India-China relations are like.

01:00:57.080 --> 01:01:01.200
[Amit Varma]: And Manoj, I guess it's only meaningful to talk of India-China relationships from the

01:01:01.200 --> 01:01:03.520
[Amit Varma]: time that India actually existed.

01:01:03.520 --> 01:01:09.000
[Amit Varma]: So shall we sort of go back to independence and talk about the contrasting approaches

01:01:09.000 --> 01:01:14.920
[Amit Varma]: of Vallabhbhai Patel and Jawaharlal Nehru to foreign policy, where Patel was more a

01:01:14.920 --> 01:01:19.960
[Amit Varma]: practical, real politic kind of guy and Nehru was sort of not.

01:01:19.960 --> 01:01:22.640
[Amit Varma]: Can you sort of elaborate on the differences between the two?

01:01:22.640 --> 01:01:26.760
[Guest]: Yeah, so I mean, if you look at how India and China both became, you know, how we became

01:01:26.760 --> 01:01:31.800
[Guest]: the Republic of India and how they became the People's Republic of China.

01:01:31.800 --> 01:01:38.040
[Guest]: China sort of emerges from a very violent, India also has deep violence, but the violence

01:01:38.040 --> 01:01:41.440
[Guest]: is different as compared to the Chinese violence.

01:01:41.440 --> 01:01:45.960
[Guest]: In China, you see that the Communist Party takes charge and it sort of comes to power

01:01:45.960 --> 01:01:49.400
[Guest]: with the barrel of the gun through a civil war, apart from all the colonialism.

01:01:49.400 --> 01:01:54.440
[Guest]: There is a civil war which leads to the Communist Party taking charge with a very clear ideology

01:01:54.440 --> 01:01:55.440
[Guest]: of communism.

01:01:55.440 --> 01:02:00.320
[Guest]: In contrast, in India, you do have some sort of a civil war in some senses, but it's a

01:02:00.320 --> 01:02:04.040
[Guest]: little bit different and the violence that you see is based out of partition.

01:02:04.040 --> 01:02:05.920
[Guest]: You get divided into two countries.

01:02:05.920 --> 01:02:10.520
[Guest]: And but yet, when you see the Indian government, it's sort of under Jawaharlal Nehru, we see

01:02:10.520 --> 01:02:12.980
[Guest]: ourselves as an international power.

01:02:12.980 --> 01:02:17.120
[Guest]: And we see ourselves as an international power, not just from the point of view of our size

01:02:17.120 --> 01:02:21.400
[Guest]: and our capacity, but also in the sense of how we got our independence.

01:02:21.400 --> 01:02:29.200
[Guest]: The idea of the Indian independence movement being an example, a methodology that others

01:02:29.200 --> 01:02:35.120
[Guest]: can emulate across the world as decolonization begins to happen is something which is deeply

01:02:35.120 --> 01:02:36.720
[Guest]: ideological for India.

01:02:36.720 --> 01:02:39.720
[Guest]: And we seek to even in some ways export that.

01:02:39.720 --> 01:02:44.880
[Guest]: We sort of talk about this idea that India provides this non-aligned idea eventually,

01:02:44.880 --> 01:02:51.360
[Guest]: but eventually this anti-colonialism, anti-imperialistic idea of India, which is deeply rooted in our

01:02:51.360 --> 01:02:53.720
[Guest]: culture and Gandhi and values and so on and so forth.

01:02:53.720 --> 01:02:55.400
[Guest]: Ahimsa, Satyagraha and whatever.

01:02:55.400 --> 01:03:01.080
[Guest]: In comparison, in China, you see the notion that strength, the gun is extremely, extremely

01:03:01.080 --> 01:03:02.080
[Guest]: important.

01:03:02.080 --> 01:03:04.840
[Guest]: So there's a slight divide in firstly how we approach these things.

01:03:04.840 --> 01:03:09.760
[Guest]: Secondly, the fact that, like I said in the previous bit of our conversation, that the

01:03:09.760 --> 01:03:15.840
[Guest]: Chinese view India with deep suspicion because they view the modern Indian state as a successor

01:03:15.840 --> 01:03:19.320
[Guest]: of the British rule in the region.

01:03:19.320 --> 01:03:24.320
[Guest]: And therefore, they have the sense that the state is firstly of capitalistic origin with

01:03:24.320 --> 01:03:30.240
[Guest]: leaders who are capitalist in their mindset and leaders who are also keen on expanding

01:03:30.240 --> 01:03:37.200
[Guest]: a hegemonic presence, whether it be by annexing territory, but expanding the kingdom, expanding

01:03:37.200 --> 01:03:39.320
[Guest]: the British Raj essentially going forward.

01:03:39.320 --> 01:03:41.440
[Guest]: But the name today is the Republic of India.

01:03:41.440 --> 01:03:44.400
[Guest]: And that's their deep suspicion that they harbor.

01:03:44.400 --> 01:03:47.960
[Guest]: In contrast, India harbors a mixed sort of approach towards China.

01:03:47.960 --> 01:03:50.760
[Guest]: So Nehru is realist in many ways.

01:03:50.760 --> 01:03:51.760
[Guest]: He's a realist.

01:03:51.760 --> 01:03:55.720
[Guest]: He also sees the fact that there is a state system internationally and the Chinese are

01:03:55.720 --> 01:03:56.920
[Guest]: along our borders.

01:03:56.920 --> 01:04:01.680
[Guest]: But he also has this fundamental sense of Asian civilization and Asian solidarity.

01:04:01.680 --> 01:04:05.400
[Guest]: And even before India becomes independent, we hold this Asian Relations Conference.

01:04:05.400 --> 01:04:09.240
[Guest]: And if you listen to Nehru's speech in that conference, it's not a wishy-washy ideologue

01:04:09.240 --> 01:04:15.440
[Guest]: who's saying things like Hindi-Chini Bhai Bhai or the Asian civilization is one and together.

01:04:15.440 --> 01:04:19.640
[Guest]: He's essentially leveraging that to pitch India as a leader in the region.

01:04:19.640 --> 01:04:24.600
[Guest]: And he's obviously in that speech, he's recognizing the fact that there is a state system, there

01:04:24.600 --> 01:04:29.200
[Guest]: are state interests, there are different civilizational appeals within the region, and there is a

01:04:29.200 --> 01:04:30.600
[Guest]: sense of conflict also.

01:04:30.600 --> 01:04:33.720
[Guest]: Yet, there is a broader thing that brings us together.

01:04:33.720 --> 01:04:39.160
[Guest]: So he's not completely ignorant of the fact that there are strands of conflict.

01:04:39.160 --> 01:04:42.920
[Guest]: And history has told us that Nehru, while he believed in certain things, he was also

01:04:42.920 --> 01:04:43.920
[Guest]: a realist.

01:04:43.920 --> 01:04:48.160
[Guest]: The distinction between Nehru and Patel comes from the fact that Patel saw the world far

01:04:48.160 --> 01:04:49.160
[Guest]: more differently.

01:04:49.160 --> 01:04:53.600
[Guest]: Once the PRC, once the Chinese sort of army, the People's Liberation Army moves into Tibet

01:04:53.600 --> 01:04:57.440
[Guest]: first in 1950, Patel is extremely worried about that.

01:04:57.440 --> 01:04:59.240
[Guest]: He's extremely concerned about that.

01:04:59.240 --> 01:05:03.600
[Guest]: And because with that, he sees a fundamental alteration of geography.

01:05:03.600 --> 01:05:09.160
[Guest]: He sees the buffer of Tibet, which was essentially a buffer state, going away, and he sees the

01:05:09.160 --> 01:05:11.360
[Guest]: Chinese now at our doorstep.

01:05:11.360 --> 01:05:15.560
[Guest]: And Patel is very suspicious of that, because he's a hard-nosed realist who believes that

01:05:15.560 --> 01:05:19.280
[Guest]: India needs to be pursuing its interests as opposed to looking at cooperation in this

01:05:19.280 --> 01:05:20.280
[Guest]: sense.

01:05:20.280 --> 01:05:23.000
[Guest]: You can work with partners, but you have certain core interests, and security is fundamental

01:05:23.000 --> 01:05:24.000
[Guest]: to that.

01:05:24.000 --> 01:05:28.000
[Guest]: And that comes a lot with the job that he's done leading soon into independence and after

01:05:28.000 --> 01:05:30.440
[Guest]: that very sort of integrating states and looking at that.

01:05:30.440 --> 01:05:35.400
[Guest]: And that sort of plays out in his perception of China, where he talks about China being

01:05:35.400 --> 01:05:37.360
[Guest]: a potential threat to India.

01:05:37.360 --> 01:05:40.360
[Guest]: And he sort of warns Nehru in a letter that he says that, you know, we've never really

01:05:40.360 --> 01:05:43.360
[Guest]: faced the Chinese directly on our border.

01:05:43.360 --> 01:05:49.400
[Guest]: The Himalayas have always been this barrier that have prevented civilizations from clashing.

01:05:49.400 --> 01:05:52.760
[Guest]: And therefore, that barrier today seems to go away.

01:05:52.760 --> 01:05:56.080
[Guest]: And this is going to be problematic for us going forward in the future.

01:05:56.080 --> 01:05:59.360
[Guest]: And that's quite a visionary thing to say at that point of time.

01:05:59.360 --> 01:06:03.640
[Guest]: Nehru believes that there is ways that we can work with the Chinese together.

01:06:03.640 --> 01:06:09.000
[Guest]: And in that, he is taken in by some of the ideas of Asian solidarity.

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:11.760
[Guest]: And that's predominantly because he's looking at this outside world and he's looking at

01:06:11.760 --> 01:06:13.520
[Guest]: India as a model externally.

01:06:13.520 --> 01:06:17.360
[Guest]: He sort of ignores the immediate threat that could develop.

01:06:17.360 --> 01:06:22.360
[Guest]: And because you've ignored the understanding of China or the Chinese leadership of India,

01:06:22.360 --> 01:06:26.680
[Guest]: if you had a deeper sense of what the Chinese actually think about or thought about the

01:06:26.680 --> 01:06:31.000
[Guest]: Indian administration at that point of time, you'd have probably been far more circumspect

01:06:31.000 --> 01:06:35.680
[Guest]: in not cooperating with them, but at least recognizing the fact that there is a distinct

01:06:35.680 --> 01:06:42.480
[Guest]: threat that they pose because they view you with hostility, because they view you fundamentally

01:06:42.480 --> 01:06:43.480
[Guest]: as problematic.

01:06:43.480 --> 01:06:47.560
[Guest]: The value based proposition of the Republic of India, led by the Congress Party at that

01:06:47.560 --> 01:06:49.560
[Guest]: point of time, was seen as problematic.

01:06:49.560 --> 01:06:53.480
[Guest]: So I think that's where the sort of essential break happens.

01:06:53.480 --> 01:06:56.120
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you were talking about how China sort of viewed India.

01:06:56.120 --> 01:07:00.520
[Amit Varma]: And it's very interesting in Gawor's book, I came across another excerpt, which I'll

01:07:00.520 --> 01:07:07.640
[Amit Varma]: just read out, quote, an authoritative classified 1990 Chinese study of the 1962 war trace that

01:07:07.640 --> 01:07:13.080
[Amit Varma]: conflict to Nehru's assimilation of the British imperialist mentality and strategy.

01:07:13.080 --> 01:07:17.680
[Amit Varma]: Nehru's core ambition was to establish a greater Indian empire within the realm of the old

01:07:17.680 --> 01:07:20.880
[Amit Varma]: British Empire and stretching from South East Asia to the Middle East.

01:07:20.880 --> 01:07:25.680
[Amit Varma]: Afghanistan, Burma and Tibet were to be buffers within this imperial framework.

01:07:25.680 --> 01:07:29.760
[Amit Varma]: The countries around India were to become subservient to Indian power.

01:07:29.760 --> 01:07:34.800
[Amit Varma]: Indian security strategy under Nehru was premised on achieving this empire's stop quote.

01:07:34.800 --> 01:07:36.320
[Amit Varma]: And this is obviously not true.

01:07:36.320 --> 01:07:39.800
[Amit Varma]: I mean, Nehru definitely did not have this imperialist mindset.

01:07:39.800 --> 01:07:45.160
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you know, if anything, it was the sort of the opposite.

01:07:45.160 --> 01:07:50.160
[Amit Varma]: And in the context of how they obviously viewed him and they viewed India, it's sort of ironic

01:07:50.160 --> 01:07:55.560
[Amit Varma]: that his policy through the 50s after Patel died and that real politics sort of went away

01:07:55.560 --> 01:08:01.880
[Amit Varma]: has often been, you know, described as appeasement and how he's often been blamed for the 1962

01:08:01.880 --> 01:08:02.880
[Amit Varma]: war.

01:08:02.880 --> 01:08:04.160
[Amit Varma]: Can you elaborate a little bit on that?

01:08:04.160 --> 01:08:08.560
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, look, at the end of what was happening was that I mean, to me, yes, the

01:08:08.560 --> 01:08:14.360
[Guest]: Indian government has started realizing what was happening with China and Tibet.

01:08:14.360 --> 01:08:17.960
[Guest]: Despite whatever was being said and whatever was being done, there were these state visits

01:08:17.960 --> 01:08:23.600
[Guest]: that were happening with Zhou Enlai and Nehru talking about building a deeper relationship.

01:08:23.600 --> 01:08:25.760
[Guest]: And there was a lot of warmth.

01:08:25.760 --> 01:08:31.640
[Guest]: It was still, I don't think Nehru was completely, like I said, he was not cognizant that the

01:08:31.640 --> 01:08:32.960
[Guest]: Chinese pose a threat.

01:08:32.960 --> 01:08:35.720
[Guest]: It was just about the nature of threat and whether you can contain the threat.

01:08:35.720 --> 01:08:38.600
[Guest]: And I think that's where there were a couple of things, right?

01:08:38.600 --> 01:08:44.560
[Guest]: Nehru's forward policy leading up to the 1962 war was seen by the Chinese as provocative.

01:08:44.560 --> 01:08:45.560
[Guest]: That was one thing.

01:08:45.560 --> 01:08:48.720
[Guest]: The other thing was that there was a lack of understanding within India about domestic

01:08:48.720 --> 01:08:50.240
[Guest]: processes in Beijing.

01:08:50.240 --> 01:08:54.360
[Guest]: Ma Zedong was under tremendous pressure after the failure of the Great Leap Forward, which

01:08:54.360 --> 01:08:56.720
[Guest]: is 57-58 onwards.

01:08:56.720 --> 01:09:01.120
[Guest]: And that pressure had meant that he had been sidelined in the party, despite him being

01:09:01.120 --> 01:09:03.120
[Guest]: the tallest leader.

01:09:03.120 --> 01:09:07.320
[Guest]: And this was an opportunity for him to launch a conflict where the party would sort of rally

01:09:07.320 --> 01:09:10.360
[Guest]: behind him and he could sort of teach India a lesson.

01:09:10.360 --> 01:09:15.720
[Guest]: And this notion of teaching India a lesson comes from the fact that India is a pretender

01:09:15.720 --> 01:09:17.520
[Guest]: power in some ways.

01:09:17.520 --> 01:09:18.520
[Guest]: It's not a real power.

01:09:18.520 --> 01:09:24.320
[Guest]: It's this conglomeration of states which is pulled together with an imperialistic design.

01:09:24.320 --> 01:09:28.200
[Guest]: And this notion of this imperialistic Nehru or imperialistic Republic of India comes from

01:09:28.200 --> 01:09:32.440
[Guest]: the fact that while we became independent, we were also assimilating princely states

01:09:32.440 --> 01:09:34.600
[Guest]: and some of them we did by force.

01:09:34.600 --> 01:09:39.440
[Guest]: So all of this was read by the Chinese as seeing India as this imperialist power.

01:09:39.440 --> 01:09:42.840
[Guest]: Leading up to the conflict, essentially, yes, there was appeasement.

01:09:42.840 --> 01:09:45.760
[Guest]: I think we could have taken a much tougher position on the Chinese.

01:09:45.760 --> 01:09:50.760
[Guest]: But the question is, within the geopolitics of the time, what sort of a position could

01:09:50.760 --> 01:09:52.800
[Guest]: you have taken which would have been tougher?

01:09:52.800 --> 01:09:58.360
[Guest]: You adopted a policy to buttress your borders and that was seen as confrontational.

01:09:58.360 --> 01:10:02.400
[Guest]: The mistake to me was not necessarily the appeasement as what is defined as appeasement.

01:10:02.400 --> 01:10:07.760
[Guest]: The mistake to me in 1962 was in some ways, there was a fundamental belief that there

01:10:07.760 --> 01:10:13.280
[Guest]: would be no conflict because these two countries have a shared history of anti-colonialism,

01:10:13.280 --> 01:10:18.440
[Guest]: which was problematic firstly, because you did not recognize the strands of nationalism

01:10:18.440 --> 01:10:23.720
[Guest]: that and the strands of domestic political turmoil that were developing within China.

01:10:23.720 --> 01:10:28.000
[Guest]: The second mistake was not to actually focus on wartime preparation and to invest in that.

01:10:28.000 --> 01:10:33.620
[Guest]: And you can take that back to again this broader sense of conflict receding because colonialism

01:10:33.620 --> 01:10:37.920
[Guest]: is happening, things are changing, although the world may still be a volatile place and

01:10:37.920 --> 01:10:41.720
[Guest]: India having to sort of be a beacon of that hope in that sense.

01:10:41.720 --> 01:10:46.160
[Guest]: Then there were a couple of strands which led to that, but a lot of it to me leads down

01:10:46.160 --> 01:10:51.840
[Guest]: to a lack of understanding of Chinese domestic politics and the systems that were underplay,

01:10:51.840 --> 01:10:55.400
[Guest]: the sort of the pulls and pushes underplay within the Chinese system itself.

01:10:55.400 --> 01:10:58.160
[Guest]: I don't think it was appeasement which led to the conflict.

01:10:58.160 --> 01:10:59.880
[Guest]: The Chinese had very clear objectives.

01:10:59.880 --> 01:11:03.000
[Guest]: We just didn't understand those objectives.

01:11:03.000 --> 01:11:07.920
[Guest]: Because if the Chinese had territorial objectives, predominantly they walked back from most of

01:11:07.920 --> 01:11:09.280
[Guest]: the territory that they conquered.

01:11:09.280 --> 01:11:11.920
[Guest]: They kept some chunks, but they essentially walked back from most of it.

01:11:11.920 --> 01:11:16.400
[Guest]: So the objective was essentially like they said later on was to teach India a lesson.

01:11:16.400 --> 01:11:20.700
[Guest]: And that has a lot to do with Chinese perception of India back then.

01:11:20.700 --> 01:11:24.880
[Guest]: And some of those strands of perception continue even till today, although a lot has changed

01:11:24.880 --> 01:11:25.880
[Amit Varma]: since then.

01:11:25.880 --> 01:11:30.680
[Amit Varma]: And all of this, of course, is playing out in the geopolitical context of the Cold War,

01:11:30.680 --> 01:11:32.400
[Amit Varma]: which is also evolving.

01:11:32.400 --> 01:11:37.520
[Amit Varma]: Like the way sort of China was forced to look at the world was through this prism of, you

01:11:37.520 --> 01:11:43.960
[Amit Varma]: know, the communist versus the imperialist on one side, Soviet versus the USA, East versus

01:11:43.960 --> 01:11:44.960
[Amit Varma]: West.

01:11:44.960 --> 01:11:48.160
[Amit Varma]: And so it's a very bipolar kind of view of the world.

01:11:48.160 --> 01:11:51.800
[Amit Varma]: But India isn't exactly fitting into this framework because, you know, Nehru is trying

01:11:51.800 --> 01:11:54.960
[Amit Varma]: to be non-aligned and he's trying all of this other stuff.

01:11:54.960 --> 01:11:59.920
[Amit Varma]: And during this time in the 50s in China, also Koji's up to Pakistan.

01:11:59.920 --> 01:12:03.360
[Amit Varma]: How is all of that evolving during that period?

01:12:03.360 --> 01:12:07.960
[Guest]: So what you see at that point of time is that this is again one of these things which is

01:12:07.960 --> 01:12:12.720
[Guest]: often not remembered is that in the 1950s, China wasn't cozying up to Pakistan.

01:12:12.720 --> 01:12:14.280
[Guest]: China was cozying up to India.

01:12:14.280 --> 01:12:16.840
[Guest]: In fact, they were looking at some sort of and there was another standard of thought

01:12:16.840 --> 01:12:21.880
[Guest]: where Pakistan wanted to work with India in order to sort of balance China.

01:12:21.880 --> 01:12:24.720
[Guest]: So there were these multiple different strands of thought up in the air.

01:12:24.720 --> 01:12:26.720
[Guest]: There were lots of different things happening.

01:12:26.720 --> 01:12:29.420
[Guest]: For the Chinese, the broad perspective was this, right?

01:12:29.420 --> 01:12:35.000
[Guest]: You had just emerged from a brutal period to having a unified state again.

01:12:35.000 --> 01:12:38.600
[Guest]: In some of those things, in some of the further territories, you needed to still unify a lot

01:12:38.600 --> 01:12:39.600
[Guest]: of things.

01:12:39.600 --> 01:12:41.640
[Guest]: You need to conquer some lands also.

01:12:41.640 --> 01:12:45.320
[Guest]: You had a partner in the Soviet Union, but your partnership with the Soviet Union has

01:12:45.320 --> 01:12:50.840
[Guest]: started to increasingly become far more shaky from, say, the mid 50s going on till the Cultural

01:12:50.840 --> 01:12:52.520
[Guest]: Revolution is launched.

01:12:52.520 --> 01:12:57.240
[Guest]: And that starts to become your primary threat.

01:12:57.240 --> 01:13:02.160
[Guest]: And that threat in more than, say, the West, that becomes your primary threat.

01:13:02.160 --> 01:13:05.800
[Guest]: And in that, subsequently, you end up developing a partnership with the US.

01:13:05.800 --> 01:13:07.920
[Guest]: With regard to India, this is what you see, right?

01:13:07.920 --> 01:13:12.480
[Guest]: You see Asia, essentially, you begin to see Asia as your sphere of influence.

01:13:12.480 --> 01:13:16.080
[Guest]: And you see an active India as problematic in that sense.

01:13:16.080 --> 01:13:21.740
[Guest]: I don't think at that point in time, Mao Zedong really had this sense of broader Chinese domination

01:13:21.740 --> 01:13:22.740
[Guest]: over Asia.

01:13:22.740 --> 01:13:24.740
[Guest]: He was looking at consolidating the state that he'd got.

01:13:24.740 --> 01:13:26.760
[Guest]: He was looking at promoting revolution.

01:13:26.760 --> 01:13:31.480
[Guest]: He was looking at promoting an ideological foreign policy while keeping China intact.

01:13:31.480 --> 01:13:36.000
[Guest]: And in that sort of a sense, he starts to do things like supporting revolutionary movements

01:13:36.000 --> 01:13:38.520
[Guest]: in different parts of the world, even in India.

01:13:38.520 --> 01:13:44.680
[Guest]: So post the 1962 war also, through much of the Cold War, China supports a number of revolutionary

01:13:44.680 --> 01:13:50.400
[Guest]: Maoist terrorist movements in India, secessionist movements in India, through small arms, through

01:13:50.400 --> 01:13:51.400
[Guest]: training.

01:13:51.400 --> 01:13:53.600
[Guest]: A lot of it has to do with the northeast of India.

01:13:53.600 --> 01:13:58.040
[Guest]: And they work on this policy with India, because the idea is that you can't have two really

01:13:58.040 --> 01:14:00.640
[Guest]: strong powers dominating Asia.

01:14:00.640 --> 01:14:03.500
[Guest]: Japan is recovering from devastation.

01:14:03.500 --> 01:14:06.080
[Guest]: So you're not really immediately worried about Japan.

01:14:06.080 --> 01:14:10.040
[Guest]: But all this sort of starts to change as the Cold War begins to wind down, as the 70s and

01:14:10.040 --> 01:14:13.920
[Guest]: the 80s come into play and China's relationship with the US changes.

01:14:13.920 --> 01:14:18.400
[Guest]: But this relationship with India still continues to remain very, very difficult because of

01:14:18.400 --> 01:14:23.560
[Guest]: this long persisting boundary dispute and the sense of each other's anxiety.

01:14:23.560 --> 01:14:27.160
[Guest]: And the sort of suspicion with each other's broader motives.

01:14:27.160 --> 01:14:31.880
[Guest]: China sees India as somebody who does not want to see any extra regional power playing

01:14:31.880 --> 01:14:35.320
[Guest]: any role in South Asia, particularly the Chinese.

01:14:35.320 --> 01:14:40.160
[Guest]: And India sees China as this block as China's relationship with Pakistan develops as a power

01:14:40.160 --> 01:14:45.480
[Guest]: that is not just threatening on its own border, but is also supporting a rival state, which

01:14:45.480 --> 01:14:47.720
[Guest]: is hell bent on bleeding India eventually.

01:14:47.720 --> 01:14:51.480
[Guest]: So I think that's where the fundamental battle lines get drawn going forward.

01:14:51.480 --> 01:14:56.520
[Amit Varma]: I want to therefore take that opportunity to move on to sort of the first flashpoint

01:14:56.520 --> 01:15:01.080
[Amit Varma]: between India and China, which was really Tibet in which, you know, both the countries

01:15:01.080 --> 01:15:02.560
[Amit Varma]: had a strategic interest.

01:15:02.560 --> 01:15:07.280
[Amit Varma]: So there's this famous 1956 talk by Mao Tse Tung, which is widely quoted in which I'll

01:15:07.280 --> 01:15:12.040
[Amit Varma]: also quote from where he's sort of giving while he's against Han chauvinism, Han, of

01:15:12.040 --> 01:15:16.520
[Amit Varma]: course, are the majority people of China, while he's against Han chauvinism, he's giving

01:15:16.520 --> 01:15:21.520
[Amit Varma]: a rationale here for what appears to be a kind of imperialism where he says, quote,

01:15:21.520 --> 01:15:25.680
[Amit Varma]: the national minority areas are extensive and rich in resources.

01:15:25.680 --> 01:15:30.440
[Amit Varma]: While the Han nationality has a large population, the national minority areas have riches under

01:15:30.440 --> 01:15:33.360
[Amit Varma]: the soil that are needed for building socialism.

01:15:33.360 --> 01:15:38.320
[Amit Varma]: The Han nationality must actively assist the national minorities to carry out socialist

01:15:38.320 --> 01:15:43.480
[Amit Varma]: economic, socialist economic and cultural construction and by improving relations between

01:15:43.480 --> 01:15:48.600
[Amit Varma]: the nationalities, mobilize all elements, both human and material, which are beneficial

01:15:48.600 --> 01:15:50.440
[Amit Varma]: to socialist construction.

01:15:50.440 --> 01:15:56.720
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote where basically he's using, you know, socialism as a rationale for what basically

01:15:56.720 --> 01:16:01.760
[Amit Varma]: seems to be imperialism, sort of like you, you spoke about the Middle Kingdom with concentric

01:16:01.760 --> 01:16:03.760
[Amit Varma]: circles going outwards.

01:16:03.760 --> 01:16:07.200
[Amit Varma]: And this probably seems to be the first of the circles.

01:16:07.200 --> 01:16:11.760
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, India has a bit of an interest in Tibet as well, because they see

01:16:11.760 --> 01:16:15.040
[Amit Varma]: it as part of their sphere of cultural influence.

01:16:15.040 --> 01:16:19.440
[Amit Varma]: You know, Buddhism was carried to Tibet to begin with by missionaries from India.

01:16:19.440 --> 01:16:23.320
[Amit Varma]: So this is not something that, you know, the Chinese invasion of Tibet doesn't really go

01:16:23.320 --> 01:16:24.680
[Amit Varma]: down well.

01:16:24.680 --> 01:16:28.400
[Amit Varma]: And this is an issue that festers for decades.

01:16:28.400 --> 01:16:33.240
[Amit Varma]: Can you tell me a little bit about the evolution of, you know, this whole issue?

01:16:33.240 --> 01:16:39.240
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, I think from a so from a Chinese perspective, some of the areas of ethnic minorities

01:16:39.240 --> 01:16:43.880
[Guest]: or the national minorities, as they call them, have to do with resources, have also got to

01:16:43.880 --> 01:16:45.640
[Guest]: do with frontier security.

01:16:45.640 --> 01:16:50.080
[Guest]: So for example, Xinjiang is one area where again, you've got resources of gas and energy,

01:16:50.080 --> 01:16:53.640
[Guest]: but you've also got frontier security as one problem with regard to terrorism and so on

01:16:53.640 --> 01:16:54.640
[Guest]: and so forth.

01:16:54.640 --> 01:16:58.880
[Guest]: But say in the specific context of Tibet, again, the Chinese state sort of saw Tibet

01:16:58.880 --> 01:17:01.820
[Guest]: as a part of Qing China.

01:17:01.820 --> 01:17:05.680
[Guest]: It was seen as a part of Qing China and there were periods of time where Tibet was sort

01:17:05.680 --> 01:17:09.760
[Guest]: of, you know, in some ways a tributary state and there were periods of time where it was

01:17:09.760 --> 01:17:13.160
[Guest]: far more dominant than what the Chinese dynasty was.

01:17:13.160 --> 01:17:18.360
[Guest]: So there was never really a part of, okay, this is the empire and Tibet is well integrated

01:17:18.360 --> 01:17:19.960
[Guest]: into the empire.

01:17:19.960 --> 01:17:25.000
[Guest]: So there were different times where there was an ebb and flow in the history of Tibet.

01:17:25.000 --> 01:17:28.840
[Guest]: But there were deep linkages with, say, the Chinese dynasties.

01:17:28.840 --> 01:17:33.720
[Guest]: And therefore you saw this as a part of broader China and as a part of the modern Chinese

01:17:33.720 --> 01:17:34.720
[Guest]: state.

01:17:34.720 --> 01:17:37.840
[Guest]: So they wanted to exercise direct control over this.

01:17:37.840 --> 01:17:42.360
[Guest]: They started doing this very early on, soon after taking power in 1949.

01:17:42.360 --> 01:17:46.120
[Guest]: In 1950, when this first sort of conversation begins and you start to create some sort of

01:17:46.120 --> 01:17:49.320
[Guest]: PLA presence in Tibet to try and annex it.

01:17:49.320 --> 01:17:53.480
[Guest]: Subsequently in 1959, you crush everything and you take full control of Tibet and you

01:17:53.480 --> 01:17:58.640
[Guest]: establish a communist party rule in full sort of capacity in Tibet.

01:17:58.640 --> 01:18:03.440
[Guest]: And then what that does essentially is that it creates sort of, there are two strands

01:18:03.440 --> 01:18:04.840
[Guest]: of conflict which are created.

01:18:04.840 --> 01:18:09.040
[Guest]: One is with India, where this traditional buffer, which was sort of an easer, which

01:18:09.040 --> 01:18:13.920
[Guest]: sort of eased the tension and eased the sort of standoff, face-off between the two massive

01:18:13.920 --> 01:18:16.320
[Guest]: states in the region goes away.

01:18:16.320 --> 01:18:18.160
[Guest]: And therefore they are now face to face.

01:18:18.160 --> 01:18:20.800
[Guest]: And that will inherently bring its own frictions.

01:18:20.800 --> 01:18:26.000
[Guest]: The second is that the fleeing of the Dalai Lama to India and India giving him refuge

01:18:26.000 --> 01:18:31.560
[Guest]: creates long term unsustainable problem between the two states, where the Dalai Lama essentially,

01:18:31.560 --> 01:18:35.240
[Guest]: eventually you set up this Tibetan government in exile in India.

01:18:35.240 --> 01:18:37.480
[Guest]: And that becomes a sore spot of friction.

01:18:37.480 --> 01:18:43.640
[Guest]: India post the 1962 war with China continues to support the Tibetan movement through covert

01:18:43.640 --> 01:18:48.160
[Guest]: means and there is enough documentary evidence to suggest that with the help of the US, we

01:18:48.160 --> 01:18:51.080
[Guest]: try to support Tibetan revolution in China.

01:18:51.080 --> 01:18:53.800
[Guest]: And the Chinese don't take that well.

01:18:53.800 --> 01:18:57.840
[Guest]: They are obviously also doing their own sort of nefarious activities in the east of India.

01:18:57.840 --> 01:19:00.600
[Guest]: But so is the Indian state doing certain things.

01:19:00.600 --> 01:19:04.800
[Guest]: And that's the problem continues till today because despite India having recognized that

01:19:04.800 --> 01:19:08.440
[Guest]: Tibet is part of China formally, we do recognize that.

01:19:08.440 --> 01:19:11.880
[Guest]: We did that under Jawaharlal Nehru himself.

01:19:11.880 --> 01:19:16.880
[Guest]: Yet that led to a conflict and the fleeing of the Dalai Lama was a crucial part of that

01:19:16.880 --> 01:19:22.640
[Guest]: conflict because it deepened this suspicion that India has designs over Tibet.

01:19:22.640 --> 01:19:25.480
[Guest]: Because it would then say that this is part of our cultural influence and while it can

01:19:25.480 --> 01:19:30.240
[Guest]: be independent, yet it becomes sort of a protectorate of India in one way or the other.

01:19:30.240 --> 01:19:33.880
[Guest]: And this suspicion sort of grows deeper.

01:19:33.880 --> 01:19:36.040
[Guest]: India signs these treaties with Bhutan.

01:19:36.040 --> 01:19:40.040
[Guest]: Eventually we annex Sikkim and Sikkim becomes a part of the Republic of India.

01:19:40.040 --> 01:19:45.160
[Guest]: India has a treaty with Nepal which sort of essentially creates Nepal as Bhutan and Nepal

01:19:45.160 --> 01:19:48.520
[Guest]: becomes sort of junior partners to India in many which ways.

01:19:48.520 --> 01:19:52.800
[Guest]: And that is a sort of sense that fuels Chinese anxiety that this is Indian imperialism which

01:19:52.800 --> 01:19:57.280
[Guest]: wants to enter and which wants to target Tibet, particularly because of its deep cultural

01:19:57.280 --> 01:20:01.320
[Guest]: linkages, the fact that they are now hosting the Dalai Lama is a bigger problem for the

01:20:01.320 --> 01:20:05.760
[Guest]: Chinese and therefore the Chinese see Tibet as historically a part of China and therefore

01:20:05.760 --> 01:20:06.760
[Guest]: it must be integrated.

01:20:06.760 --> 01:20:10.960
[Guest]: And historically while the linkages might have been weak, it was a part of China.

01:20:10.960 --> 01:20:15.520
[Guest]: That is a sort of historical narrative that the PRC holds firm to.

01:20:15.520 --> 01:20:20.000
[Guest]: The reality is that there were historical linkages but Tibet was never necessarily a

01:20:20.000 --> 01:20:21.840
[Guest]: part of the Chinese Empire.

01:20:21.840 --> 01:20:26.720
[Guest]: And I think that's the reason why this continues so far is again this sense that the PRC has

01:20:26.720 --> 01:20:29.600
[Guest]: struggled to maintain its control over Tibet.

01:20:29.600 --> 01:20:32.080
[Guest]: They have securitized the region heavily.

01:20:32.080 --> 01:20:33.680
[Guest]: They have tried to undermine religion.

01:20:33.680 --> 01:20:35.480
[Guest]: They have tried to undermine language.

01:20:35.480 --> 01:20:40.680
[Guest]: They have tried to undermine the sense of autonomy in many ways to try and promote integration.

01:20:40.680 --> 01:20:43.040
[Guest]: That periodically has led to backlashes.

01:20:43.040 --> 01:20:47.840
[Guest]: The 14th Dalai Lama has been extremely popular internationally in his ability to mobilize

01:20:47.840 --> 01:20:51.520
[Guest]: public opinion and the fact that he stays in India and there is a Tibetan government

01:20:51.520 --> 01:20:56.920
[Guest]: in exile in India continues to be a sore spot between the two countries because the Chinese

01:20:56.920 --> 01:21:00.720
[Guest]: then believe, then argue that well you are not respecting our core interests.

01:21:00.720 --> 01:21:05.000
[Guest]: And the Indian argument in return is that look he's a refugee who's living in India.

01:21:05.000 --> 01:21:06.400
[Guest]: He's a religious leader.

01:21:06.400 --> 01:21:09.240
[Guest]: It's a religious movement which we can't stop.

01:21:09.240 --> 01:21:11.120
[Guest]: We're a democracy.

01:21:11.120 --> 01:21:15.680
[Guest]: Politically we recognize that we abide by the one China principle.

01:21:15.680 --> 01:21:18.620
[Guest]: So we therefore acknowledge that Tibet is part of China also.

01:21:18.620 --> 01:21:21.680
[Guest]: So politically we're not really saying anything against that.

01:21:21.680 --> 01:21:23.200
[Guest]: But he's living here as an exile.

01:21:23.200 --> 01:21:26.720
[Guest]: It's part of our policy that he can live here and it's a religious movement.

01:21:26.720 --> 01:21:29.200
[Guest]: So we don't interfere in matters of religion.

01:21:29.200 --> 01:21:31.360
[Guest]: The Chinese obviously don't buy that argument.

01:21:31.360 --> 01:21:32.920
[Guest]: And therefore it continues to be a sore spot.

01:21:32.920 --> 01:21:38.160
[Guest]: And in fact it's going to probably be once again one of the most difficult issues between

01:21:38.160 --> 01:21:40.640
[Guest]: the two sides given the Dalai Lama's failing health.

01:21:40.640 --> 01:21:42.480
[Guest]: There's going to be issues about succession.

01:21:42.480 --> 01:21:47.880
[Guest]: There's going to be issues about religion, politics colliding with each other and whether

01:21:47.880 --> 01:21:52.840
[Guest]: you have a new Dalai Lama who is appointed as a successor by the current Dalai Lama,

01:21:52.840 --> 01:21:57.320
[Guest]: whether he's an Indian national, whether he's born in India, whether he's living in India,

01:21:57.320 --> 01:22:01.920
[Guest]: or whether it's a he or a she, and whether the Chinese would want to therefore have their

01:22:01.920 --> 01:22:06.280
[Guest]: own system of succession, which they've clearly told India that we will have our own system

01:22:06.280 --> 01:22:08.240
[Guest]: and you must respect that.

01:22:08.240 --> 01:22:12.160
[Guest]: So therefore it continues to be a massive issue between the two sides.

01:22:12.160 --> 01:22:15.920
[Amit Varma]: Maybe it can be like the World Boxing Championship where you have like five, six Dalai Lamas

01:22:15.920 --> 01:22:18.120
[Amit Varma]: and they can combine belts and all of that.

01:22:18.120 --> 01:22:20.280
[Amit Varma]: You know, as an aside, you mentioned the 14th Dalai Lama.

01:22:20.280 --> 01:22:22.680
[Amit Varma]: We're recording this on Monday, the 14th of October.

01:22:22.680 --> 01:22:25.760
[Amit Varma]: And there was a nice Twitter thread, which I noticed today morning.

01:22:25.760 --> 01:22:29.680
[Amit Varma]: I don't know if it's from today morning by Amitav Ghosh, where he gives this interesting

01:22:29.680 --> 01:22:36.080
[Amit Varma]: nugget on Nepal, where he talks about how in the 18th century, when the British Empire

01:22:36.080 --> 01:22:42.040
[Amit Varma]: was thinking, was invited by the Pancham Lama to take Nepal under their wing, you know,

01:22:42.040 --> 01:22:46.960
[Amit Varma]: they were voluntarily giving themselves up to the empire, the Britishers decided not

01:22:46.960 --> 01:22:52.040
[Amit Varma]: to do so because it would piss China off and they wanted to maintain their trade with China,

01:22:52.040 --> 01:22:55.120
[Amit Varma]: which was at that time mainly in opium and tea.

01:22:55.120 --> 01:22:58.880
[Amit Varma]: Tea of course came from China, though many Indians won't accept this, but that is just

01:22:58.880 --> 01:22:59.880
[Amit Varma]: how it is.

01:22:59.880 --> 01:23:01.520
[Amit Varma]: And that's interesting.

01:23:01.520 --> 01:23:06.120
[Amit Varma]: And you sort of mentioned, you know, and I want to segue from this into our other territorial

01:23:06.120 --> 01:23:11.800
[Amit Varma]: disputes and a good way to do that is, you know, you mentioned how Nehru accepted China's

01:23:11.800 --> 01:23:13.880
[Amit Varma]: jurisdiction over Tibet.

01:23:13.880 --> 01:23:19.560
[Amit Varma]: And the former Foreign Secretary JN Dixit wrote a book in 1999, where he wrote about

01:23:19.560 --> 01:23:25.160
[Amit Varma]: this, I'll quote from that quote, the first occasion when we could have negotiated a realistic

01:23:25.160 --> 01:23:30.560
[Amit Varma]: deal with China was when Nehru acquiesced with the Chinese resuming their sovereignty

01:23:30.560 --> 01:23:32.740
[Amit Varma]: and jurisdiction over Tibet.

01:23:32.740 --> 01:23:36.740
[Amit Varma]: We could have told the Chinese that in return for our accepting their resumption of authority

01:23:36.740 --> 01:23:42.480
[Amit Varma]: over Tibet, they should confirm the delineation of the Sino-Indian boundary as inherited by

01:23:42.480 --> 01:23:46.640
[Amit Varma]: them and us from the British period, we could have and should have demanded the quid pro

01:23:46.640 --> 01:23:51.480
[Amit Varma]: quo of their not questioning the delineated boundary of British times and asked them not

01:23:51.480 --> 01:23:55.720
[Amit Varma]: to revive any of their tenuous claims on what was Indian territory.

01:23:55.720 --> 01:23:58.480
[Amit Varma]: We did not utilize the opportunity, stop quote.

01:23:58.480 --> 01:24:03.880
[Amit Varma]: And this partly again plays to the point of perhaps Nehru not being hard nosed enough

01:24:03.880 --> 01:24:09.120
[Amit Varma]: had he had that sort of real politic and practical wisdom of say Patel, he he might have just

01:24:09.120 --> 01:24:10.500
[Amit Varma]: cut that hard deal.

01:24:10.500 --> 01:24:15.100
[Amit Varma]: But tell me a little bit about I mean, from what I understand, correct me if I'm wrong,

01:24:15.100 --> 01:24:18.960
[Amit Varma]: we have broadly two ongoing territorial disputes with China.

01:24:18.960 --> 01:24:23.280
[Amit Varma]: One of course is in the Northeast, Arunachal Pradesh and so on.

01:24:23.280 --> 01:24:26.640
[Amit Varma]: And the other is Aksai Chin.

01:24:26.640 --> 01:24:32.320
[Amit Varma]: And at one point, the proposal that they put on the table is that they don't fight over

01:24:32.320 --> 01:24:35.920
[Amit Varma]: the Northeast anymore and they accept the British boundaries by the McMahon line and

01:24:35.920 --> 01:24:38.880
[Amit Varma]: all that as long as we give them Aksai Chin.

01:24:38.880 --> 01:24:41.720
[Amit Varma]: And we apparently sort of did not agree to that.

01:24:41.720 --> 01:24:44.120
[Amit Varma]: And then that offer is no longer on the table.

01:24:44.120 --> 01:24:47.720
[Amit Varma]: Take me through the complicated history of the territorial disputes that we have with

01:24:47.720 --> 01:24:48.720
[Guest]: them.

01:24:48.720 --> 01:24:53.600
[Guest]: So yeah, like you rightly identified, there are so across our eastern boundaries, starting

01:24:53.600 --> 01:24:55.320
[Guest]: from the top in the Northeast.

01:24:55.320 --> 01:25:00.800
[Guest]: So we've got from say, from Aksai Chin, and not just Aksai Chin, which is a part of the

01:25:00.800 --> 01:25:04.800
[Guest]: former state of Jammu and Kashmir, which the Chinese control.

01:25:04.800 --> 01:25:09.920
[Guest]: But also there's a certain part which the Pakistanis ceded to China, the Saksham valley,

01:25:09.920 --> 01:25:12.760
[Guest]: which is with the Chinese.

01:25:12.760 --> 01:25:14.360
[Guest]: And that's being controlled by them.

01:25:14.360 --> 01:25:17.960
[Guest]: So that's the dispute around the northern part of India.

01:25:17.960 --> 01:25:23.080
[Guest]: Then we come to the middle sector around the boundary around Nepal and that area.

01:25:23.080 --> 01:25:27.760
[Guest]: Again, we have territorial disputes over there with the Chinese on certain plots of land.

01:25:27.760 --> 01:25:32.720
[Guest]: But those are sort of much better managed and less strategically significant in many

01:25:32.720 --> 01:25:33.720
[Guest]: ways.

01:25:33.720 --> 01:25:37.800
[Guest]: And then we come down to the Northeast where we've got Arunachal Pradesh and the Makhmau

01:25:37.800 --> 01:25:40.880
[Guest]: on line, which is the matter of dispute.

01:25:40.880 --> 01:25:46.560
[Guest]: Interestingly, early on, the Chinese didn't necessarily have a big issue with Arunachal

01:25:46.560 --> 01:25:47.560
[Guest]: Pradesh.

01:25:47.560 --> 01:25:50.240
[Guest]: They didn't really raise that as a major dispute.

01:25:50.240 --> 01:25:56.080
[Guest]: In fact, in the early negotiations, there was lots of back and forth about sharing maps,

01:25:56.080 --> 01:26:00.480
[Guest]: understanding each other's areas of dispute, understanding each other's claims.

01:26:00.480 --> 01:26:04.120
[Guest]: India in the 1950s published a map which outlined certain claims.

01:26:04.120 --> 01:26:07.800
[Guest]: The Chinese didn't take kindly to that map because they felt that it was excessive in

01:26:07.800 --> 01:26:10.200
[Guest]: terms of what they were claiming as Indian territory.

01:26:10.200 --> 01:26:16.080
[Guest]: And you need to think of maps in the context of, they're not just sort of empty pictures.

01:26:16.080 --> 01:26:18.560
[Guest]: They create imaginations of territory.

01:26:18.560 --> 01:26:20.800
[Guest]: They create imaginations among the public.

01:26:20.800 --> 01:26:24.960
[Guest]: And therefore, then to negotiate something away can become very, very complex.

01:26:24.960 --> 01:26:27.560
[Guest]: And the Chinese were sort of annoyed with that.

01:26:27.560 --> 01:26:31.800
[Guest]: But they never sought to provide clarity on their claims very often.

01:26:31.800 --> 01:26:34.800
[Guest]: This idea of what you spoke about a package proposal.

01:26:34.800 --> 01:26:39.240
[Guest]: So after the 1962 war, in the 1950s, there was some conversation about sharing maps,

01:26:39.240 --> 01:26:44.880
[Guest]: sharing details and about settling our boundary issues, which obviously didn't work out very

01:26:44.880 --> 01:26:45.880
[Guest]: well.

01:26:45.880 --> 01:26:49.840
[Guest]: Eventually, from 1962 onwards, this conversation stopped.

01:26:49.840 --> 01:26:54.760
[Guest]: And there was some stress at the border while each side didn't want to raise the pitch and

01:26:54.760 --> 01:26:59.960
[Guest]: one of the last sort of conflicts that happened, where a shot was fired was 1967.

01:26:59.960 --> 01:27:05.520
[Guest]: But since then, the border has been maintained peaceful because both sides had other interests.

01:27:05.520 --> 01:27:09.760
[Guest]: The Chinese look internally, we looked at other interests externally and internally

01:27:09.760 --> 01:27:12.760
[Guest]: post the late 60s and 70s.

01:27:12.760 --> 01:27:15.280
[Guest]: And therefore, the border has by and large remained calm.

01:27:15.280 --> 01:27:19.560
[Guest]: But in terms of settling this dispute, so the first real movement comes towards this

01:27:19.560 --> 01:27:21.720
[Guest]: package proposal that you're talking about.

01:27:21.720 --> 01:27:27.920
[Guest]: The first substantial conversation on this that comes out is in the 80s, when Deng Xiaoping

01:27:27.920 --> 01:27:31.640
[Guest]: actually offers this package proposal that you're talking about that, you know, in the

01:27:31.640 --> 01:27:35.480
[Guest]: Northeast, we sort of gave up what we are claiming, whereas you gave us a side chain

01:27:35.480 --> 01:27:38.000
[Guest]: and we just let things end.

01:27:38.000 --> 01:27:42.200
[Guest]: And in the middle sector, whatever little bit adjustments need to be made, we can make,

01:27:42.200 --> 01:27:43.360
[Guest]: but we can let this end.

01:27:43.360 --> 01:27:48.840
[Guest]: And this is to do a lot with Deng Xiaoping's approach of, you know, economic diplomacy.

01:27:48.840 --> 01:27:52.120
[Guest]: You want to sort of end political problems and you want to start looking at economic

01:27:52.120 --> 01:27:53.120
[Guest]: diplomacy.

01:27:53.120 --> 01:27:57.000
[Guest]: Once India sort of says no to this, and there's a reason why India says no to this, because

01:27:57.000 --> 01:28:01.040
[Guest]: India's approach to the boundary dispute has been more process driven.

01:28:01.040 --> 01:28:03.520
[Guest]: It's been more legalistic and process driven.

01:28:03.520 --> 01:28:09.560
[Guest]: And that's quite interesting because our ability to gather historical archival documents and

01:28:09.560 --> 01:28:15.520
[Guest]: to present them as matters of our claims is extremely poor compared to what the Chinese

01:28:15.520 --> 01:28:16.560
[Guest]: have done.

01:28:16.560 --> 01:28:22.040
[Guest]: The Chinese have over the years done far greater archival management, far better archival management.

01:28:22.040 --> 01:28:26.800
[Guest]: And therefore, often you will see Chinese diplomats and Chinese foreign ministry spokespeople

01:28:26.800 --> 01:28:32.860
[Guest]: and even politicians quoting from archives far more frequently, quoting documents, quoting

01:28:32.860 --> 01:28:38.000
[Guest]: accords far more frequently, and accords going back to far, far, many more centuries behind

01:28:38.000 --> 01:28:40.520
[Guest]: and data going back to many more centuries behind.

01:28:40.520 --> 01:28:45.880
[Guest]: In contrast, our ability to be able to do that is very, very limited because we don't

01:28:45.880 --> 01:28:49.760
[Guest]: necessarily have a sort of historical records divisions are very, very poorly managed.

01:28:49.760 --> 01:28:53.120
[Guest]: Also, we need to be declassifying some of our archives so that people can actually do

01:28:53.120 --> 01:28:54.120
[Guest]: better work on them.

01:28:54.120 --> 01:28:55.120
[Guest]: But that's another story.

01:28:55.120 --> 01:29:00.200
[Guest]: In terms of the boundary dispute, what starts to happen is that things essentially get ossified.

01:29:00.200 --> 01:29:06.080
[Guest]: In 87-88, we had another sort of confrontation in Sun Drang Chu, which is famous now because

01:29:06.080 --> 01:29:09.980
[Guest]: after that confrontation, Rajiv Gandhi visits Beijing.

01:29:09.980 --> 01:29:14.240
[Guest]: And that's when you start this new period of the Indo-China relationship, where both

01:29:14.240 --> 01:29:20.800
[Guest]: sides essentially say formally that our objective is to maintain the boundary peaceful, while

01:29:20.800 --> 01:29:26.040
[Guest]: we both focus on other things that we can work together on and also on internal development

01:29:26.040 --> 01:29:27.040
[Guest]: issues.

01:29:27.040 --> 01:29:30.600
[Guest]: And I think that's where this sort of dispute is even today ossified.

01:29:30.600 --> 01:29:34.840
[Guest]: Today, also the issue from our point of view predominantly is this, that we would like

01:29:34.840 --> 01:29:36.320
[Guest]: this to be resolved.

01:29:36.320 --> 01:29:41.640
[Guest]: But resolution would mean somebody's taking tremendous amount of political capital.

01:29:41.640 --> 01:29:45.400
[Guest]: In the 50s, even when Nehru was talking to the parliament, for the political capital

01:29:45.400 --> 01:29:50.080
[Guest]: that even he commanded, it seemed extremely difficult for Nehru to give away territory

01:29:50.080 --> 01:29:53.700
[Guest]: which had become part of this identity of India.

01:29:53.700 --> 01:29:58.080
[Guest]: And that's what happens once you start to very early issue maps, is that you create

01:29:58.080 --> 01:30:01.280
[Guest]: this idea and identity of this imagined community.

01:30:01.280 --> 01:30:05.120
[Guest]: And that becomes very, very difficult to then give away within the broader public when you

01:30:05.120 --> 01:30:07.440
[Guest]: create this identity.

01:30:07.440 --> 01:30:12.160
[Guest]: Yet if he couldn't do it back then, there wasn't really a concrete proposal on the table.

01:30:12.160 --> 01:30:14.560
[Guest]: There wasn't enough trust to do that back then.

01:30:14.560 --> 01:30:16.720
[Guest]: In the 80s, there was a proposal on the table.

01:30:16.720 --> 01:30:20.920
[Guest]: We didn't want to give it up because we were following very process driven, legalistic

01:30:20.920 --> 01:30:24.800
[Guest]: processes saying that no, but by this statement and by this logic, this is ours and that is

01:30:24.800 --> 01:30:25.800
[Guest]: ours.

01:30:25.800 --> 01:30:27.960
[Guest]: And the Chinese were saying, look, we're not interested in the details.

01:30:27.960 --> 01:30:29.120
[Guest]: The details can be worked out.

01:30:29.120 --> 01:30:32.120
[Guest]: Let's agree to a political settlement and we'll move forward.

01:30:32.120 --> 01:30:36.520
[Guest]: Yet we were very suspicious of that, partly because yes, Akshaya Chain has strategic value.

01:30:36.520 --> 01:30:39.720
[Guest]: But there are certain losses that you need to cut at certain points of time.

01:30:39.720 --> 01:30:41.840
[Guest]: And at that point in time, we decided we didn't want to cut those losses.

01:30:41.840 --> 01:30:47.440
[Guest]: Today, we're in a position where the Chinese, to my mind, have very little incentive to

01:30:47.440 --> 01:30:48.440
[Guest]: settle this.

01:30:48.440 --> 01:30:51.920
[Guest]: They enjoy a massive power asymmetry within India.

01:30:51.920 --> 01:30:53.480
[Guest]: The economy is five times larger.

01:30:53.480 --> 01:30:56.480
[Guest]: They're rapidly modernizing their armed forces.

01:30:56.480 --> 01:31:00.880
[Guest]: They're far larger, far stronger, far more equipped armed force than ours.

01:31:00.880 --> 01:31:03.760
[Guest]: And I think that poses challenges to us.

01:31:03.760 --> 01:31:06.960
[Guest]: And therefore, there is very little incentive for them to settle because they can continue

01:31:06.960 --> 01:31:11.720
[Guest]: to keep using the border, maintain it peacefully, but, you know, raise tensions as and when

01:31:11.720 --> 01:31:18.080
[Guest]: needed in order to ensure that political messages sent to India that India needs to stay in

01:31:18.080 --> 01:31:21.920
[Guest]: line and realize that the Chinese are the bigger power.

01:31:21.920 --> 01:31:26.960
[Guest]: And why would you, when you enjoy such an asymmetry, want to settle by giving up some

01:31:26.960 --> 01:31:28.520
[Guest]: territory when you no longer need to?

01:31:28.520 --> 01:31:32.000
[Amit Varma]: No, and one of the points you made is extremely fascinating because and, you know, I start

01:31:32.000 --> 01:31:38.840
[Amit Varma]: to wonder about how we can actually be imprisoned conceptually by the maps that we make.

01:31:38.840 --> 01:31:44.200
[Amit Varma]: That once we have made maps which show, you know, Kashmir to be a certain way and Aksai

01:31:44.200 --> 01:31:48.320
[Amit Varma]: Chin to be part of India, then it becomes very difficult and we get hardened into those

01:31:48.320 --> 01:31:49.320
[Amit Varma]: positions.

01:31:49.320 --> 01:31:53.120
[Amit Varma]: Is it true that Aksai Chin also like POK is not actually under our control?

01:31:53.120 --> 01:31:54.840
[Guest]: It's basically under Chinese control, right?

01:31:54.840 --> 01:31:55.840
[Guest]: It's under Chinese control.

01:31:55.840 --> 01:31:56.840
[Guest]: It's not in our control.

01:31:56.840 --> 01:32:01.280
[Guest]: There are two chunks of the former state of Jammu and Kashmir, which are no longer in

01:32:01.280 --> 01:32:02.280
[Guest]: our control.

01:32:02.280 --> 01:32:09.440
[Guest]: And in some ways, I mean, this current abrogation of Article 370, whatever else one can talk

01:32:09.440 --> 01:32:12.960
[Guest]: about it, at least from a Chinese point of view, whatever the reaction has been and it's

01:32:12.960 --> 01:32:17.200
[Guest]: been played up in the media about being, you know, aggressive and pro-Pakistan and all

01:32:17.200 --> 01:32:20.240
[Guest]: of that, which is true, it is pro-Pakistan in some ways.

01:32:20.240 --> 01:32:22.960
[Guest]: But the Chinese also see a possibility there, right?

01:32:22.960 --> 01:32:29.200
[Guest]: You're redrawing maps, you're redrawing imaginations, you're segregating what is the Kashmir issue

01:32:29.200 --> 01:32:32.880
[Guest]: with Pakistan, with what is the Kashmir issue with China.

01:32:32.880 --> 01:32:37.040
[Guest]: You're creating new identities, which can then go and negotiate some of the solutions.

01:32:37.040 --> 01:32:40.320
[Guest]: So it opens up certain new possibilities, whether those possibilities will lead to a

01:32:40.320 --> 01:32:41.960
[Guest]: resolution of the different ballgame.

01:32:41.960 --> 01:32:45.040
[Guest]: But it opens up new possibilities because you're redrawing imagination.

01:32:45.040 --> 01:32:49.640
[Amit Varma]: And what another thing you said, which also struck me was about how now China being in

01:32:49.640 --> 01:32:53.240
[Amit Varma]: this massive position of power has no incentive to settle.

01:32:53.240 --> 01:32:54.240
[Amit Varma]: So is it?

01:32:54.240 --> 01:32:57.560
[Amit Varma]: I mean, obviously, one of the mature things that both nations have done is that they've

01:32:57.560 --> 01:33:02.560
[Amit Varma]: done that boundary conflict management where, you know, battles at the border won't get

01:33:02.560 --> 01:33:04.760
[Amit Varma]: out of hand, which is great.

01:33:04.760 --> 01:33:10.520
[Amit Varma]: But also that it is in China's interest to sort of hold what is happening in the Northeast

01:33:10.520 --> 01:33:16.160
[Amit Varma]: as, you know, a strategic wedge they can use or maybe do the same in with Kashmir, for

01:33:16.160 --> 01:33:19.320
[Amit Varma]: example, where it is not in their interest to resolve the issue.

01:33:19.320 --> 01:33:22.480
[Guest]: Yeah, in the near term, it's just not in the interest to resolve the issue.

01:33:22.480 --> 01:33:28.080
[Guest]: I mean, you've got an India which the Chinese fear would drift into an American orbit, although

01:33:28.080 --> 01:33:31.840
[Guest]: that would have its own cost for India and its own sense of perception of itself as a

01:33:31.840 --> 01:33:32.840
[Guest]: major power.

01:33:32.840 --> 01:33:37.000
[Guest]: But the Chinese fear is that in India that can drift into an American orbit, but also

01:33:37.000 --> 01:33:42.840
[Guest]: India that can become vibrant, that can grow rapidly and therefore provide a value based

01:33:42.840 --> 01:33:45.600
[Guest]: challenge to the Chinese model, right?

01:33:45.600 --> 01:33:49.840
[Guest]: The Chinese model is that a single party unified rule works.

01:33:49.840 --> 01:33:52.040
[Guest]: It's provided economic growth.

01:33:52.040 --> 01:33:55.720
[Guest]: And for that, you need to make certain political compromises in terms of political liberties

01:33:55.720 --> 01:33:57.600
[Guest]: and so on and so forth, social liberties.

01:33:57.600 --> 01:34:02.000
[Guest]: A vibrant, democratic, thriving India with sort of the similar amount of people in it,

01:34:02.000 --> 01:34:07.160
[Guest]: you know, 1.3, 1.4 billion people, thriving, growing, economically also prospering while

01:34:07.160 --> 01:34:12.720
[Guest]: having this democracy, which has its own frictions and everything within it, being a desirable

01:34:12.720 --> 01:34:18.560
[Guest]: alternative right next door poses a value based challenge to the Chinese state also,

01:34:18.560 --> 01:34:20.400
[Guest]: an ideological challenge to the Chinese state.

01:34:20.400 --> 01:34:26.400
[Guest]: So it's useful to keep in India, which has got border disputes, which is slightly conflicted,

01:34:26.400 --> 01:34:31.760
[Guest]: which has to therefore keep a watch on certain security imperatives, not just on one side

01:34:31.760 --> 01:34:34.040
[Guest]: of its border, but on both sides of its land border.

01:34:34.040 --> 01:34:38.440
[Guest]: Whereas you'd want that sort of friction to remain so that you can constantly send India

01:34:38.440 --> 01:34:44.160
[Guest]: a message saying, look, if you're going to try and drift in somebody's orbit, which is

01:34:44.160 --> 01:34:48.320
[Guest]: our competitor, there are other things that you need to worry about directly.

01:34:48.320 --> 01:34:52.320
[Guest]: And you need to then think whether that partner of yours will come and stand by you.

01:34:52.320 --> 01:34:56.560
[Guest]: The other thing is that when you keep this land boundary dispute alive with India, you

01:34:56.560 --> 01:35:02.800
[Guest]: make sure that India invests its limited resources in defense on ensuring protection of the land

01:35:02.800 --> 01:35:05.000
[Guest]: boundary, because that's what your primary threat is.

01:35:05.000 --> 01:35:07.480
[Guest]: That leaves the oceans open.

01:35:07.480 --> 01:35:12.880
[Guest]: And again, that leaves limited investment, limited focus on the maritime domain.

01:35:12.880 --> 01:35:15.760
[Guest]: And that's where the Chinese today want their focus to be.

01:35:15.760 --> 01:35:18.560
[Guest]: Their naval development is among the biggest in the world.

01:35:18.560 --> 01:35:20.640
[Guest]: They're pumping money by the billions.

01:35:20.640 --> 01:35:25.680
[Guest]: They're building new vessels, carriers, and all of those start to operate around the world.

01:35:25.680 --> 01:35:30.800
[Guest]: And initially in the near regions, in the near seas and the Pacific Ocean, but increasingly

01:35:30.800 --> 01:35:36.780
[Guest]: in the Indian Ocean, which is where a lot of Chinese trade and energy comes from.

01:35:36.780 --> 01:35:42.360
[Guest]: So there would you want an India which is stronger, which is focused on naval development,

01:35:42.360 --> 01:35:46.280
[Guest]: which is focused on naval partnerships, or you want an India which is slightly unbalanced

01:35:46.280 --> 01:35:50.640
[Guest]: because it's worried also about its boundaries, land boundaries, and therefore investing there.

01:35:50.640 --> 01:35:54.400
[Guest]: And I think those are sort of reasons why there is no incentive to actually settle this

01:35:54.400 --> 01:35:55.400
[Guest]: dispute.

01:35:55.400 --> 01:35:59.120
[Guest]: So your objective is to keep it calm, to keep the border calm, but still keep it sufficiently

01:35:59.120 --> 01:36:03.640
[Guest]: hot but not live so that India is focused over there.

01:36:03.640 --> 01:36:09.040
[Guest]: And when time comes, when push comes to shove, you can talk about trying to move forward

01:36:09.040 --> 01:36:10.040
[Guest]: towards resolving it.

01:36:10.040 --> 01:36:15.320
[Guest]: You can also talk about trying to take certain steps forward to keep it calm and tranquil

01:36:15.320 --> 01:36:16.640
[Guest]: while you keep India engaged.

01:36:16.640 --> 01:36:21.040
[Guest]: So it keeps pumping its resources on the land boundary as opposed to looking at the maritime

01:36:21.040 --> 01:36:22.040
[Guest]: domain.

01:36:22.040 --> 01:36:25.400
[Guest]: And you keep sending India a message every time you feel that it's drifting too much

01:36:25.400 --> 01:36:30.160
[Guest]: away from challenging your interests, whether with regard to the US or whether in the Indian

01:36:30.160 --> 01:36:36.560
[Guest]: Ocean region or whether in broader South Asia, by sort of creating a mini crisis, which you

01:36:36.560 --> 01:36:40.560
[Guest]: know that is in your interest and in India's interest to manage, because also you know,

01:36:40.560 --> 01:36:45.400
[Guest]: the Chinese know, Beijing knows that conflict with India is also not in its interest.

01:36:45.400 --> 01:36:47.000
[Guest]: India is not a small country.

01:36:47.000 --> 01:36:49.360
[Guest]: India is a powerful country with substantial capacity.

01:36:49.360 --> 01:36:52.360
[Guest]: And push comes to shove, Beijing will have to suffer substantial damage.

01:36:52.360 --> 01:36:54.720
[Guest]: And you don't want to suffer that damage.

01:36:54.720 --> 01:36:56.560
[Amit Varma]: So that's the objective.

01:36:56.560 --> 01:37:00.560
[Amit Varma]: Since you mentioned broader South Asia, let's kind of talk about the neighborhood now.

01:37:00.560 --> 01:37:06.280
[Amit Varma]: I'll quote another bit from an analyst called Colonel Gurmeet Kanwal, writing in 99 and

01:37:06.280 --> 01:37:09.240
[Amit Varma]: again, this was quoted in Gawar's book, which is where I've picked the quote from where

01:37:09.240 --> 01:37:13.520
[Amit Varma]: he talks about the Chinese policy of strategic encirclement.

01:37:13.520 --> 01:37:18.000
[Amit Varma]: And he writes, quote, while China professes a policy of peace and friendliness towards

01:37:18.000 --> 01:37:23.800
[Amit Varma]: India, its deeds clearly indicate that concentrated efforts are underway aimed at strategic encirclement

01:37:23.800 --> 01:37:24.920
[Amit Varma]: of India.

01:37:24.920 --> 01:37:29.600
[Amit Varma]: For the last several decades, China has been engaged in efforts to create a string of anti

01:37:29.600 --> 01:37:35.120
[Amit Varma]: Indian influence around India through military and economic assistance programs to neighborly

01:37:35.120 --> 01:37:37.880
[Amit Varma]: countries combined with complementary diplomacy.

01:37:37.880 --> 01:37:43.080
[Amit Varma]: Pakistan, Bangladesh, Nepal and Sri Lanka have been assiduously and cleverly cultivated

01:37:43.080 --> 01:37:45.080
[Amit Varma]: towards the same stop code.

01:37:45.080 --> 01:37:48.120
[Amit Varma]: And what's happening is India is kind of aware of this.

01:37:48.120 --> 01:37:50.480
[Amit Varma]: And in a diplomatic way, India fights back.

01:37:50.480 --> 01:37:56.760
[Amit Varma]: Maldives was a recent sort of, you know, battleground, so to say of diplomatic efforts to this end

01:37:56.760 --> 01:38:01.400
[Amit Varma]: where you know, both the parties concerned want a government that is friendly to them.

01:38:01.400 --> 01:38:07.240
[Amit Varma]: How has this been playing out over the years, because, you know, Gawar also says elsewhere

01:38:07.240 --> 01:38:11.160
[Amit Varma]: in his book, where he talks about the attitude of these other countries, quote, the most

01:38:11.160 --> 01:38:16.000
[Amit Varma]: common response represented by Pakistan, Iran, Bangladesh, Myanmar and Sri Lanka is to see

01:38:16.000 --> 01:38:21.800
[Amit Varma]: China as an again, a quote within a quote, a benign state whose power and independent

01:38:21.800 --> 01:38:26.800
[Amit Varma]: role enhances their security by balancing other major states such as India or the United

01:38:26.800 --> 01:38:29.760
[Amit Varma]: States or Russia that are the pivotal concern.

01:38:29.760 --> 01:38:34.240
[Amit Varma]: Stop code so in one sense, a lot of these countries also welcome Chinese influence because

01:38:34.240 --> 01:38:36.680
[Amit Varma]: of you, India as a neighborhood bully.

01:38:36.680 --> 01:38:41.120
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about how the dynamics of this has been playing out over the decades.

01:38:41.120 --> 01:38:46.400
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, I think Gurmit Kawal's point in that book is well made.

01:38:46.400 --> 01:38:51.320
[Guest]: And look, I think this has a lot to do with which perspective you want to look at it from.

01:38:51.320 --> 01:38:57.520
[Guest]: If you're a strategist sitting in New Delhi, and you're seeing China investing in ports,

01:38:57.520 --> 01:39:03.600
[Guest]: roads, infrastructure projects, finance, you know, across South Asia, in sort of military

01:39:03.600 --> 01:39:07.600
[Guest]: to military diplomacy in countries in your neighborhood, you're bound to get concerned

01:39:07.600 --> 01:39:11.760
[Guest]: and you're bound to see it from your prism saying that this is a string of influence

01:39:11.760 --> 01:39:15.520
[Guest]: or more recently, as this conversation has been a string of pearls, which is being put

01:39:15.520 --> 01:39:17.480
[Guest]: together to contain India.

01:39:17.480 --> 01:39:21.440
[Guest]: So I can see that very logically from a Delhi strategist point of view.

01:39:21.440 --> 01:39:26.760
[Guest]: But if you look at it from a Chinese point of view, this is a region which is underdeveloped,

01:39:26.760 --> 01:39:30.160
[Guest]: unconnected with potential for growth with massive population.

01:39:30.160 --> 01:39:33.120
[Guest]: Bangladesh is a very largely populated country.

01:39:33.120 --> 01:39:35.680
[Guest]: Pakistan is a largely highly heavily populated country.

01:39:35.680 --> 01:39:41.000
[Guest]: There are other countries which have significant strategically Sri Lanka, Myanmar, and you

01:39:41.000 --> 01:39:42.600
[Guest]: and Maldives increasingly.

01:39:42.600 --> 01:39:46.920
[Guest]: And you can see opportunities to build your support systems over there because so much

01:39:46.920 --> 01:39:49.680
[Guest]: of your trade and energy is reliant on the Indian Ocean.

01:39:49.680 --> 01:39:54.400
[Guest]: So the Chinese are looking at this also from the point of view of markets and opportunity,

01:39:54.400 --> 01:39:59.160
[Guest]: and also some degree of strategic security because they feel threatened that their sealings

01:39:59.160 --> 01:40:03.800
[Guest]: of communications can be disrupted in the Indian Ocean.

01:40:03.800 --> 01:40:08.480
[Guest]: And particularly if you were to see India as a dominant power in the Indian Ocean region,

01:40:08.480 --> 01:40:13.760
[Guest]: and that India wants to keep away extra regional powers, and there's a history of India wanting

01:40:13.760 --> 01:40:14.760
[Guest]: to do that.

01:40:14.760 --> 01:40:21.080
[Guest]: Our efforts in the Maldives in the late 80s, our attempt at sending the IPKF in Sri Lanka,

01:40:21.080 --> 01:40:26.440
[Guest]: our recent sort of engagements in Sri Lanka and in the Maldives again, our engagement

01:40:26.440 --> 01:40:27.920
[Guest]: with Bangladesh more recently.

01:40:27.920 --> 01:40:33.280
[Guest]: There is an attempt at trying to build India, trying to ensure that India remains a dominant

01:40:33.280 --> 01:40:34.520
[Guest]: power in the region.

01:40:34.520 --> 01:40:39.360
[Guest]: Although increasingly, the rise of Chinese capacity and the rise of Chinese overall national

01:40:39.360 --> 01:40:43.000
[Guest]: power driven by economic growth has begun to challenge that.

01:40:43.000 --> 01:40:46.680
[Guest]: So from a Chinese perspective, if you look at India, which is viewed as fundamentally

01:40:46.680 --> 01:40:53.800
[Guest]: hostile or potentially hostile as the largest power in this region, which is getting increasingly

01:40:53.800 --> 01:40:58.760
[Guest]: closely aligned to the United States, which is a geopolitical rival, and which now is

01:40:58.760 --> 01:41:05.520
[Guest]: partnering in, although differently interpreted, but the Indo-Pacific as an idea, which the

01:41:05.520 --> 01:41:09.520
[Guest]: Chinese see as increasingly step moving towards containment of China.

01:41:09.520 --> 01:41:13.560
[Guest]: You can see why they want to sort of, why this is a scope for greater hostility between

01:41:13.560 --> 01:41:16.920
[Guest]: the two sides, because your interests are sort of rubbing against each other far more

01:41:16.920 --> 01:41:22.200
[Guest]: vigorously and you're worried about this becoming a bigger issue.

01:41:22.200 --> 01:41:26.720
[Guest]: But the third perspective of this is from the point of view of these individual states.

01:41:26.720 --> 01:41:30.440
[Guest]: I'm going to leave Pakistan out of it because Pakistan has very different objectives.

01:41:30.440 --> 01:41:36.080
[Guest]: But if you look at Sri Lanka, the Maldives, Bangladesh, Myanmar, these are states where

01:41:36.080 --> 01:41:38.360
[Guest]: there is a deep development deficit.

01:41:38.360 --> 01:41:41.880
[Guest]: These are states which have had complex domestic history.

01:41:41.880 --> 01:41:46.440
[Guest]: Sri Lanka has gone through a domestic, has gone through a civil war.

01:41:46.440 --> 01:41:49.040
[Guest]: Bangladesh has deep issues in party and infrastructure deficit.

01:41:49.040 --> 01:41:53.120
[Guest]: The Myanmar's have been dealing with the civil war and national isolation for a very long

01:41:53.120 --> 01:41:58.800
[Guest]: period of time to then becoming a democratic country after serious, after prolonged dictatorial

01:41:58.800 --> 01:42:00.640
[Guest]: sort of army junta rule.

01:42:00.640 --> 01:42:04.160
[Guest]: These are countries that are looking at opportunities for development.

01:42:04.160 --> 01:42:09.160
[Guest]: And the Chinese are increasingly saying that, yes, we want to invest.

01:42:09.160 --> 01:42:10.160
[Guest]: We have the money.

01:42:10.160 --> 01:42:11.160
[Guest]: We have the political will.

01:42:11.160 --> 01:42:12.160
[Guest]: But we want to invest.

01:42:12.160 --> 01:42:14.280
[Guest]: We want to pursue development projects.

01:42:14.280 --> 01:42:18.880
[Guest]: For these countries, this is an opportunity not just to balance against India as the quote

01:42:18.880 --> 01:42:23.880
[Guest]: that you said pointed out, you know, you see it as an opportunity to balance Indian influence,

01:42:23.880 --> 01:42:28.400
[Guest]: but you also see it as an opportunity to ensure that you develop.

01:42:28.400 --> 01:42:32.760
[Guest]: So you're hedging with India, but you're also accepting certain influence to develop.

01:42:32.760 --> 01:42:35.960
[Guest]: But that does not mean that you necessarily give away your agency.

01:42:35.960 --> 01:42:40.360
[Guest]: You still as a small state command significant agency to be able to maneuver between larger

01:42:40.360 --> 01:42:42.920
[Guest]: states to achieve your foreign policy objectives.

01:42:42.920 --> 01:42:48.400
[Guest]: And increasingly, if you see how the Chinese, at least publicly and how India also publicly

01:42:48.400 --> 01:42:52.200
[Guest]: is now talking about some of these countries, there's a far more.

01:42:52.200 --> 01:42:56.200
[Guest]: So today you see India talking about things like non-reciprocal foreign policy gestures

01:42:56.200 --> 01:43:00.720
[Guest]: in the region where you're being the bigger actor, which is not really demanding things.

01:43:00.720 --> 01:43:04.920
[Guest]: Although, yes, you are demanding certain security interests be kept in mind.

01:43:04.920 --> 01:43:07.800
[Guest]: The second thing is that you're looking at promoting democracy.

01:43:07.800 --> 01:43:12.520
[Guest]: You're looking at talking about sovereignty of states being respected.

01:43:12.520 --> 01:43:16.200
[Guest]: The Chinese have played this game for a very long time where they keep talking about the

01:43:16.200 --> 01:43:20.120
[Guest]: importance of sovereignty, whether you're large or small, and particularly in the context

01:43:20.120 --> 01:43:23.000
[Guest]: of India and India's role in the region, they keep emphasizing with some of these other

01:43:23.000 --> 01:43:27.040
[Guest]: countries that, you know, we respect your sovereignty as opposed to, you know, this

01:43:27.040 --> 01:43:28.040
[Guest]: bully India.

01:43:28.040 --> 01:43:30.760
[Guest]: But India is sort of beginning to adapt to that thing.

01:43:30.760 --> 01:43:35.360
[Guest]: So I think there are these three perspectives from which you need to look at Chinese investments

01:43:35.360 --> 01:43:37.680
[Guest]: and the rise of China in the region.

01:43:37.680 --> 01:43:41.400
[Guest]: India's policy under this current government with regard to Nepal a couple of years ago

01:43:41.400 --> 01:43:46.720
[Guest]: when we imposed that blockade, opened the scope for China to expand its reach in the

01:43:46.720 --> 01:43:47.720
[Guest]: country, right?

01:43:47.720 --> 01:43:49.640
[Guest]: Just this week, we've had Xi Jinping visit Nepal.

01:43:49.640 --> 01:43:53.600
[Guest]: He's the first Chinese president to visit the country in 23 years.

01:43:53.600 --> 01:43:55.800
[Guest]: Nepal is an ally of India in many ways.

01:43:55.800 --> 01:43:58.320
[Guest]: It's got such a deep relationship with India.

01:43:58.320 --> 01:44:01.680
[Guest]: Its trade with India is about six to seven billion dollars.

01:44:01.680 --> 01:44:03.720
[Guest]: Its trade with China is about a billion dollars.

01:44:03.720 --> 01:44:05.720
[Guest]: But that's picked up in the last few years.

01:44:05.720 --> 01:44:08.400
[Guest]: And yet China has been able to make increase in roads.

01:44:08.400 --> 01:44:12.240
[Guest]: Part of that is because Nepal is looking for newer opportunities and newer financing.

01:44:12.240 --> 01:44:18.200
[Guest]: But part of that is also because increasingly our influence has been seen as problematic

01:44:18.200 --> 01:44:19.200
[Guest]: by Nepal.

01:44:19.200 --> 01:44:24.920
[Guest]: And that's punctuated by the last blockade that we imposed, which created more complications.

01:44:24.920 --> 01:44:27.520
[Guest]: So there are ways in which these states will also act.

01:44:27.520 --> 01:44:31.720
[Guest]: So my sort of broad takeaway to anybody looking at this particular issue is that, yes, from

01:44:31.720 --> 01:44:35.440
[Guest]: a Delhi strategic point of view and from an Indian interest point of view, some of these

01:44:35.440 --> 01:44:38.440
[Guest]: Chinese investments are a matter of concern.

01:44:38.440 --> 01:44:42.960
[Guest]: And yes, I can see why one would think of a string of influence being stretched together.

01:44:42.960 --> 01:44:48.520
[Guest]: From a Chinese point of view, there are many more imperatives than just encircling India

01:44:48.520 --> 01:44:50.520
[Guest]: that are going into this approach.

01:44:50.520 --> 01:44:54.720
[Guest]: And thirdly, from the point of view of these states, which have their own individual agency,

01:44:54.720 --> 01:44:59.160
[Guest]: which often gets lost in the conversation about two great powers challenging each other

01:44:59.160 --> 01:45:02.560
[Guest]: in the region, is that these states have their own agency.

01:45:02.560 --> 01:45:07.320
[Guest]: And it's not really easy to push around and influence and manipulate them into action,

01:45:07.320 --> 01:45:11.560
[Guest]: because they might be small states in some ways, but they command large populations.

01:45:11.560 --> 01:45:16.440
[Guest]: Bangladesh, particularly, is an increasingly growing, fast growing economy, and they have

01:45:16.440 --> 01:45:17.900
[Guest]: strategic significance.

01:45:17.900 --> 01:45:22.760
[Guest]: So while you still see contests being played out, their own agency is not insignificant.

01:45:22.760 --> 01:45:27.760
[Amit Varma]: So moving on from the elephant in the elevator, let's talk about the elephant in the room,

01:45:27.760 --> 01:45:30.640
[Amit Varma]: which is, you know, which we haven't met, the neighbor we haven't mentioned so far,

01:45:30.640 --> 01:45:31.640
[Amit Varma]: which is Pakistan.

01:45:31.640 --> 01:45:36.560
[Amit Varma]: You know, China's become friendlier with Pakistan in the past, they've invested more there,

01:45:36.560 --> 01:45:41.480
[Amit Varma]: they have more leverage there to influence matters, their incentives have changed, Pakistan's

01:45:41.480 --> 01:45:43.120
[Amit Varma]: incentives have changed.

01:45:43.120 --> 01:45:46.880
[Amit Varma]: How is all this sort of affecting the neighborhood?

01:45:46.880 --> 01:45:48.080
[Amit Varma]: And is it good for us?

01:45:48.080 --> 01:45:49.080
[Amit Varma]: Is it bad for us?

01:45:49.080 --> 01:45:52.280
[Guest]: I guess it's in terms of it being good for us or bad for us.

01:45:52.280 --> 01:45:53.840
[Guest]: I mean, that time will tell.

01:45:53.840 --> 01:45:57.920
[Guest]: But I think there are certain changes that are happening, which we need to keep in mind.

01:45:57.920 --> 01:46:03.720
[Guest]: So China's relationship with Pakistan, starting from the late 50s and the 60s, when they start

01:46:03.720 --> 01:46:08.320
[Guest]: to cozy up with each other much more, until they eventually develop this bond, which is

01:46:08.320 --> 01:46:13.000
[Guest]: higher than the highest mountains and sweeter than honey and deeper than the deepest seas,

01:46:13.000 --> 01:46:17.760
[Guest]: until they develop this iron brother bond, predominantly militarily driven, it's predominantly

01:46:17.760 --> 01:46:22.000
[Guest]: driven by a common sense of threat perception with regard to India.

01:46:22.000 --> 01:46:29.160
[Guest]: And from a Chinese point of view, Pakistan is a useful partner in keeping India unbalanced.

01:46:29.160 --> 01:46:32.120
[Guest]: Increasingly the security element sort of develops.

01:46:32.120 --> 01:46:36.640
[Guest]: So from 60s, 70s, 80s, you see predominantly this being a security partnership.

01:46:36.640 --> 01:46:41.680
[Guest]: China assists Pakistan in its missile development program and its nuclear program.

01:46:41.680 --> 01:46:47.720
[Guest]: Today that's expanded to actually even assisting Pakistan in joint development of fighter jets,

01:46:47.720 --> 01:46:53.840
[Guest]: submarine programs, to increasingly even supporting its new sort of security propositions in terms

01:46:53.840 --> 01:46:59.560
[Guest]: of city security, citywide sort of policing grid and those sorts of things.

01:46:59.560 --> 01:47:05.460
[Guest]: So the security engagement has deepened over the years, and that primarily led the partnership.

01:47:05.460 --> 01:47:11.760
[Guest]: But starting sort of from the 2000s onwards to CPEC being launched in 2013, 2014, you

01:47:11.760 --> 01:47:16.400
[Guest]: start to see this economic engagement becoming far more important.

01:47:16.400 --> 01:47:19.560
[Guest]: The military to military partnership still dominates this relationship, but increasingly

01:47:19.560 --> 01:47:21.960
[Guest]: the economic engagement has become important.

01:47:21.960 --> 01:47:23.440
[Guest]: That has to do with a couple of reasons.

01:47:23.440 --> 01:47:29.360
[Guest]: The Chinese see a desire in necessarily expanding their stake in Pakistan directly because there

01:47:29.360 --> 01:47:31.120
[Guest]: are strategic interests involved.

01:47:31.120 --> 01:47:36.360
[Guest]: Gwadar, we've often spoken about Gwadar as a potential Chinese base or Jivani in Pakistan

01:47:36.360 --> 01:47:38.120
[Guest]: as a potential Chinese base.

01:47:38.120 --> 01:47:42.160
[Guest]: Those could still come to be, yes, there could be potential bases, if not a formal full-fledged

01:47:42.160 --> 01:47:43.160
[Guest]: base.

01:47:43.160 --> 01:47:50.280
[Guest]: But the same could happen if increasing Chinese vessels are manufactured or sold to Pakistanis.

01:47:50.280 --> 01:47:54.080
[Guest]: You will have maintenance depots and spare parts systems being put up in Pakistan, which

01:47:54.080 --> 01:47:59.320
[Guest]: could therefore be a synthesized Pakistani Navy providing support to Chinese vessels

01:47:59.320 --> 01:48:03.560
[Guest]: in the sea because you've got enough spare parts and you've got enough systems in place

01:48:03.560 --> 01:48:04.840
[Guest]: to service those vessels.

01:48:04.840 --> 01:48:06.620
[Guest]: So you're going to see that increase.

01:48:06.620 --> 01:48:11.480
[Guest]: But the economic aspect through CPEC, where China is presently invested about 20, $22

01:48:11.480 --> 01:48:16.000
[Guest]: billion in Pakistan, and those investment is not directly in terms of actual equity

01:48:16.000 --> 01:48:17.000
[Guest]: investments.

01:48:17.000 --> 01:48:18.000
[Guest]: They are sort of loans.

01:48:18.000 --> 01:48:19.000
[Guest]: There are preferential loans.

01:48:19.000 --> 01:48:24.720
[Guest]: There are really steep loans at very terrible interest rates, terribly opaque investments.

01:48:24.720 --> 01:48:30.520
[Guest]: But that's gone across the board in energy, infrastructure, roadways, railways, agriculture,

01:48:30.520 --> 01:48:32.520
[Guest]: more increasingly, sort of SME sector.

01:48:32.520 --> 01:48:33.880
[Guest]: And they're doing all of that.

01:48:33.880 --> 01:48:37.360
[Guest]: So essentially, you're embracing each other far more tightly.

01:48:37.360 --> 01:48:41.520
[Guest]: That brings with, from an Indian point of view, there are a couple of things that that

01:48:41.520 --> 01:48:42.520
[Guest]: brings.

01:48:42.520 --> 01:48:46.920
[Guest]: One is that the closer you are, the closer you are on a daily basis, the more sort of

01:48:46.920 --> 01:48:49.360
[Guest]: distance, what's that saying?

01:48:49.360 --> 01:48:51.200
[Guest]: That distance generates fondness.

01:48:51.200 --> 01:48:53.520
[Guest]: Proximity will generate friction.

01:48:53.520 --> 01:48:55.440
[Guest]: So the closer you are, there will be friction.

01:48:55.440 --> 01:48:57.160
[Guest]: And we've seen some of this, right?

01:48:57.160 --> 01:49:02.200
[Guest]: Some Chinese workers who are in Pakistan have sort of abused people and there's been violence.

01:49:02.200 --> 01:49:08.320
[Guest]: There's been cases where Chinese people have been accused of human trafficking, where women

01:49:08.320 --> 01:49:12.740
[Guest]: in Pakistan, particularly Christian women in Pakistan, have been married to Chinese

01:49:12.740 --> 01:49:19.280
[Guest]: men and then taken to China and then sold either into prostitution or they've been abused.

01:49:19.280 --> 01:49:23.520
[Guest]: And that's become a problem socially, where there is an investigation that is launched

01:49:23.520 --> 01:49:28.440
[Guest]: by Pakistani police forces, although the Pakistani government and even the legislatures across

01:49:28.440 --> 01:49:33.520
[Guest]: the country sort of say things like, well, this is all external propaganda, while essentially

01:49:33.520 --> 01:49:36.880
[Guest]: police forces in Pakistan have filed these complaints and are investigating hundreds

01:49:36.880 --> 01:49:38.360
[Guest]: of such cases.

01:49:38.360 --> 01:49:41.680
[Guest]: But there is, this sort of gives you a sense that there is social friction that's going

01:49:41.680 --> 01:49:43.120
[Guest]: to increasingly happen.

01:49:43.120 --> 01:49:47.280
[Guest]: The other thing is that if you go back to a couple of years ago, not a couple of years

01:49:47.280 --> 01:49:51.560
[Guest]: ago, but quite a few years ago, when that Lal Masjid siege happened during Musharraf

01:49:51.560 --> 01:49:56.000
[Guest]: reign in Pakistan, the reason for those terrorists to go and take over that Lal Masjid was essentially

01:49:56.000 --> 01:50:02.800
[Guest]: because they were fed up with Chinese presence because of the cultural clash with Chinese

01:50:02.800 --> 01:50:08.240
[Guest]: massage parlours in the cities, violating cultural norms in Pakistan.

01:50:08.240 --> 01:50:12.540
[Guest]: So I think that those sort of frictions are going to increase and that proximity will

01:50:12.540 --> 01:50:15.080
[Guest]: breed some degree of contempt for sure.

01:50:15.080 --> 01:50:19.080
[Guest]: The other broad thing is that because China has far more greatly invested in Pakistan

01:50:19.080 --> 01:50:25.040
[Guest]: and now many more Chinese actors from state firms to private firms are invested, the matrix

01:50:25.040 --> 01:50:28.640
[Guest]: of interest and the actors who are interested changes and that might influence potential

01:50:28.640 --> 01:50:29.920
[Guest]: government policy.

01:50:29.920 --> 01:50:34.840
[Guest]: China would be far more keen to see stability in Pakistan and also stability in the India-Pakistan

01:50:34.840 --> 01:50:39.360
[Guest]: relationship because that will impact its economic gains in Pakistan and its investments

01:50:39.360 --> 01:50:40.800
[Guest]: in Pakistan.

01:50:40.800 --> 01:50:45.680
[Guest]: So increasingly because of this expanded role in Pakistan, you're seeing the Chinese act

01:50:45.680 --> 01:50:47.120
[Guest]: essentially as colonial powers.

01:50:47.120 --> 01:50:51.200
[Guest]: The Chinese ambassador holds meetings with provincial leaders across the country, tries

01:50:51.200 --> 01:50:56.280
[Guest]: to broker solutions and you don't see ambassadors in other countries play such roles.

01:50:56.280 --> 01:50:57.760
[Guest]: But the Chinese ambassador is doing that.

01:50:57.760 --> 01:51:00.320
[Guest]: He's essentially become a governor general in some ways.

01:51:00.320 --> 01:51:04.360
[Guest]: And that will also lead to its own sense of friction within society over the course of

01:51:04.360 --> 01:51:08.960
[Guest]: time because you suddenly see a sense of loss of political authority, loss of sovereignty.

01:51:08.960 --> 01:51:13.400
[Guest]: And as people start to feel that while the economic gains that are promised don't necessarily

01:51:13.400 --> 01:51:18.040
[Guest]: materialise as rapidly as they are promised, that could potentially lead to friction.

01:51:18.040 --> 01:51:21.280
[Guest]: Like I said, from an Indian point of view, what you're seeing is that China is far more

01:51:21.280 --> 01:51:26.000
[Guest]: invested in stability in Pakistan that could result in some degree of cooperation between

01:51:26.000 --> 01:51:30.680
[Guest]: India and China on issues of terrorism, not just in Pakistan, but also because of Chinese

01:51:30.680 --> 01:51:36.200
[Guest]: additional interests across the Middle East and the fulcrum of terror that Pakistan is,

01:51:36.200 --> 01:51:37.720
[Guest]: it links to the Middle East.

01:51:37.720 --> 01:51:40.700
[Guest]: And therefore, you could see greater Indian-Chinese cooperation on terrorism.

01:51:40.700 --> 01:51:44.640
[Guest]: But my hopes are not very high on that, but there is a possibility of doing more in that

01:51:44.640 --> 01:51:45.640
[Guest]: regard.

01:51:45.640 --> 01:51:50.240
[Guest]: The other broad thing is that increasingly China's interest becomes in managing the mistrust

01:51:50.240 --> 01:51:52.840
[Guest]: and the conflict between India and Pakistan.

01:51:52.840 --> 01:51:56.280
[Guest]: So you might potentially see China wanting to play a greater role as a broker between

01:51:56.280 --> 01:51:57.280
[Guest]: India and Pakistan.

01:51:57.280 --> 01:51:59.160
[Guest]: And there are some signs of that.

01:51:59.160 --> 01:52:02.760
[Guest]: In the last couple of months, you've seen the Chinese, despite going to the UN Security

01:52:02.760 --> 01:52:07.760
[Guest]: Council, say things like India and Pakistan are both friendliest partners of China.

01:52:07.760 --> 01:52:11.120
[Guest]: And we wish that you both could leave historical issues and work on development and we will

01:52:11.120 --> 01:52:12.120
[Guest]: help you with that.

01:52:12.120 --> 01:52:14.560
[Guest]: So you want to play the big brother, the balancer.

01:52:14.560 --> 01:52:18.400
[Guest]: But the challenge is, would India ever accept something like that?

01:52:18.400 --> 01:52:22.760
[Guest]: Would India use China as an instrument at certain times to talk to the Pakistanis?

01:52:22.760 --> 01:52:23.760
[Guest]: Perhaps.

01:52:23.760 --> 01:52:27.600
[Guest]: But you see the Chinese as a mediator or as a balancer in the region, highly unlikely

01:52:27.600 --> 01:52:30.520
[Guest]: that India would accept such a proposition.

01:52:30.520 --> 01:52:32.880
[Guest]: So that's how the Chinese role is evolving.

01:52:32.880 --> 01:52:38.640
[Guest]: And Beijing's attempt would predominantly be to ensure that, yes, this conflict can

01:52:38.640 --> 01:52:42.280
[Guest]: sustain, but the mistrust and the problems between the two sides can be managed.

01:52:42.280 --> 01:52:44.600
[Guest]: And it has a role to play in managing that.

01:52:44.600 --> 01:52:48.320
[Amit Varma]: No, and while we may not accept them as a mediator, I think from the Indian point of

01:52:48.320 --> 01:52:54.040
[Amit Varma]: view, it just strikes me as a very good development because one, as you pointed out, China's incentives

01:52:54.040 --> 01:52:55.800
[Amit Varma]: change, they want a stable Pakistan.

01:52:55.800 --> 01:52:59.840
[Amit Varma]: They don't want a Pakistan which is indulging in all the kind of cross-border terrorism

01:52:59.840 --> 01:53:02.120
[Amit Varma]: they do across different borders.

01:53:02.120 --> 01:53:07.680
[Amit Varma]: And from Pakistan's point of view, their incentives to, you know, to hasten their own economic

01:53:07.680 --> 01:53:13.760
[Amit Varma]: development is to sort of toe the China line and get stability.

01:53:13.760 --> 01:53:18.160
[Amit Varma]: So that's that sort of also seems very welcome to me.

01:53:18.160 --> 01:53:22.840
[Amit Varma]: And my next question is about both India and China being nuclear.

01:53:22.840 --> 01:53:27.200
[Amit Varma]: I mean, for example, there is, you know, a popular perception in India that, hey, we

01:53:27.200 --> 01:53:31.040
[Amit Varma]: went nuclear in the late 90s because it was Pakistan we were worried about.

01:53:31.040 --> 01:53:35.560
[Amit Varma]: But you know, Vajpayee himself justified going nuclear by writing a letter to Bill Clinton

01:53:35.560 --> 01:53:41.040
[Amit Varma]: at that time, which later got leaked, where he said that he was responding to China's

01:53:41.040 --> 01:53:42.240
[Amit Varma]: threats.

01:53:42.240 --> 01:53:48.000
[Amit Varma]: And it is those elliptical threats from China, which made him sort of go nuclear.

01:53:48.000 --> 01:53:49.000
[Amit Varma]: What's your take on this?

01:53:49.000 --> 01:53:51.480
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, I think we went nuclear because of China.

01:53:51.480 --> 01:53:55.800
[Guest]: I think we went nuclear because of China, because I don't think our primary concern

01:53:55.800 --> 01:53:56.800
[Guest]: was Pakistan.

01:53:56.800 --> 01:54:01.080
[Guest]: Pakistan plays a role in this in the sense that we see it as I think we went nuclear

01:54:01.080 --> 01:54:02.800
[Guest]: not necessarily just because of China.

01:54:02.800 --> 01:54:06.960
[Guest]: So Pakistan was a factor, China was a bigger factor.

01:54:06.960 --> 01:54:12.200
[Guest]: But the biggest factor was, to my mind, was the sense of aspiration in India of achieving

01:54:12.200 --> 01:54:13.720
[Guest]: a certain kind of power status.

01:54:13.720 --> 01:54:16.440
[Guest]: I think that is what predominantly drove that policy.

01:54:16.440 --> 01:54:20.680
[Guest]: From a security threat perspective, yes, our security threats are Pakistan and China.

01:54:20.680 --> 01:54:24.600
[Guest]: More so increasingly, China was seen as a threat given that India had started to begin

01:54:24.600 --> 01:54:26.840
[Guest]: its sort of growth trajectory.

01:54:26.840 --> 01:54:29.320
[Guest]: And China had also started its sort of growth trajectory.

01:54:29.320 --> 01:54:35.400
[Guest]: But that was a period of time, 1998, where China was actually in a fairly, China was

01:54:35.400 --> 01:54:40.320
[Guest]: sort of very reluctant to be aggressive, because it was looking at the possibility of entering

01:54:40.320 --> 01:54:41.640
[Guest]: the WTO.

01:54:41.640 --> 01:54:47.080
[Guest]: So it didn't like the idea of it being painted as this aggressive entity.

01:54:47.080 --> 01:54:49.440
[Guest]: And there wasn't any immediate sort of threat.

01:54:49.440 --> 01:54:53.480
[Guest]: But it was important for us to go nuclear on multiple fronts.

01:54:53.480 --> 01:54:56.400
[Guest]: After we went nuclear, the Kargil War happened.

01:54:56.400 --> 01:54:59.280
[Guest]: And when the Kargil War happened, you saw the Chinese being very circumspect in how

01:54:59.280 --> 01:55:01.720
[Guest]: they reacted to Pakistan.

01:55:01.720 --> 01:55:05.800
[Guest]: You saw the Americans very clearly telling that Pakistan is what they should be doing,

01:55:05.800 --> 01:55:08.960
[Guest]: and telling Bill Clinton very clearly telling Nawaz Sharif that he needs to step out and

01:55:08.960 --> 01:55:11.680
[Guest]: take responsibility for this and pull back.

01:55:11.680 --> 01:55:16.680
[Guest]: So I think going nuclear, therefore, was important from not just maintaining, changing the dynamics

01:55:16.680 --> 01:55:23.120
[Guest]: of the conflict with Pakistan, but also signaling to the Chinese that, you know, any misadventures

01:55:23.120 --> 01:55:27.560
[Guest]: will be handled, you know, we've got the capacity to handle anything that escalates.

01:55:27.560 --> 01:55:30.440
[Guest]: And you need to think twice before escalating anything.

01:55:30.440 --> 01:55:32.880
[Guest]: And I think the concern has to do a lot to do with the fact that, you know, how would

01:55:32.880 --> 01:55:37.360
[Guest]: Beijing react in a conflict with Pakistan also, I don't think we immediately saw ourselves

01:55:37.360 --> 01:55:41.160
[Guest]: in a conflict with the Chinese because the Chinese were pursuing very different economic

01:55:41.160 --> 01:55:43.720
[Guest]: and very different foreign policy and economic agendas.

01:55:43.720 --> 01:55:48.160
[Guest]: But the threat was via Pakistan, potentially China, and how do you deter China?

01:55:48.160 --> 01:55:50.440
[Guest]: And I think that was predominantly what was going on.

01:55:50.440 --> 01:55:54.920
[Amit Varma]: So I did an episode on the India Pakistan conflict with Srinath Raghavan, where we discussed

01:55:54.920 --> 01:56:00.800
[Amit Varma]: the game theory of it and all of that and and also an episode on India going nuclear

01:56:00.800 --> 01:56:04.040
[Amit Varma]: with your colleague, General Prakash Menon.

01:56:04.040 --> 01:56:09.800
[Amit Varma]: And one of the points both of them made was that before we went nuclear, you know, our

01:56:09.800 --> 01:56:13.480
[Amit Varma]: conventional army was obviously considered to be much better than Pakistan's, but both

01:56:13.480 --> 01:56:16.920
[Amit Varma]: sides going nuclear sort of put them on parity.

01:56:16.920 --> 01:56:20.480
[Amit Varma]: And it also means that when India deals with Pakistan, there is a certain line we cannot

01:56:20.480 --> 01:56:23.280
[Amit Varma]: cross because we don't know how they will react.

01:56:23.280 --> 01:56:28.160
[Amit Varma]: Is that also the case between India and China, except that now we are the weaker side, but

01:56:28.160 --> 01:56:32.400
[Amit Varma]: being nuclear helps it means they can't, you know, push us around too much?

01:56:32.400 --> 01:56:33.400
[Guest]: Exactly.

01:56:33.400 --> 01:56:34.960
[Guest]: Yeah, it makes a difference, right?

01:56:34.960 --> 01:56:40.640
[Guest]: I mean, what's fascinating is that both India and China are subscribed to the no first use

01:56:40.640 --> 01:56:41.640
[Guest]: policy.

01:56:41.640 --> 01:56:46.200
[Guest]: So both sides expressly state that we are committed to not using nuclear weapons first.

01:56:46.200 --> 01:56:51.000
[Guest]: But from a signaling point of view for the Chinese, I mean, look, in 1998, I don't see

01:56:51.000 --> 01:56:55.320
[Guest]: the disparity between India and China in terms of its armed forces being that massive.

01:56:55.320 --> 01:57:00.840
[Guest]: But the potential of that being a big problem going forward, particularly with India facing

01:57:00.840 --> 01:57:05.840
[Guest]: threats on two fronts at any point of time, is where to my mind, this decision comes into

01:57:05.840 --> 01:57:09.240
[Guest]: play from a security threat perspective, that you will signal to the Chinese that there

01:57:09.240 --> 01:57:11.720
[Guest]: will be escalation from our side if this is happening.

01:57:11.720 --> 01:57:14.200
[Guest]: Although you're saying that, you know, we're subscribed to no first use.

01:57:14.200 --> 01:57:20.160
[Guest]: To me, a lot of our reason to actually go nuclear had to do with our desire for power,

01:57:20.160 --> 01:57:24.520
[Guest]: and power in the sense of national power, as that, you know, we wanted to express ourselves

01:57:24.520 --> 01:57:27.400
[Guest]: as an international power with a certain kind of capacity.

01:57:27.400 --> 01:57:32.280
[Guest]: It had security, it has signaling value to our immediate adversaries, but it has a lot

01:57:32.280 --> 01:57:34.280
[Guest]: to do with our own internal sense of power.

01:57:34.280 --> 01:57:39.760
[Guest]: Because if you remember, the narrative and the reaction of the country upon going nuclear,

01:57:39.760 --> 01:57:43.760
[Guest]: it was about us arriving at the world stage.

01:57:43.760 --> 01:57:48.160
[Guest]: And to me, as much as the security sort of aspect of it was important, that was one of

01:57:48.160 --> 01:57:50.760
[Guest]: the underlying motives that we need to be doing this.

01:57:50.760 --> 01:57:51.760
[Amit Varma]: Right.

01:57:51.760 --> 01:57:55.600
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, we've spoken for more than two hours, and we have yet to reach the sort

01:57:55.600 --> 01:57:58.360
[Amit Varma]: of the current situation where we stand today.

01:57:58.360 --> 01:58:03.320
[Amit Varma]: And you obviously written a wonderful paper for Takshashila on this just before the current

01:58:03.320 --> 01:58:07.320
[Amit Varma]: meet happened, the recent meet happened between she and Modi, which I'll link from the show

01:58:07.320 --> 01:58:12.240
[Amit Varma]: notes, but sort of sum up for me briefly that what are the issues now at stake?

01:58:12.240 --> 01:58:14.760
[Amit Varma]: Where does the relationship now stand?

01:58:14.760 --> 01:58:19.160
[Amit Varma]: You know, what did the previous Wuhan meet achieve?

01:58:19.160 --> 01:58:23.160
[Amit Varma]: And what can the two sides realistically achieve going forward?

01:58:23.160 --> 01:58:25.280
[Guest]: So okay, so what did Wuhan achieve?

01:58:25.280 --> 01:58:27.680
[Guest]: Now, Wuhan came at an interesting time, right?

01:58:27.680 --> 01:58:28.680
[Guest]: It was April 2018.

01:58:28.680 --> 01:58:32.880
[Guest]: We'd just gone through a very difficult period in the bilateral relationship.

01:58:32.880 --> 01:58:38.800
[Guest]: And with the Doklam stand of sort of punctuating the difficult period, there were tensions

01:58:38.800 --> 01:58:43.120
[Guest]: between India and China over the listing of Masood Azhar as a terrorist of the United

01:58:43.120 --> 01:58:44.120
[Guest]: Nations.

01:58:44.120 --> 01:58:47.800
[Guest]: There were tensions about India's entry into the nuclear suppliers group, which China had

01:58:47.800 --> 01:58:48.800
[Guest]: been blocking.

01:58:48.800 --> 01:58:53.800
[Guest]: So India got a sense that terrorism, which is a core interest of ours, the Chinese are

01:58:53.800 --> 01:58:59.400
[Guest]: not respecting that, given the overwhelming evidence that exists on aspirational interests,

01:58:59.400 --> 01:59:04.080
[Guest]: which is the nuclear supplier group, the Chinese are not respecting our aspirations.

01:59:04.080 --> 01:59:11.120
[Guest]: And then we have entered into this punctuated conflict in Doklam, in which sort of the fundamentals

01:59:11.120 --> 01:59:15.000
[Guest]: that were keeping us stable, like India's argument was in 2012, we had an agreement

01:59:15.000 --> 01:59:19.320
[Guest]: that in places where there's a tri-junction between India, China and a third country on

01:59:19.320 --> 01:59:23.000
[Guest]: the boundary, you know, status quo would be maintained and Chinese, then the Chinese were

01:59:23.000 --> 01:59:26.560
[Guest]: building that road in Doklam, were violating that status quo.

01:59:26.560 --> 01:59:30.920
[Guest]: And therefore, the Chinese were being far more assertive and not respecting our interests

01:59:30.920 --> 01:59:32.920
[Guest]: and our aspirations at all.

01:59:32.920 --> 01:59:34.760
[Guest]: And therefore, we had to do what we had to do.

01:59:34.760 --> 01:59:38.000
[Guest]: That standoff eventually led to some sort of a de-escalator mechanism where both sides

01:59:38.000 --> 01:59:42.560
[Guest]: start to realize that we need to be talking before this spirals into something bigger.

01:59:42.560 --> 01:59:45.920
[Guest]: And we need to be talking at a leader level because we need to set up some sort of a protocol

01:59:45.920 --> 01:59:49.080
[Guest]: of how do we see our relationship.

01:59:49.080 --> 01:59:52.880
[Guest]: Because things have changed from the last time we had this big conversation, which was

01:59:52.880 --> 01:59:58.160
[Guest]: 1988, when Rajiv Gandhi visited, and we created a template for this relationship saying, we'll

01:59:58.160 --> 02:00:01.720
[Guest]: put the difficult issues aside, we'll try and negotiate confidence building measures

02:00:01.720 --> 02:00:06.520
[Guest]: and we'll try and maintain peace on the boundary while focusing on economic development.

02:00:06.520 --> 02:00:07.520
[Guest]: And things have changed since then.

02:00:07.520 --> 02:00:10.400
[Guest]: And that was a point of time where we were at relative economic parity.

02:00:10.400 --> 02:00:14.320
[Guest]: In fact, India was probably a little bit ahead in terms of its GDP.

02:00:14.320 --> 02:00:16.800
[Guest]: And you know, things have changed since then.

02:00:16.800 --> 02:00:18.400
[Guest]: Today, the scenario is completely different.

02:00:18.400 --> 02:00:20.600
[Guest]: Both of us have broader interests now.

02:00:20.600 --> 02:00:24.240
[Guest]: So in Wuhan, when they met, when Xi Jinping and Modi met, essentially the conversation

02:00:24.240 --> 02:00:26.880
[Guest]: was about how do you set up a new template?

02:00:26.880 --> 02:00:28.760
[Guest]: And what was the new template that they came up with?

02:00:28.760 --> 02:00:32.960
[Guest]: They basically said that, okay, look, we need to advance this relationship by keeping a

02:00:32.960 --> 02:00:36.800
[Guest]: long term perspective in mind and not letting short term issues derail this.

02:00:36.800 --> 02:00:39.760
[Guest]: We need to respect each other's sensitivities and aspirations.

02:00:39.760 --> 02:00:42.700
[Guest]: We need to also pursue deeper and broad based engagement.

02:00:42.700 --> 02:00:47.280
[Guest]: So we need to meet more regularly, not just at a leader level, but we also need to make

02:00:47.280 --> 02:00:49.320
[Guest]: sure that engagement is broad based.

02:00:49.320 --> 02:00:50.320
[Guest]: So people to people.

02:00:50.320 --> 02:00:52.960
[Guest]: And that's absolutely great.

02:00:52.960 --> 02:00:58.200
[Guest]: Because you know, we have about 200,000 Chinese tourists that come to India every year.

02:00:58.200 --> 02:01:01.360
[Guest]: China sends about 130 million tourists to the world.

02:01:01.360 --> 02:01:03.640
[Guest]: And we have 200,000 of them visiting India.

02:01:03.640 --> 02:01:06.040
[Guest]: India should be having far more Chinese tourists coming in.

02:01:06.040 --> 02:01:08.000
[Guest]: There should be far greater educational linkages.

02:01:08.000 --> 02:01:09.800
[Guest]: There should be movies and all that.

02:01:09.800 --> 02:01:14.560
[Guest]: That linkage should happen so that this deep abiding sense of lack of information with

02:01:14.560 --> 02:01:17.560
[Guest]: each other and suspicion, therefore, can start to go away.

02:01:17.560 --> 02:01:21.560
[Guest]: You should have far more scholarly exchanges to understand what the other side is thinking

02:01:21.560 --> 02:01:24.000
[Guest]: or what drives the other side's actions.

02:01:24.000 --> 02:01:27.720
[Guest]: Because that was one of the reasons why we sort of went through this downward spiral in

02:01:27.720 --> 02:01:28.720
[Guest]: the 50s and the 60s.

02:01:28.720 --> 02:01:30.560
[Guest]: So those are good ideas.

02:01:30.560 --> 02:01:35.040
[Guest]: The third big thing was to maintain peace and tranquility along the boundary while trying

02:01:35.040 --> 02:01:39.360
[Guest]: to identify specific confidence building measures to do that.

02:01:39.360 --> 02:01:42.880
[Guest]: And in the course of the year since Wuhan, there were steps taken.

02:01:42.880 --> 02:01:47.640
[Guest]: The boundary patrols became staggered, decided a certain time periods where you would patrol

02:01:47.640 --> 02:01:52.560
[Guest]: certain areas because each side perceives a different area as well as the LAC lies.

02:01:52.560 --> 02:01:55.640
[Guest]: And you would not sort of enter into eyeball confrontation.

02:01:55.640 --> 02:01:57.520
[Guest]: You'd sort of keep distances.

02:01:57.520 --> 02:02:00.240
[Guest]: You'd inform each other a little bit more about what you're doing.

02:02:00.240 --> 02:02:05.240
[Guest]: And that has meant some degree of stability because since Wuhan, there were no major incidents

02:02:05.240 --> 02:02:10.840
[Guest]: at the boundary until September this year when there was a bit of a flash point in Ladakh,

02:02:10.840 --> 02:02:17.000
[Guest]: which also because the protocols that were set in place was addressed within 24 hours.

02:02:17.000 --> 02:02:20.360
[Guest]: In the past, these have gone on for days and days and weeks even.

02:02:20.360 --> 02:02:21.600
[Guest]: So that was what Wuhan was.

02:02:21.600 --> 02:02:25.760
[Guest]: And the broader dictum that sort of underlined all of this was this idea that differences

02:02:25.760 --> 02:02:28.400
[Guest]: must not be allowed to turn into disputes.

02:02:28.400 --> 02:02:32.760
[Guest]: To me, this is an extremely interesting statement because it says that we acknowledge that there

02:02:32.760 --> 02:02:33.760
[Guest]: are differences.

02:02:33.760 --> 02:02:35.240
[Guest]: There's an acknowledgement there.

02:02:35.240 --> 02:02:40.240
[Guest]: And there is a hope that policy will ensure that this does not escalate.

02:02:40.240 --> 02:02:43.480
[Guest]: And therefore, it calls for action for policy to not let this escalate.

02:02:43.480 --> 02:02:47.640
[Guest]: And the action is in this context, by maintaining peace at the border through different protocols,

02:02:47.640 --> 02:02:52.840
[Guest]: by expanding engagement at across levels, and by ensuring that you build the economic

02:02:52.840 --> 02:02:55.400
[Guest]: relationship and talk about some of these prickly issues.

02:02:55.400 --> 02:02:57.200
[Guest]: The prickly issues that persist are the same.

02:02:57.200 --> 02:03:02.600
[Guest]: Are the border, are our aspirations, are each side's aspirations, China's in the Indian

02:03:02.600 --> 02:03:07.080
[Guest]: Ocean and broader geopolitically with regard to India's relationship with the US, India's

02:03:07.080 --> 02:03:11.880
[Guest]: with regard to China's relationship with Pakistan, but not just Pakistan, China's role in the

02:03:11.880 --> 02:03:17.320
[Guest]: broader South Asian region, China's policies of limiting India's rise in the international

02:03:17.320 --> 02:03:22.040
[Guest]: order, whether it is the NSG, whether it is the UN Security Council reform, issues of

02:03:22.040 --> 02:03:26.120
[Guest]: new technologies, how do you mitigate some of the threats, what is a threat that China

02:03:26.120 --> 02:03:32.880
[Guest]: poses in cases of say 5G and Huawei, and how does India mitigate that, yet partner with

02:03:32.880 --> 02:03:36.920
[Guest]: them on science and technology cooperation, because China is increasingly a powerhouse

02:03:36.920 --> 02:03:38.880
[Guest]: when it comes to science and technology.

02:03:38.880 --> 02:03:45.080
[Guest]: So the idea is to be able to find spaces where you can work together while manage the risks

02:03:45.080 --> 02:03:47.140
[Guest]: that you each perceive from each other.

02:03:47.140 --> 02:03:51.720
[Guest]: And that's broadly what this process of informal symmetry is supposed to do.

02:03:51.720 --> 02:03:56.000
[Guest]: That could be in trade, that could be in technology, that could be on security issues.

02:03:56.000 --> 02:04:00.360
[Guest]: The problem that I have with informal symmetry is that it is informal.

02:04:00.360 --> 02:04:06.160
[Guest]: So you don't necessarily formally commit yourself to some targets.

02:04:06.160 --> 02:04:09.520
[Guest]: We've been talking about addressing the trade deficit with China for nearly seven, eight

02:04:09.520 --> 02:04:11.600
[Guest]: years to a decade.

02:04:11.600 --> 02:04:15.600
[Guest]: Very little has been done and very little has been done because there is no target.

02:04:15.600 --> 02:04:19.960
[Guest]: There is no clear policy direction apart from a rhetorical commitment that yes, this is

02:04:19.960 --> 02:04:21.520
[Guest]: something that we need to do.

02:04:21.520 --> 02:04:23.000
[Guest]: We need to achieve more balanced trade.

02:04:23.000 --> 02:04:28.000
[Guest]: There are structural reasons why there is a trade deficit, but there are also very clear

